{"formatVersion":"1","manifest":{"primaryCategory":"Faith & Devotion","subcategory":"Sufism","audienceTags":["tradition:sufism","theme:love","theme:wisdom","audience:meditation"],"sortPriority":27,"groupingLevels":["work"],"groupingLabels":["Work"],"dataPath":"Data/Collections/Rumi_Masnavi.json","supplementalDataPath":null,"languageCode":"en","displayNameEnglish":"Rumi — Masnavi & Divan","script":"Latin","isRTL":false,"transliterationAvailable":false,"contentRating":"devotional","sourceId":"rumiMasnavi","displayName":"Rumi — Masnavi & Divan","version":"2.0","language":"English","edition":"Whinfield, Nicholson Translations","type":"quotes","browseOrder":"sequence","itemCount":1469,"supportsRandom":true,"supportsBrowse":true},"data":[{"id":"rumi-mas-1-1","text":"Listen to this reed how it tells a tale, complaining of separations.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 1 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"1","verse":"1"},"sequenceIndex":0,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-1-2","text":"Ever since I was parted from the reed-bed, men and women have mourned in unison with me.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 1 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"1","verse":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-1-3","text":"I want a bosom torn by severance, that I may describe the pain of love-longing.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 1 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:grief","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"1","verse":"3"},"sequenceIndex":2,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-1-4","text":"Every one who remained far from his origin seeks again the time of his union with it.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 1 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"1","verse":"4"},"sequenceIndex":3,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-1-5","text":"The secret of my lamentation is not far from my plaint, but eye and ear lack that light and shade.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 1 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"1","verse":"5"},"sequenceIndex":4,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-1-6","text":"Body is not veiled from soul, nor soul from body, yet none is permitted to see the soul.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 1 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"1","verse":"6"},"sequenceIndex":5,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-1-7","text":"Rumi said: I searched for myself, but myself I could not see; whatever I saw, that was He.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 1 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"1","verse":"7"},"sequenceIndex":6,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-1-8","text":"Fire is love, and the intellect is only smoke; let the smoke go, and bask in the light of love.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 1 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"1","verse":"8"},"sequenceIndex":7,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-1-9","text":"Love is the elixir, the philosopher's stone that turns the copper of our being to gold.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 1 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"1","verse":"9"},"sequenceIndex":8,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-1-10","text":"The secret of fire is not extinguished by water; the secret of the sun is not obscured by cloud.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 1 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"1","verse":"10"},"sequenceIndex":9,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-1-11","text":"Love is the medicine for every sort of pride and self-conceit.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 1 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"1","verse":"11"},"sequenceIndex":10,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-1-12","text":"I am the slave of that master who does not exult in the mastery of himself.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 1 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"1","verse":"12"},"sequenceIndex":11,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-1-13","text":"The fire of love which is not fed by the body turns the whole universe to ash.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 1 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"1","verse":"13"},"sequenceIndex":12,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-1-14","text":"O friend, seek that treasure that does not leave you — seek that which remains when all else is gone.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 1 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"1","verse":"14"},"sequenceIndex":13,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-1-15","text":"Copper did not know gold until it touched the philosopher's stone. So I knew not that I had worth until love touched me.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 1 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"1","verse":"15"},"sequenceIndex":14,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-2-1","text":"Sell your cleverness and buy bewilderment. Cleverness is mere opinion, bewilderment is intuition.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 2 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"2","verse":"1"},"sequenceIndex":15,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-2-2","text":"Out beyond ideas of wrongdoing and rightdoing, there is a field. I'll meet you there.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 2 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"2","verse":"2"},"sequenceIndex":16,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-2-3","text":"When you let go of who you are, you become who you might be.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 2 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"2","verse":"3"},"sequenceIndex":17,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-2-4","text":"If you are irritated by every rub, how will your mirror be polished?","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 2 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"2","verse":"4"},"sequenceIndex":18,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-2-5","text":"The wound is the place where the Light enters you.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 2 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"2","verse":"5"},"sequenceIndex":19,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-2-6","text":"Don't grieve. Anything you lose comes round in another form.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 2 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"2","verse":"6"},"sequenceIndex":20,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-2-7","text":"The morning wind spreads its fresh smell. We must get up and take that in, that wind that lets us live.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 2 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"2","verse":"7"},"sequenceIndex":21,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-2-8","text":"The way you make love is the way God will be with you.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 2 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"2","verse":"8"},"sequenceIndex":22,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-2-9","text":"There is a community of the spirit. Join it, and feel the delight of walking in the noisy street, and being the noise.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 2 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:relationships","tradition:animism","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"2","verse":"9"},"sequenceIndex":23,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-2-10","text":"Let yourself be silently drawn by the strange pull of what you really love. It will not lead you astray.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 2 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"2","verse":"10"},"sequenceIndex":24,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-2-11","text":"Everything in the universe is within you. Ask all from yourself.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 2 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","theme:solitude","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"2","verse":"11"},"sequenceIndex":25,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-2-12","text":"Yesterday I was clever, so I wanted to change the world. Today I am wise, so I am changing myself.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 2 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"2","verse":"12"},"sequenceIndex":26,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-2-13","text":"Be melting snow. Wash yourself of yourself.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 2 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"2","verse":"13"},"sequenceIndex":27,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-2-14","text":"The lamps are different, but the Light is the same.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 2 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"2","verse":"14"},"sequenceIndex":28,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-2-15","text":"Wherever you are, and whatever you do, be in love.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 2 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"2","verse":"15"},"sequenceIndex":29,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-3-1","text":"It's your road, and yours alone. Others may walk it with you, but no one can walk it for you.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 3 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:solitude","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"3","verse":"1"},"sequenceIndex":30,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-3-2","text":"The light which shines in the eye is really the light of the heart.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 3 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"3","verse":"2"},"sequenceIndex":31,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-3-3","text":"Be empty of worrying. Think of who created thought!","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 3 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"3","verse":"3"},"sequenceIndex":32,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-3-4","text":"I have lived on the lip of insanity, wanting to know reasons, knocking on a door. It opens. I've been knocking from the inside.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 3 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"3","verse":"4"},"sequenceIndex":33,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-3-5","text":"Respond to every call that excites your spirit.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 3 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:animism","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"3","verse":"5"},"sequenceIndex":34,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-3-6","text":"Very little grows on jagged rock. Be ground. Be crumbled, so wildflowers will come up where you are.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 3 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"3","verse":"6"},"sequenceIndex":35,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-3-7","text":"What hurts you, blesses you. Darkness is your candle.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 3 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"3","verse":"7"},"sequenceIndex":36,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-3-8","text":"Start a huge, foolish project, like Noah. It makes absolutely no difference what people think of you.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 3 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"3","verse":"8"},"sequenceIndex":37,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-3-9","text":"Love comes with a knife, not some shy question, and not with fears for its reputation!","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 3 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"3","verse":"9"},"sequenceIndex":38,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-3-10","text":"The guest is God. Be awake at every moment, for that guest may come at any instant.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 3 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"3","verse":"10"},"sequenceIndex":39,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-3-11","text":"Every moment I shape my destiny with a chisel — I am the carpenter of my own soul.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 3 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"3","verse":"11"},"sequenceIndex":40,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-3-12","text":"A thousand half-loves must be forsaken to take one whole heart home.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 3 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"3","verse":"12"},"sequenceIndex":41,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-3-13","text":"Oh soul, you worry too much. You have seen your own strength. You have seen your own beauty.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 3 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:beauty","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:resilience","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:confucianism","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"3","verse":"13"},"sequenceIndex":42,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-3-14","text":"The Beloved is everywhere. The man of God is drunk without wine.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 3 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"3","verse":"14"},"sequenceIndex":43,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-3-15","text":"All day I think about it, then at night I say it. Where did I come from, and what am I supposed to be doing?","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 3 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"3","verse":"15"},"sequenceIndex":44,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-4-1","text":"Your task is not to seek for love, but merely to seek and find all the barriers within yourself that you have built against it.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 4 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","theme:solitude","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"4","verse":"1"},"sequenceIndex":45,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-4-2","text":"Reason is the shadow cast by God. God is the sun.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 4 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"4","verse":"2"},"sequenceIndex":46,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-4-3","text":"The quieter you become, the more you are able to hear.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 4 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"4","verse":"3"},"sequenceIndex":47,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-4-4","text":"When you find yourself in the company of poor people, you are in God's presence.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 4 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"4","verse":"4"},"sequenceIndex":48,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-4-5","text":"Every prophet, every saint has his path, but as they return to God, all are one.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 4 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"4","verse":"5"},"sequenceIndex":49,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-4-6","text":"Work. Keep digging your well. Don't think about getting off from work. Water is there somewhere.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 4 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"4","verse":"6"},"sequenceIndex":50,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-4-7","text":"Travel brings power and love back into your life.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 4 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"4","verse":"7"},"sequenceIndex":51,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-4-8","text":"When the water of a river stops flowing, it becomes a rotting pool. Keep going — keep flowing.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 4 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"4","verse":"8"},"sequenceIndex":52,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-4-9","text":"A thousand prayers, a thousand ecstatic prostrations — or just one look of love from God.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 4 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"4","verse":"9"},"sequenceIndex":53,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-4-10","text":"Do you know what you are? You are a manuscript of a divine letter. You are a mirror reflecting a noble face.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 4 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"4","verse":"10"},"sequenceIndex":54,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-5-1","text":"Die! Die! Die in this love! If you die in this love, your soul will be renewed.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 5 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:confucianism","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"5","verse":"1"},"sequenceIndex":55,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-5-2","text":"Live where you fear to live. Destroy your reputation. Be notorious.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 5 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"5","verse":"2"},"sequenceIndex":56,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-5-3","text":"That which is false troubles the heart, but the truth brings joyous tranquility.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 5 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:truth","theme:wisdom","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"5","verse":"3"},"sequenceIndex":57,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-5-4","text":"Do not be satisfied with the stories that come before you. Unfold your own myth.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 5 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"5","verse":"4"},"sequenceIndex":58,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-5-5","text":"There are as many ways to God as there are souls on Earth.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 5 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:animism","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"5","verse":"5"},"sequenceIndex":59,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-5-6","text":"The breeze at dawn has secrets to tell you. Don't go back to sleep.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 5 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"5","verse":"6"},"sequenceIndex":60,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-5-7","text":"Silence is the language of God. All else is poor translation.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 5 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:solitude","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"5","verse":"7"},"sequenceIndex":61,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-5-8","text":"Remember, the entrance door to the sanctuary is inside you.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 5 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"5","verse":"8"},"sequenceIndex":62,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-5-9","text":"You are not a drop in the ocean. You are the entire ocean, in a drop.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 5 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"5","verse":"9"},"sequenceIndex":63,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-5-10","text":"Speak in the tongue of love, and you will find your path to God.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 5 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"5","verse":"10"},"sequenceIndex":64,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-6-1","text":"I looked in temples, churches, and mosques. But I found the Divine within my heart.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 6 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:solitude","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"6","verse":"1"},"sequenceIndex":65,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-6-2","text":"My soul is from elsewhere, I'm sure of that, and I intend to end up there.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 6 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"6","verse":"2"},"sequenceIndex":66,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-6-3","text":"Close your eyes, fall in Love, stay there.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 6 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"6","verse":"3"},"sequenceIndex":67,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-6-4","text":"You have forgotten the One who doesn't care about ownership, who doesn't try to turn a profit from every human exchange.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 6 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"6","verse":"4"},"sequenceIndex":68,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-mas-6-5","text":"The desire to know your own soul will end all other desires.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi, Book 6 (Whinfield/public domain trans.)","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"groups":{"book":"6","verse":"5"},"sequenceIndex":69,"isVerified":true},{"id":"rumi-ext-000071","text":"He whose intellect overcomes his desire is higher than the angels; he whose desire overcomes his intellect is less than an animal.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:resilience","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000072","text":"The fault is in the one who blames. Spirit sees nothing to criticize.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000073","text":"This discipline and rough treatment are a furnace to extract the silver from the dross. This testing purifies the gold by boiling the scum away.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000074","text":"Fortunate is he who does not carry envy as a companion.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000075","text":"The idol of your self is the mother of all idols. To regard the self as easy to subdue is a mistake.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000076","text":"If you wish mercy, show mercy to the weak.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000077","text":"If you dig a pit for others to fall into, you will fall into it yourself.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000078","text":"Many of the faults you see in others, dear reader, are your own nature reflected in them.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000079","text":"The lion who breaks the enemy's ranks is a minor hero compared to the lion who overcomes himself.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:resilience","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000080","text":"Whoever gives reverence receives reverence.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000081","text":"Were there no men of vision, all who are blind would be dead.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:leadership","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000082","text":"If you are wholly perplexed and in straits, have patience, for patience is the key to joy.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000083","text":"Anyone in whom the troublemaking self has died, sun and cloud obey. As his heart is afire with knowledge and love, the sun cannot burn him.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000084","text":"If you wish to shine like day, burn up the night of self-existence. Dissolve in the Being who is everything.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000085","text":"There is no worse sickness for the soul, O you who are proud, than this pretense of perfection. The heart and eyes must bleed a lot before self-complacency falls away.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000086","text":"God turns you from one feeling to another and teaches by means of opposites, so that you will have two wings to fly, not one.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000087","text":"When the remedy you have offered only increases the disease, then leave him who will not be cured, and tell your story to someone who seeks the truth.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:truth","theme:wisdom","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000088","text":"Whoever enters the Way without a guide will take a hundred years to travel a two-day journey.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:leadership","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000089","text":"Whoever undertakes a profession without a master becomes the laughingstock of city and town.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000090","text":"Even though you're not equipped,keep searching:equipment isn't necessary on the way to the Lord.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000091","text":"If an ant seeks the rank of Solomon,don't smile contemptuously upon its quest.Everything you possess of skill, and wealth and handicraft,wasn't it first merely a thought and a quest?","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000092","text":"Come, seek, for search is the foundation of fortune:Every success depends upon focusing the heart.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000093","text":"That which God said to the rose,and caused it to laugh in full-blown beauty,He said to my heart,and made it a hundred times more beautiful.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000094","text":"Many have been led astray by the Qur'an:by clinging to that rope many have fallen into the well.There is no fault in the rope, O perverse man,for it was you who had no desire to reach the top.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000095","text":"The eye of outward sense is as the palm of a hand, The whole of the object is not grasped in the palm. The sea itself is one thing, the foam another; Neglect the foam, and regard the sea with your eyes.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000096","text":"When you see anyone complainingof such and such a person's ill-nature and bad temper,know that the complainant is bad-tempered,forasmuch as he speaks ill of that bad-tempered person,because he alone is good-tempered who is quietly forbearingtowards the bad-tempered and ill-natured.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:solitude","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000097","text":"Everyone sees the unseen in proportion to the clarity of his heart, and that depends upon how much he has polished it. Whoever has polished it more sees more — more unseen forms become manifest to him.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000098","text":"Love is the ark appointed for the righteous,Which annuls the danger and provides a way of escape.Sell your cleverness and buy bewilderment.Cleverness is mere opinion, bewilderment intuition.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000099","text":"Reason is like an officer when the King appears;The officer then loses his power and hides himself.Reason is the shadow cast by God; God is the sun.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000100","text":"How can these works and this earning in the way of righteousness be accomplished without a master, O father? Can you practice the meanest profession in the world without a master's guidance?","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000101","text":"Are you fleeing from Love because of a single humiliation?What do you know of Love except the name?Love has a hundred forms of pride and disdain,and is gained by a hundred means of persuasion.Since Love is loyal, it purchases one who is loyal:it has no interest in a disloyal companion.The human being resembles a tree; its root is a covenant with God:that root must be cherished with all one's might.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000102","text":"If in thirst you drink water from a cup, you see God in it. Those who are not in love with God will see only their own faces in it.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000103","text":"The lower self does not want anyone to receive anything from anybody else, and if it is aware of something receiving a special boon, it seeks to destroy it.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000104","text":"Whatever possessions and objects of its desires the lower self may obtain, it hangs on to them, refusing to let them go out of greed for more, or out of fear of poverty and need.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000105","text":"I died as a mineral and became a plant,I died as plant and rose to animal,I died as animal and I was Man.Why should I fear? When was I less by dying?Yet once more I shall die as Man, to soarWith angels blest; but even from angelhoodI must pass on: all except God doth perish.When I have sacrificed my angel-soul,I shall become what no mind e'er conceived.Oh, let me not exist! for Non-existenceProclaims in organ tones, 'To Him we shall return.'","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000106","text":"The branch might seem like the fruit's origin:In fact, the branch exists because of the fruit.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000107","text":"\"There's no courage\", The Prophet said, \"before the war has begun.\"Drunkards vaunt their bravery when you speak of war.But in the blaze of battle they scatter like mice.I'm astonished by the man who wants purityAnd yet trembles when the harshness of polishing begin...When a man beats a carpet again and againIt's not the carpet he's attacking, but the dirt in it.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:courage","theme:love","theme:resilience","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000108","text":"Love is the path and road of our ProphetWe were born from Love and Love was our mother.O you who are our mother, you are hidden within veils,Concealed from our disbelieving natures","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:solitude","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000109","text":"The fire of Love cooks meEvery night it drags me to the Tavern.It seats me with the People of the TavernSo that no one except the People of the Tavern will know me.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000110","text":"By eating meagerly, you become clever and aware.And by eating gluttonously, you become foolish and idle.Your being full of misery is entirely from your gluttony.You will become less miserable if you become a sparse eater.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000111","text":"If you dwell with unaware people, you will be cold,But if you dwell with aware ones, you will be a true manGo, and build your hermit cell inside a furnace, like goldIf you go out of the furnace, you will be frozen solid","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000112","text":"Dwell in the place where your companions are spiritual heroes,So that they may wash the foul soot from your [heart]Don't think about their faults, for theyWill know about it before you think.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000113","text":"I am so happy, I cannot be contained in the world;But like a spirit, I am hidden from the eyes of the world.If the foot of the trees were not tied to earth, they would be pursuing me;For I have blossomed so much, I am the envy of the gardens.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:grief","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000114","text":"Study me as much as you like, you will not know me, &nbsp;&nbsp; for I differ in a hundred ways from what you see me to be. Put yourself behind my eyes and see me as I see myself, &nbsp;&nbsp; for I have chosen to dwell in a place you cannot see.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000115","text":"We have a way from this visible world to the Unseen, for we are the companions of religion's messenger.We have a way from the house to the garden, we are the neighbor of the cypress and jasmine.Every day we come to the garden and see a hundred blossoms.In order to scatter them among the lovers, we will our robes to overflowing...Behold our words! They are the fragrance of those roses--we are the rosebush of certainty's rosegarden.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:grief","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000116","text":"Our caravan leader is the pride of the world, Mustafa [Muhammad].","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:leadership","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000117","text":"Everyone has been made for some particular work, and the desire for that work has been put in every heart.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000118","text":"The men of God are like fishes in the ocean; they pop up into view on the surface here and there and everywhere, as they please.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000119","text":"Let the beauty of what you love be what you do.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:beauty","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000120","text":"I want a heart which is split, part by part, because of the pain of separation from God, so that I might explain my longing and complaint to it.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:grief","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000121","text":"The Sufi is hanging on to Muhammad, like Abu Bakr.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000122","text":"I am the servant of the Qur'an as long as I have life.I am the dust on the path of [Muhammad], the Chosen one.If anyone quotes anything except this from my sayings,I am quit of him and outraged by these words","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:leadership","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000123","text":"You were born with wings. Why prefer to crawl through life?","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000124","text":"Wherever you stand, be the soul of that place.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000125","text":"Seek truth from thought, not in mouldy books. Look in the sky to find the moon, not in the pool.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:truth","theme:wisdom","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000126","text":"Ah, me! so poor, can I declare that friend, who never had another friend his like,—none, therefore, who could know his soul?","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000127","text":"Supreme Being soars above thought and imagination. We are lost when we would comprehend or even suspect that which he is. How vain, then, to seek words worthy of that Being! Let it suffice us to adore in reverent silence!","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:solitude","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000128","text":"Thou, nearer to me than I to myself.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000129","text":"O heart! weak follower of the weak,&nbsp;&nbsp;That thou shouldst traverse land and sea, In this far place that God to seek&nbsp;&nbsp;Who long ago had come to thee!","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000130","text":"The prophets hear in their mind voices that others never perceive, as the voices of the Peris, which, although they sound out clearly, are never apprehended by our ears.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000131","text":"This universe is a drop from the ocean of his beauty, unable from its fulness to find place in the parent bosom.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000132","text":"When rises the sun and chases the night,What need have we then of the lamp for a light?When the friend all beloved appears to the eye,What want dost thou feel that the post bring him nigh?But when the rose-time is past, and the rose-bloom gone by,Then gladly the eye seeks the water of roses to spy.Is the Master within to thy soul not revealed?Well then may’st thou turn to the Volume of message unsealed.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","theme:solitude","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000133","text":"As water from the glasses is all poured into one vessel, so all the praises are mingled together. Since He that is celebrated is wholly one, all religions form but one religion.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000134","text":"The compass only serves to direct the prayers of those who are outside of the Caaba, whilst within it no one knows the use of it.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:solitude","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000135","text":"If this world were our abiding place, we might complain that it makes our bed so hard: But it is only our night-quarters on a journey; and who can expect home comforts?","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000136","text":"As the stranger, far distant in foreign climes, draws towards home, so the soul, from midst of this world of multiplicity, pants and soars upward to the Unity.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000137","text":"Rabia, sick upon her bed,By two saints was visited,Holy Malik, Hassan wise,—Men of mark in Moslem eyes.Hassan says, \"Whose prayer is pureWill God's chastisements endure.\"Malik, from a deeper sense,Uttered his experience:\"He who hears his Master's voiceWill in chastisement rejoice.\"Rabia saw some selfish willIn their maxims lingering still,And replied, \"O men of grace!He who sees his Master's face,Will not in his prayer recallThat he is chastised at all.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:resilience","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000138","text":"Love is the water of life; receive it in thy heart and soul.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000139","text":"None but the sun can display the sun.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000140","text":"Pants thy spirit to be giftedWith a deathless life,Let it seek to be upliftedO’er earth’s storm and strife.Spurn its joys,—its ties dissever,Hopes and fears divest;Thus, aspire to live for ever,Be for ever blest.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:mortality","theme:nature","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000141","text":"'Tis marvellous by what way thou wentest from the worldThou didst strongly shake thy wings and feathers and having broken thy cageDidst ae to the air and journey towards the world of soul.Thou wert a favourite falcon kept in captivity by an old womanWhen thou heard’st the falcon-drum, thou didst fly away into the void.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000142","text":"After all soul is linked to bodyThough it in nowise resembles the bodyThe power of the light of the eye is mated with fatThe light of the heart is hidden in a drop of bloodJoy harbours in the kidneys and pain in the liverThe lamp of reason in the brains of the head.These connections are not without a why and howBut reason is at a loss to understand the how.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:grief","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000143","text":"For this cause, O son, the Prince of men declared'The majority of those in Paradise are the foolish'.Cleverness is as a wind raising storms of prideBe foolish, so that your heart may he at peace.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000144","text":"This world of illusions, fancies, desires and fearsIs a mighty obstacle in the traveller's path.Thus when these forms of delusive imaginationsMisled Abraham, who was a very mountain of wisdom.He said of the star 'This is my Lord'.Having fallen into the midst of the world of illusionSeeing then that this world of eye-fascinating illusionSeduced from the right path such a mountain as Abraham.So that he said of the star 'This is my Lord',What will not its illusions effect on a stupid ass?","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000145","text":"First he appeared in the class of inorganic things,Next he passed therefrom into that of plants,For years he lived as one of the plants,Remembering naught of his inorganic state so different,And when he passed from the vegetive to the animal stateHe had no remembrance of his state as a plant.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000146","text":"The prophets chose the better part, futurity.The foolish chose the worst, the world's fatuity.Each bird will flock with birds of its own feather stillThe cock well knows his mate and follows where she will.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000147","text":"The lover is a monarch; two worlds lie at his feet;The king pays no heed to what lies at his feet;'Tis love and the lover that live to all eternitySet not thy heart on aught else; 'tis only borrowed.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000148","text":"The root of hatred is hell and that hate of yoursIs a part of that whole and is the foe of your religionSince you are a part of hell, beware!For the part ever tends towards its wholeBut if you are a portion of heaven, O renowned one,Your joy will be as lasting as heaven itself.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000149","text":"Let us seek refuge with Allah from Satan;Alas! we are perishing from his insolence.The dog is one yet he enters a thousand forms;Whatever he enters, straight becomes himself;Whatever makes you shiver, know he is in it,The Devil is hidden beneath its outward form.When he finds no form at hand, he enters your thoughtsTo cause them to draw you into sin.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000150","text":"For love of our Almighty God, the Lord of all,Who would not die; a stock, a block, we needs must call.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000151","text":"Imitate the water-wheel that groans and weeps;By prayers and groans and tears a man his heart pure keeps;Wouldst thou shed tears? Feel pity when thou meetest woe,Wouldst mercy find? Show mercy, when men bow them low.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000152","text":"Our celestial spirit is free to eternity,Although for a short time we are imprisoned in forms of flesh.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000153","text":"With thee hell would he a mansion of delightWith thee a prison would be a rose garden.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000154","text":"With thee how should we be afraid of lossO thou, who turnest every loss to gain.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:grief","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000155","text":"Why, when God’s earth is so wide, have you fallen asleep in prison?","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000156","text":"The majority of those in Paradise are the simpleWho have escaped the snares of philosophy.Strip yourself bare of overweening intellectThat grace may ever be shed upon you from above.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000157","text":"Whereas want of fidelity is shameful even in dogs,How can it be right in men?God Almighty himself makes boast of fidelitySaying 'Who is more faithful to his promise than we?'","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000158","text":"Open your arms if you desire an embrace,Break the idol of clay that you may behold the face of the fair.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:justice","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000159","text":"Earth receives the seed and guards it,&nbsp;&nbsp;Trustfully it dies:Then what teeming life rewards it,&nbsp;&nbsp;For self-sacrifice.With green leaf and clustering blossom&nbsp;&nbsp;Clad, or golden fruit,See it from earth’s cheerless bosom &nbsp;&nbsp;Ever sunward shoot.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:grief","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:relationships","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000160","text":"Hearken to the reed-flute, how it discoursesWhen complaining of the pains of separation;'Ever since they tore me from my osier-bed,My plaintive notes have moved men and women to tears.I burst my breast striving to give vent to sighs,And to express the pangs of yearning for my home;He who abides far away from his home,Is ever longing for the day he shall return.'","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:grief","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000161","text":"Come, come for you will not find another friend like Me,Where indeed is a Beloved like Me in all the world?Come, come, and do not spend your life in wandering to and fro,Since there is no market elsewhere for your money.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000162","text":"Come, and think of Me, Who gave you the faculty of thought,Since from my mine you may purchase an ass-load of rubies;Come, advance towards Him Who gave you a foot,Look with all your eyes upon Him Who gave you an eye.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000163","text":"That spiritual garden accompanies them everywhereYet it is never revealed to the eyes of the people,Its fruits ever asking to be gathered,Its fount of life welling up to be drunk.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000164","text":"We used to be on the earth, ignorant of the earth,Ignorant of the treasure buried within it.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:solitude","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000165","text":"Thou wert a love-lorn nightingale among owls,The scent of the rose-garden reached thee, and thou didst go to the rose-garden.Thou didst suffer sore headache from this bitter ferment,At last thou wentest to the tavern of eternity.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000166","text":"'Tis slave-caressing thy love has practised,Else, where is the heart worthy of that love?Every heart that has slept one night in thine airIs like radiant day; thereby the air is illuminated.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000167","text":"How many letters thou writest with Thy Almighty penThrough marvelling thereat stones become as wax;These letters exercise and perplex reason,Write on, O skilful Fair-writer,Imprinting every moment on Not-being the fair formsOf the world of ideals to confound all thought.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:justice","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000168","text":"Mine eye is from that source, and from another universeHere a world and there a world: I am seated on the threshold;On the threshold are they alone, whose eloquence is mute,'Tis enough to utter this intimation: say no more, draw back thy tongue.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:solitude","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000169","text":"What pearl art thou that none possesseth the price of thee?What does the world possess that is not thy gift?","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000170","text":"Why does not the soul take wing when from the glorious presenceA speech of sweet favour comes to it saying, 'Aloft!'","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000171","text":"Why should a falcon not fly from the quarry towards the KingWhen it hears by drum and drum-stick the notice of 'Return?'Why should not every Sufi begin to dance like a mote,In the sun of eternity that it may deliver him from decay.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000172","text":"When the sun goeth up, where stayeth night?When the joy of bounty came, where lagged affliction?","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000173","text":"Weave no more with soot, like the spider, a web of care,Wherein both woof and warp are rotten.While thou art silent, His speech is thy speech,While thou weavest not, God is the weaver.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000174","text":"When thou seest in the pathway a severed head,Which is rolling toward our field,Ask of it, ask of it the secrets of the heart,For of it thou wilt learn our hidden mystery.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000175","text":"How long shall we, like children in the earthly sphereFill our lap with dust and stones and sherds?Let us give up the earth and fly heavenwards,Let us flee from childhood to the banquet of men.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:animism","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000176","text":"Were there no hostility, war would be impossible,Hadst thou no lust, obedience to the law could not beHadst thou no concupiscence there could be no abstinenceWhere no antagonist exists, what need is there of armies?","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000177","text":"Such grace and beauty and loveliness and bestowal of life,O misery and error, if anyone dispense with Him!Fly, fly O bird, to thy native home,For thou hast escaped from the cage, and thy pinions are outspread.Travel away from the bitter stream towards the water of life,Return from the vestibule to the high seat of the soul.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000178","text":"Whereas the springhead is undying, its branch gives water continually;Since neither can cease, why are you lamenting?Conceive the Soul as a fountain and these created things as rivers;While the fountain flows, the rivers run from itPut grief out of your head, and keep quaffing this river water,Do not think of the water failing; for this water is without end.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:grief","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000179","text":"When you have seen the millstone turning round,Then, prithee, go and see the stream that turns it.When you have seen the dust rising up into the air,Go and mark the air in the midst of the dust.You see the kettles of thought boiling over,Look with intelligence at the fire beneath them.God said to Job \"Out of my clemencyI have given a grain of patience to every hair of thine\"Look not then, so much at your own patience,After seeing patience, look to the giver of patience.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000180","text":"Our wakefulness fetters our spirits,Then our souls are a prey to various whims,Thoughts of loss and gain and fears of misery.They retain not purity nor dignity nor lustre,Nor aspiration to soar heavenwards.That one is really sleeping who hankers after each whimAnd holds parley with each fancy.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:grief-healing","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:grief","theme:justice","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000181","text":"As there are many demons with men’s faces,It is wrong to join hands with every one.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000182","text":"Since the latter of your states were better than the former,Seek annihilation and adore change of state;You have already seen hundreds of resurrectionsOccur every moment from your origin till now;One from the inorganic state to the vegetive state,From the vegetive state to the animal state of trial;Thence again to rationality and good discernment,Again you will rise from this world of sense and form.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","theme:wisdom","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000183","text":"Since you are properly a clod you will not rise into the air;You will rise into the air if you break and become dust,If you break not, He who moulded you will break you.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000184","text":"Having chosen thy Director, be not weak of heartNor yet sluggish and lax like water and mud;But if thou takest umbrage at every rubHow wilt thou become a polished mirror?","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000185","text":"When God decides to humble any sinner proudA demon stirs this last to insult some man of GodAnd he whom God elects to cloak where 'tis he haltsHas grace bestowed on him to cover others' faults.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:solitude","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000186","text":"Since all things are dependent on probability,Religion is so first of all, for thereby you find release.In this world no knocking at the door is possibleSave hope, and God knows what is best.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000187","text":"When the preacher himself has no light or life,How can his words yield leaves and fruit?He impudently preaches to others to walk aright,While himself he is unsteady as a reed shaken by wind.Thus though his preaching is very eloquent,It hides within it unsteadiness in the faith.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","theme:solitude","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000188","text":"When thou endurest not the pains of abstinence,And fulfillest not the terms, thou gainest no reward;How easy those terms! how abundant that reward!A reward that enchants the heart and charms the soul.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:grief","theme:love","theme:resilience","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000189","text":"Should envy fill thy breast ’gainst one that envies notFoul stains ensue; thy heart’s impure; all good’s forgotProstrate thyself then at the feet of holy men,Cast dust upon thy head, God’s pardon to obtain.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000190","text":"When the discourse touched on the matter of love,Pen was broken and paper torn;None but the sun can display the sun.If you would see it displayed, turn not away from it.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000191","text":"Traditional knowledge when inspiration is availableIs like making ablutions with sand when water is nearMake yourself ignorant, be submissive, and thenYou will obtain release from your ignorance.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000192","text":"When, O spiritual one, thou hast become thy own fortuneThen, being thyself thy fortune, thou wilt never lose itHow, O fortunate one, cans't thou ever lose thyselfWhen thy real self is thy treasure and thy kingdom.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000193","text":"When the drop departed from its native home and returnedIt found a shell and became a pearl.Did not Joseph go on a journey from his father weeping?Did he not in the journey come to fortune and kingdom and victory?","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000194","text":"As the arrow speeds from the bow, like the bird of your imaginationKnow that the Absolute will certainly flee from the imaginary;His name will flee when it sees an attempt at speech;He will flee from you so that if you limn his pictureThe picture will fly from the tablet, the impression will flee from the soul.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000195","text":"Thou wilt never more endure without the flame, when thou hast known the rapture of burning.If the water of life should come to thee, it would not stir thee from the flame.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:resilience","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000196","text":"O brave friend, grasp His skirt,Who is removed alike from the world above and below;Who will abide with thee in the house and abroadWhen thou lackest house and homeHe will bring forth peace out of perturbationsAnd when thou art afflicted, will keep His promise.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:courage","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000197","text":"The seed of the spirit sown beneath this water and clay (the body)Becomes not a tree until it reach Thy spring.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000198","text":"Pass over names and look to qualitiesSo that qualities may lead thee to essence;The differences of sects arise from His namesWhen they pierce to His essence, they find His peace.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000199","text":"There is a tradition ‘The heart is like a featherIn the desert, which is borne captive by the winds;The wind drives it everywhere at random,Now to right and now to left in opposite directions.’","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000200","text":"David said ‘O Lord, since Thou hast no need of us,Say then, what wisdom was there in creating the two worlds?’God said to him ‘O temporal man, I was a hidden treasure;I sought that that treasure of loving kindness and bounty should be revealed.’","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000201","text":"One must have king-recognising eyesTo recognise the king in each disguise.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000202","text":"Let others grow pale from fear of misfortune,Do thou smile like the rose at loss and gain.For the rose, though its petals be torn asunderStill smiles on, and it is never cast down.It says ‘Why should I fall into grief in disgrace?I gather beauty even from the thorn of disgrace.’What is Sufism? ’Tis to find joy in the heartWhensoever distress and care assail it.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:beauty","theme:creativity","theme:grief","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000203","text":"O heart, why art thou a captive in the earth that is passing away?Fly forth from this enclosure, since thou art a bird of the spiritual world;Thou art a darling bosom-friend, thou art always behind the secret veil;Why dost thou make thy dwelling-place in this perishable abode?","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000204","text":"The spirit ever leads to haunts of holy men,The flesh would cast thee in the pit of sin again.Beware! Feed thou thy soul with love from holy ground;Make haste! seek means of grace from one who grace hath found.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000205","text":"Yesterday the Master with a lantern was roaming about the city,Crying ‘I am tired of devil and beast, I desire a man.’","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000206","text":"It behoves not, son, to beat a drum under a quilt,Plant like brave men, thy banner in the midst of the desert.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:courage","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000207","text":"&nbsp;&nbsp; This world which is only a dreamSeems to the sleeper as a thing enduring for everBut when the morn of the last day shall dawn,The sleeper will escape from the cloud of illusion.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000208","text":"Makers of base coin hate the daylightCoins of pure gold love the daylight,Because daylight is the mirror that reflects themSo that they see their own perfect beauty.God has named the resurrection ‘that day,’Day shows off the beauty of red and yellow.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000209","text":"O lovers, O lovers, it is time to abandon the world,The drum of departure reaches my spiritual ear from heavenBehold, the driver has risen and made ready the files of camelsAnd begged us to acquit him of blame; why, O travellers are you asleep?These sounds before and behind are the din of departure and of the camel-bells;With each moment a soul and a spirit is setting off into the void.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","theme:nature","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000210","text":"O the many pure heads scattered beneath the clay,That thou mayest know the head depends on that other head;That original head hidden, and this derived head manifest,Forasmuch as behind this world lies the infinite universe.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000211","text":"O Brother, you are essentially thought,All the rest of you is bone and sinew,If your thoughts are rose-like, you are a rose-gardenIf they are thorn-like, you are fuel for the furnace.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000212","text":"Ah! many are the conditions which at first are hard,But are afterwards relieved and lose their harshnessOftentimes hope succeeds to hopelessnessMany times does sunlight succeed to darkness.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000213","text":"Thou who dost blame injustice in mankind'Tis but the image of thine own dark mind;In them reflected all thy nature isWith all its angles and obliquities;Around thyself thyself the noose hast thrownAnd dost a self-inflicted wound bemoan;‘Back to each other we reflections throw’So spoke the holy Prophet long ago:And he who gazes through a glass that’s dimWhat wonder if the world look dark to him?","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:beauty","theme:justice","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000214","text":"O indestructible Love! O divine minstrelThou art both stay and refuge; a name equal to thee I have not found.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000215","text":"Whence did this breath come to thee, O my soul;Whence this throbbing, O my heart?O bird, speak the language of birdsI can understand thy hidden meaning.The soul answered ‘I was in the divine factoryWhile the house of water-and-clay was a-bakingI was flying away from the material workshopWhile the workshop was being createdWhen I could resist no more, they dragged meTo mould me into shape like a ball.’","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000216","text":"How blessed are the eyes that smart with sorrow’s brine,How blessed is the heart inflamed with love divine!Contrition’s tears are ever hallowed by heaven’s smile,The latter end of all things man should scan awhile.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:grief","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000217","text":"Lo! a besotted fool like thee to scorn,The votaries of love! God’s wine has drownedThy wits and bidden thee wrestle with thy Lord,As when a bird his airy flight resumesExultingly, nor dreads the distant lure,Fate to his bosom speeds the shaft of woe.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000218","text":"O Thou, who art my soul’s comfort in the season of sorrow,O Thou, who art my spirit’s treasure in the bitterness of dearth,That which the imagination has not conceived, that which the understanding has not seen,Visiteth my soul from thee; hence in worship I turn towards Thee.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:grief","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000219","text":"O Thou, Who art exempt from ‘us’ and ‘we’Who pervadest the spirits of all men and women;When man and woman become one, thou art that one.When their union is dissolved, lo Thou abidest.Thou hast made these ‘us’ and ‘we’ for that purposeTo wit, to play chess with them by thyself.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000220","text":"O chosen cup-bearer, O apple of mine eyes, the like of thee,Ne’er appeared in Persia, nor in Arabia have I found it;Pour out wine till I become a wanderer from myself,For in self-hood and existence I have felt only fatigue.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000221","text":"Thee to thy goal wit-sharpening will not bring,Only the broken-hearted find the favour of the king.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:meditation","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000222","text":"The philosopher denies the existence of the DevilAt the same time he is the Devil’s laughing-stock.If thou hast not seen the Devil, look at thyself,Without demon’s aid how came that blue turban on thy brow.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000223","text":"Alas for this life so light, beware of this slumber so heavy,O soul seek the Beloved,O friend seek the FriendO watchman be wakeful; it behoves not a watchman to sleep.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000224","text":"Thought is an arrow shot by God into the airHow can it stay in the air? It returns to God.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000225","text":"The angel grew with knowledge, the beast with ignorance,Man remained in dispute between them.Sometimes knowledge draws him to the seventh heaven,Sometimes ignorance drags him down, so that (he says) 'Come what will!'","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000226","text":"The ice that remains in the shade is frozenIt saw not the brilliance of my glowing sun.All ice that has seen the smile of the sun’s faceGrows itself again, and says ‘I am the water of life.’","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000227","text":"In man’s esteem the world is vast without an endWith Power Infinite compared, a grain of sandThe world’s around the soul a dismal prison denArise! Escape! Regain the fields at large! Be men!","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000228","text":"If wheat were not valued as sweet and good for food,The cheat who shows wheat and sells barley would make no profit.Say not then that all these creeds are falseThe false ones ensnare hearts by the scent of truth.Say not that they are all erroneous fanciesThere is no fancy in the universe without some truth.In the crowd of rag-wearers there is one faqir,Search well and find out that true one.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:truth","theme:wisdom","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000229","text":"If there were no bitter things,And no opposition of fair and foul, stone and pearl,And no lust or Satan or concupiscence,And no wounds or war or fraud,Pray, O destroyer of virtue, by what name and titleCould the King of kings address his slaves?How could He say ‘O temperate’ or ‘O meek one,’Or ‘O courageous one’ or ‘O wise one.’","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:courage","theme:justice","theme:love","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:stoicism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000230","text":"If you desire that God may be pleasing to you,Then look at Him with the eyes of those that love Him.Look not at that Beauty with your own eyes,Look at that Object of desire with His votaries’ eyes.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000231","text":"Though thy nurse may frighten thee away from waterDo thou fear not, but haste on into the ocean;Thou art a duck, and flourishest on land and water,And dost not like a domestic fowl dig up the house.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000232","text":"The soul of the prophet cares for nought but God,It has nothing to do with approving or disapproving His works.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000233","text":"Human reason is drowned like the high mountains In the flood of illusion and vain imaginations.The very mountains are overwhelmed by this flood,Where is safety to be found save in Noah's ark?By illusions that plunder the road of faithThe faithful have been split into seventy-two sects;But the man of conviction escapes illusion,He does not mistake his eye-brow for the new moon.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000234","text":"Why should setting be injurious to the sun and moon?To thee it seems a setting, but ’tis a rising;Tho’ the vault seems a prison, ’tis the release of the soul.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000235","text":"Weep that at length thou may’st be of a smiling countenance,For this lamentation hath great value with God;And the value which sorrow hath there, where else has it such?Happy the eye that thus weeps,Noble the heart that thus burns,In the end all our weeping shall be turned to smiles,The man who considers the end is a blessed servant.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:grief","theme:leadership","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000236","text":"You say 'Although the fear of loss is before me,Yet I feel greater fear in remaining idle.I have a better hope through exerting myselfMy fear is increased by remaining idle.'Why then, O faint-hearted one in the matter of religion,Are you paralysed by the fear of loss?See you not how the traders in this market of oursMake large profits, both apostles and saints?","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:grief","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000237","text":"O man of double vision, hearken with attention,Seek a cure for your defective sight by listeningMany are the holy words that find no entranceInto blind hearts but they enter hearts full of light.But the deceits of Satan enter crooked heartsEven as crooked shoes fit crooked feet.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:leadership","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000238","text":"They say ‘What is love?’ Say ‘renunciation of will’Whoso has not escaped from will, no will has he.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000239","text":"He said ‘Who is at the door?’ Said I ‘Thy humble servant.’He said ‘What business have you?’ Said I ‘Lord, to greet thee.’He said ‘How long will you push?’ Said I ‘Till thou call.’He said ‘How long will you glow?’ Said I ‘Till resurrection.’","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:leadership","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000240","text":"‘Qh heart,’ said I, ‘may it bless theeTo have entered the circle of lovers,To look beyond the range of the eyeTo penetrate the windings of the bosom.’","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000241","text":"He saith ‘These saints are My childrenThough remote and alone and away from their Lord.For their trial they are orphans and wretchedYet in love I am ever holding communion with them.Thou art backed by all My protection,My children are as it were parts of Me.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:solitude","tradition:christianity","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000242","text":"He speaks to the rose’s ear and causes it to bloom,(He speaks to the stone and it becomes a jewel of the mine),He speaks a spell to body and it becomes soul,He speaks to the sun and it becomes a fount of lightAgain in its ear He whispers a word of powerAnd its face is darkened as by a hundred eclipses.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000243","text":"He said ‘O friends, God has given me inspirationOftentimes strong counsel is suggested to the weak.The wit taught by God to the beeIs withheld from the lion and the wild ass.It fills its cells with liquid sweets,For God opens the door of this knowledge to it.The skill taught by God to the silkwormIs a learning beyond the reach of the elephant.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000244","text":"The khalifa said to Laila ‘Art thou really sheFor whom Majnun lost his head and went distracted?Thou art not fairer than many other fair ones.’She replied, ‘Be silent; thou art not Majnun!If thou hadst Majnun’s eyes,The two world’s would be within thy view.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:justice","theme:love","theme:solitude","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000245","text":"The Prophet said that God has declared,‘I am not contained in aught above or below,I am not contained in earth or sky or evenIn highest heaven, know this for a surety, O beloved,Yet am I contained in the believer’s heart,If ye seek Me, search in such hearts.’","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:animism","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000246","text":"Cease to behave as wolves and dogs that you may experience the Shepherd’s love.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000247","text":"As a stone which is changed into a pure rubyIs filled with the bright light of the sun,In that stone its own properties abide notIt is filled with the sun’s properties altogether.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000248","text":"You wish to have both God and the base world together,This is impossible, ridiculous and mad.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000249","text":"God sent the prophets for this purposeNamely to sever infidelity from faith,Infidel and faithful, Mussalman and Jew,Before the prophets came, seemed all as one.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000250","text":"All the four elements are seething in this cauldron (the world)None is at rest, neither earth nor fire nor water nor airNow earth takes the form of grass on account of desireNow water becomes air for the sake of this affinity,By way of unity water becomes fireFire also becomes air in this expanse by reason of love.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:animism","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000251","text":"Both sorts of bee (i.e. bee and wasp) draw nourishment from one place but from this comes the sting and from that other the honey.Both sort of deer feed on the same grass and water; by this only dung is produced, by that pure musk.Both reeds (the common reed and the sugar-cane) are fed from one source; this one is hollow, while that one is full of sugar.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000252","text":"He, the door of whose breast has been opened, sees the sun reflected in every atom.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000253","text":"Impossibities are possible to Him,The stubbornest is docile when His will curbs whim,The blind from birth, the leper, e’en the dead ariseWhole, sound, whene’er the Omnipotent ‘Come forth!’ but cries.His smallest daily toil, a work-like pleasure still,Is to send forth three armies, bound to work His will.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000254","text":"Every moment the voice of Love is coming from left and rightWe are bound for heaven; who has a mind to sight-seeing?","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000255","text":"Every form you see has its archetype in the placeless world,If the form perished, no matter, since its original is everlasting,Every fair shape you have seen, every deep saying you have heard,Be not cast down that it perished, for that is not so.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:justice","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000256","text":"Sensual desire is a bridle and men are as camelsDo not suppose there is any bridle except that for the senseless camel.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000257","text":"The noise of clapping of hands is never heardFrom one of thy hands unaided by the other handThe man athirst cries, ‘Where is delicious water?’Water too cries ‘Where is the water-drinker?’This thirst in my soul is the attraction of the waterI am the water’s and the water is mine.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000258","text":"Know you a name without a thing answering to it?Have you ever plucked a rose (Gul) from Gaf and Lam?You name His name; go seek the reality named by it.Look for the moon in heaven, not in the water.If you desire to rise above mere names and lettersMake yourself free from self at one stroke.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000259","text":"Ah! O crow, give up this life and live anew!In view of God’s changes cast away your life!Choose the new, give up the old,For each single present year is better than three past.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000260","text":"Ah! make not thyself a eunuch, become not a monk,Because chastity is mortgaged to lust.Without lust, denial of lust is impossible,No man can display bravery against the dead.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:courage","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000261","text":"His argument is this; he says again and again‘If there were aught beyond this life, we should see it.’But if the child sees not the state of reason,Does the man of reason therefore forsake reason?And if the man of reason sees not the state of loveIs the blessed moon of love thereby eclipsed?","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000262","text":"Jesus, thy spirit, is present beside thee,Ask aid of Him for He is a sufficient helper.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000263","text":"Jesus, son of Mary, went to heaven and his ass remained below,I remain on the earth but my spirit has flown to the sky.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000264","text":"Love is that flame which, when it is kindled,Devours everything except the Beloved.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000265","text":"This is Love; to fly heavenwardTo rend every instant a hundred veils.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000266","text":"Love of God cuts short reasonings, O beloved,For it is a present refuge from perplexities.Through love bewilderment befalls the power of speechIt no longer dares to utter what passes;Therefore it closes lips from saying good or badSo that its treasure may not escape it.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:courage","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000267","text":"Love and mistress are both veiled and hiddenImpute it not as a fault if I call Him ‘Bride.’I would have kept silence from fear of my BelovedIf He had granted me but a moment’s respite.But He said, ‘Speak on, ’tis no fault,’Tis naught but the necessary result of the hidden decree’Tis a fault only to him who only sees faultsHow can the Pure Hidden Spirit notice faults.’","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","theme:solitude","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000268","text":"Union exists beyond all thought and speechBetween great Allah and the soul of each.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000269","text":"The world without that king is like a headless body;Fold yourself turban-wise, round such a head.Unless you are black, do not let the mirror go from your handThe soul is your mirror, while the body is rust.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000270","text":"Although a fool may show you sympathyAt the end he will wound you with his folly.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000271","text":"The souls of our first parents, even before their hands,Flew away from fidelity after vain pleasure.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000272","text":"My soul is grown weary of Pharaoh and his tyranny,I desire the light of the countenance of Moses, son of ʿImran.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000273","text":"When thou seest my hearse, cry not, ‘parted! parted!’Union and meeting are mine in that hour.If thou commit to the grave, say not ‘farewell! farewell!’For the grave is a curtain hiding the communion of Paradise.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000274","text":"The soul resembles a clear mirror, the body is dust upon it,Our beauty is invisible since we are under the dust.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000275","text":"The soul resembles day and the body night and we in the middleAre like the dawn between oar own day and night.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000276","text":"The bough’s attraction drew the sap from root to summit,Even as attraction draws the soul upward without a ladder.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000277","text":"Exert thyself, O man; put shoulder to the wheelThe prophets and the saints to imitate in zeal. Exertion’s not a struggle against Providence,’Twas Providence enjoined it; made it our defenceBlasphemer may I be, if ever single manBestowed in vain one effort to fulfil God’s plan.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000278","text":"Love exalts our earthly bodies to heaven,And makes the very hills to dance with joy!O Lover, ’twas love that gave life to Mount SinaiWhen it quaked and Moses fell down in a swoon.Did my Beloved only touch me with his lipsI too, like the flute would burst out in melody.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000279","text":"Pleasures of the flesh are as nuts and raisins, O son,If you are a man dispense with these two things;And if you dispense with them the goodness of GodWill set you above the nine heavens.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000280","text":"The bodies of the righteous are as pure soulsTheir words, their actions, their praises Are all as a pure soul without spot or blemish.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000281","text":"Can eye now behold Thee as truly Thou art?Can heart Thy love picture and smiles e’en in part?The heart that’s a slave to a love or a smileCan never be worthy to see thee awhile.Engrossed he that’s now with pleasure and painCan he by these accidents live o’er again?Green pastures of love in their infinitudeMore fruits yield than care and than beatitude.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:grief","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000282","text":"The motion of every atom is towards its originA man comes to be the thing on which he is bent;By the attraction of yearning and fondness the soul and the heartAssume the qualities of the Beloved and the soul of souls.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000283","text":"Men are moved by God’s decree and fixed ordinance,As sharp-set teeth are caused by heat of belly,'Tis Primal Soul that dominates the Second Soul.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000284","text":"Our every motion every moment testifiesFor it proves the presence of the everlasting God,So the revolution of the millstone so violentTestifies to the existence of a stream of water.O Thou who art above our conception and descriptions,Dust be upon our heads and upon our similitudes of Thee.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000285","text":"Every moment the world and we are renewedYet we are ignorant of this renewing for ever and aye.Life like a stream of water is renewed and renewedThough it wears the appearance of continuity in form,That seeming continuity arises from its swift renewalAs when a single spark of fire is whirled round swiftly.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000286","text":"The whole world is jealous for this causeThat God surpasseth the world in jealousy.God is as a soul and the world is as a bodyAnd bodies derive their good and evil from souls.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000287","text":"All the seventy and two heresies lurk in you,Have a care lest one day they prevail over you;He in whose breast the leaf of true faith is grownMust tremble as a leaf from fear of such a catastrophe.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000288","text":"All creatures are enslaved to thought,For this cause are they sad at heart and sorrowful.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:grief","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000289","text":"If all dissolute men were shut up in prisonThey would all be temperate and devout and pious.When power of choice is absent, actions are worthlessBut beware lest death snatch away your capital,Your power of choice is a capital yielding profitRemember well the day of final account.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:mortality","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000290","text":"Except in the house of communion with God there is no peace.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000291","text":"Only in the night the moon shines,Only in pain of heart seek the Beloved.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:grief","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000292","text":"Opposites can only he know by opposites,Only through a wound is a caress understood;Certainly this world first comes into view,That we may understand the value of that eternal world;When you are released from this, you go to that;In that eternal home of delight, you are grateful.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:gratitude","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000293","text":"Nuts in plenty but no kernel in any of them,Relish is needed for devotions to bear fruit,Kernels are needed that seeds may yield trees,How can seeds without kernels become trees?Form without life is only a dream.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000294","text":"Our earthly passions are a part of hell&nbsp;&nbsp;And the parts always share the nature of the whole.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000295","text":"Infidels when enjoying prosperity do wrongWhen they are in hell, they cry ‘O our Lord!’The prison is the hermitage of the wicked thiefFor when he is there, he is ever crying to God.Whereas the object of man’s being is to worship God,Hell is ordained as a place of worship for the proud.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000296","text":"What need were there of stars, O humble one,To one who was guided by the light of the sun,Neither moon nor planets would be needed,By one who saw directly the sun of the truth.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:leadership","theme:love","theme:truth","theme:wisdom","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000297","text":"If a saint handles earth, it becomes goldIf a sinner handles gold, it turns to dust,Whereas the saint is well-pleasing to God,In his actions his hand is the hand of God.But the sinner’s hand is the hand of Satan and demons,Because he is ensnared in falsity and fraud.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:solitude","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000298","text":"Thy business is changing things and bestowing favours,My business is mistakes and forgetfulness and error,Change my mistakes and forgetlulness to knowledgeI am altogether vile; make me temperate and meek.O thou that convertest salt earth into breadAnd bread again into the life of men,Thou makest some earth-born men as heavenAnd multipliest heaven-born saints on earth.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000299","text":"The Worker is hidden in the workshop,Enter the workshop and behold him face to face;Since a veil is drawn over the Worker by his work,Apart from His work you cannot see Him.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000300","text":"Mankind like waterfowl are sprung from the sea, the sea of soulRisen from that sea, why should the bird make here his home?Nay, we are pearls in that sea, therein we all abide,Else why does wave follow wave from the sea of soul.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000301","text":"Men are as demons and lust of wealth their chain,Which drags them forth to toil in shop and field;This chain is made of their fears and anxieties,Deem not that these men have no chains upon them.It causes them to engage in labour and the chase,It forces them to toil in mines and on the sea.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000302","text":"All hearts are the abodes of devilsBe not deceived by devil-men.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000303","text":"Your heart is as Solomon’s signet; take careThat it falls not a prey to demons.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000304","text":"Why does the formation of an infant take nine months,Because God’s method is to work by slow degrees.Not hurrying on like you, O raw one,Who claim to be a Shaikh whilst yet only a child.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000305","text":"In the world there is nought so wondrous as the sun,But the Sun of the soul sets not and has no yesterday.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000306","text":"’Tis blasphemy to praise Him: I proclaim Myself extant and ‘self’ is mortal shame.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mortality","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000307","text":"Who is he in my ear that hearkens to my voice,Or who is he that utters words in my mouth?Who is he in mine eye that looks out of mine eyeOr what is the soul—wilt thou not say—of which I am the garment?","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000308","text":"You have seen the mountain, not the mine within the mountain.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:solitude","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000309","text":"What seed went down into the earth but it grew,Why this doubt of thine as regards the seed of man?","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000310","text":"Read ‘I was a hidden treasure and desired to be known;’Hide not the hidden treasure but disclose it;Your true treasure is hidden under a false one,Just as butter is hidden within the substance of milk,The false one is this transitory body of yours,The true one your divine soul.Long time this milk is exposed to viewAnd the soul’s butter is hidden and of no account.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","theme:solitude","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000311","text":"Though the ruby has no stamp, what matters it?Love is fearless in the midst of the sea of fear.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:courage","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000312","text":"No favour was left which that winsome beauty did not bestow,What fault of ours if he failed in bounty towards you?Thou art reviling because that charmer wrought tyranny,Whoever saw in the two worlds a fair one that played not the tyrant?When the spirit became lost in contemplation, it said this‘None but God has contemplated the beauty of God;’This eye and that lamp are two lights, each individual,When they came together, no-one distinguished them.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:creativity","theme:justice","theme:love","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000313","text":"We are the family of the Lord and His sucking babes,The Prophet said ‘The people are God’s family,’He who sends forth the rain from heaven,Can He not also provide our daily bread?","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:relationships","tradition:christianity","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000314","text":"We have been in heaven, we have been friends of the angelsThither, sire, let us return for that is our country,How different a source have the world of dust and the pure substance,Though we came down, let us haste back—what place is this?","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000315","text":"I regard not the outside and the words,I regard the inside and the state of heart;I look at the heart if it be humble,Though the words may be the reverse of humble;Because the heart is substance and words accidents,Accidents are only a means, substance is the final cause,How long wilt thou dwell on words and superficialities, A burning heart is what I want; consort with burning.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000316","text":"Then think not lowly of thy heart, though lowly,For holy is it and there dwells the holy,God’s presence-chamber is the human breast,Ah! happy spirit with such Inmate blest.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000317","text":"As we are all members of AdamWe have heard these melodies in Paradise;Though earth and water have cast their veil upon usWe retain faint reminiscences of those earthly songs;But while we are thus shrouded by gross earthly veilsHow can the tones of the dancing spheres reach us?","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000318","text":"The moon sheds her light and the dogs howl;Everyone acts according to his nature,To each his office is allotted by the divine decree.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000319","text":"The body loves green pastures and running water,For this cause that its origin is from them.The love of the soul is for wisdom and knowledge,That of the body for houses, gardens, and vineyards;The love of the soul is for things exalted on high,That of the body for acquisition of goods and food.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000320","text":"Look not in the world for bliss and fortune, since thou wilt not find them,Seek bliss in both worlds by serving Him.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000321","text":"Read the text ‘I have not created Jinns and men but to worship me,’The only object of the world is to worship God.Though the object of a book is to teach an art,If you make a pillow of it, it serves that purpose too,Yet its main object is not to serve as a pillowBut to impart knowledge and useful instruction.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000322","text":"If for the Faith thou bear’st thy wealth, it thenThe Prophet says, is pure to righteous men.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000323","text":"I am sweet-smiling Jesus by whom the world is revived,But my lineage is from God: I know nought of Mary.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000324","text":"I was, ere a name had been named upon earth,Ere one trace yet existed of aught that has birth:When the locks of the Loved One streamed forth for a sign,And Being was none save the Presence Divine!Named and name were alike emanations from Me,Ere aught that was ‘I’ yet existed, or ‘We’;Ere the veil of the flesh for Messiah was wrought,To the Godhead I bowed in prostration of thought.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000325","text":"I extracted the marrow of the Koran, and threw the bone to the dogs.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000326","text":"I am thy lute, on every vein (chord) of mineThou strikest the quill, and I vibrate.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000327","text":"I’ll be the very slave of him who at each stageWill not suppose the goal ’tis of his pilgrimage;Before the traveller reach the home he bears in mindHow many stages are there must be left behind!","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000328","text":"Repentance lights on him who tests one tested already.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000329","text":"I am ever in concord with this father of ours,And earth ever appears to me as a Paradise;Each moment a fresh form, a new beauty,So that weariness vanishes at these ever-fresh sights;I see the world filled with blessings,Fresh waters ever welling up from new fountains.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:creativity","theme:gratitude","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","theme:nature","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000330","text":"Thou and I individuals no more shall be mingled in ecstasy,Joyful and secure from foolish babble, thou and I.All the bright plumed birds of heaven will devour their hearts with envyIn the place where we shall laugh in such a fashion thou and I.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000331","text":"Death of the body is a benefaction to the spiritual,What damage has pure gold to dread from the shears.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:mortality","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000332","text":"If death be a human being say to him ‘Draw nearThat I may closely fold him in a fond embrace,From him I extort by force eternal life,Whilst he but snatches from me the dervish’s party-coloured dress.’","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:mortality","theme:nature","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000333","text":"Those drunk with God though they be thousands, yet are one,Those drunk with lust, though it be a single one, he is a double.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000334","text":"The billow of largesse hath appeared, the thunder of the sea hath arrived,The morn of blessedness hath dawned. Morn? No, ’tis the light of God.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000335","text":"Then love the saints; their love plant deeply in thy heart,The pure of mind alone deserve a pure love’s part,Court not despair; hope ever springs in human breast,Seek not the dark; the sun of light shines full confest.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:solitude","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000336","text":"The sect of lovers is distinct from all others,Lovers have a religion and a faith of their own.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000337","text":"Every night spirits are released from this cage (the body)And set free, neither lording it nor lorded over,At night prisoners are unaware of their prison,At night kings are unaware of their majesty, Then there is no thought or care for loss or gain,No regard to such an one or such an one,The state of the ‘knower’ is such as this even when awakeGod says ‘Thou would’st deem him awake though asleep,’Sleeping to the affairs of the world day and nightLike a pen in the directing hand of the writer.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:grief-healing","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:grief","theme:justice","theme:love","tradition:animism","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000338","text":"Has not the copper of your existence been changed, like Moses, to gold by his alchemy?What matter though you have no gold in a sack, like Qarun?Within you is an Egypt, and you are its garden of sugar-canes;What matter though you have no supply of sugar from without?","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:solitude","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000339","text":"The lover shineth among his fellows as in heavenThe brilliant moon among the host of stars.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000340","text":"The ant of lust becomes by habit like a snake,Slay first of all the snake of your lust,Else this snake of yours will become a dragon;But every one regards his own snake as an ant,Go inquire of your true state from a man of heart.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000341","text":"A pauper may amused be with counterfeited coin,But take this to the mint; defaced ’twill be in fine;Then be not thou misled with gilded counterfeit,Delusion will thee plunge headlong into hell’s pit.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000342","text":"The generous die but their kindness remains,O happy he who drove this chariot (of kindness),The unjust die and their injustice remains,Alas for the soul that commits deceit and fraud.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:justice","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000343","text":"Victory falls to the believers at last,The hypocrites have death in the next world.Although both parties are engaged in one game,Yet, as regards one another, they are inhabitants of Merv and Rai (i.e., far asunder),Each goes to his own place,Each fares according to his name.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:mortality","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000344","text":"T am a bird of the heavenly garden; I belong not to the earthly sphere,They have made for two or three days a cage of my body.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000345","text":"A bird flies with its wings towards its nest,The wings of a man are his aspiration and aim.If a lover be befouled with good and evilYet regard not these; regard rather his aspiration,Though a falcon be all white and unmatched in form,If he hunts mice, he is contemptible and worthless,And if an owl fixes his affection on the king,He is a falcon in reality; regard not his outward form.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000346","text":"He is only scented with musk, he is not himself musk,He smells of musk, but is really naught but dung,For his dung to become musk, O disciple,He must graze year after year in the divine pasture.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000347","text":"Seek ye a purchaser who will pay you gold,Where will you find one more liberal than God?He buys the worthless rubbish which is your wealth,He pays you the light that illumines your heart,He accepts these frozen and lifeless bodies of yoursAnd gives you a kingdom beyond what you dream of,He takes a few drops of your tearsAnd gives you the divine fount sweeter than sugar.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000348","text":"O Moses! the lovers of fair rites are one class,They whose hearts and souls burn with love are another,If they speak amiss, call them not sinners,If a martyr be stained with blood, wash it not away,Blood is better than water for martyrs,This fault is better than a thousand correct forms.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:justice","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","theme:solitude","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000349","text":"Good news! Good news! Lo! the spring is at hand,If the blossoms did not shine as bright helmets,How could the fruits display their globes?When the blossoms are shed, the fruits come to a head,When the body is destroyed, the soul lifts up its head.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:grief","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000350","text":"The blast of the last trump will be God’s commandTo every atom to lift its head from the earth,The souls also of each will return to their bodies,Even as sense returns to bodies awaking from sleep,On that morn each soul will recognise its own bodyAnd return to its own ruin like hidden treasure.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000351","text":"Thou takest on thyself the shame of hemp and wine,In order that thou mayest for one moment escape from thyself.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000352","text":"None but God hath contemplated the beauty of God.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000353","text":"The strange thing is, not that winged fowlFall into the deadly snare without seeing it,But that they see the snare and the limed twig,And yet fall into it, whether they will or no.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000354","text":"Become nought, nought from self-hood, becauseThere is no crime worse than thy being.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000355","text":"Mere fancy’s pictures ever objects mar,Things non-existent often frenzy paints,We see mankind deluded over feints;Their peace, their war not seldom for a sham,Their pride, their shame some sorry epigram.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:grief","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000356","text":"Thou hadst not seen a single blind man seated on the moat-edge,Had they sought God instead of morsel and pittance.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000357","text":"Defects are the mirrors of the attributes of beautyThe base is the mirror of the High and Glorious One,Because one contrary shows forth its contraryAs honey’s sweetness is shown by vinegar’s sourness,Who recognises and confesses his own defectsIs hastening in the way that leads to perfection.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000358","text":"I am the sunlight falling from above,Yet never severed from the sun I love.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000359","text":"Thy light is at once joined with all things and apart from all.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000360","text":"This soul is a measure; how should the measure knowThat it is receiving of spirit and conveying to dust?Its task is to measure in restless love,Taking from heaven above, scattering o’er earth below.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000361","text":"Woman is a ray of God, not a mere mistress,The Creator’s self as it were, not a mere creature!","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000362","text":"What rays of wisdom poured on water and on landEre earth could nourish seed, yield corn to our demand!The earth, a faithful trustee, gives back what we sow,No fraud, embezzlement, in its trust do we know.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:relationships","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000363","text":"Where should the ignoble lament and pray,If Thou didst only accept the good, O merciful One?Go, do not commit sin, for even our good deedsAppear as sin in the sight of our Beloved.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000364","text":"In outward form thou art the microcosmBut in reality the macrocosm,Seemingly the bough is the cause of the fruit,But really the bough exists because of the fruit.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000365","text":"The mind’s ear becomes the sensorium of inspiration,For what is this Divine voice but the inward voice?The spirit’s eye and ear possess this sense,The eye and ear of reason and sense lack it.The word ‘compulsion’ makes me impatient for love’s sake,’Tis he who loves not, who is fettered by compulsion,This is close communion with God, not compulsion,The shining of the sun, and not a dark cloud.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000366","text":"As soul became pregnant by the Soul of souls,So by the former soul did the world become pregnant;Then the world brought forth another world,And of this last are brought forth other worlds.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000367","text":"In presence of Joseph no coquetries useBut humble thyself; soft entreaties infuse;From Jesus a breath then may blow upon thee,Transform thee to what he was, what thou mayest be:A stone will not blossom because it is spring,As earth make thyself; flowers around thee may cling.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:grief","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","theme:nature","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000368","text":"Before they (the prophets) came, we were all alike,No one knew whether he was right or wrong,Genuine coin and base coin were current alike,The world was a night and we travellers in the dark,Till the sun of the prophets arose and cried‘Begone, O slumber! welcome, O pure light!’Now the eye sees how to distinguish colours,It sees the difference between rubies and pebbles.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000369","text":"All elephants, wolves and lions of the forest,All dragons and snakes and even little ants,Yea, even air, water, earth and fire,Draw their sustenance from Him both winter and summer,Every moment the Heaven cries to Him, saying‘O Lord, guilt not Thy hold of me for a moment!The pillar of my being is Thy aid and protection.’","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","theme:nature","tradition:animism","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000370","text":"When words deceitful are employed as wraps for guile,They’re bubbles on the water, only last awhile,Such words are merely shell; the intent their kernel is,Or coloured portraiture of man; no life is his,A shell may often cover kernel of foul smell,A kernel sound can well afford to lose its shell.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000371","text":"We are pieces of steel, and Thy love is the magnet,Thou art the source of all inspiration, in myself I have seen none.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000372","text":"Take the cotton of evil suggestions from the mind’s ear,That the heavenly voice from above may enter it,That you may understand that riddle of His,That you may be cognisant of that open secret.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000373","text":"Love is a perfect muzzle of evil suggestions;Without love who ever succeeded in stopping them?Be a lover and seek that fair beauty,Haunt for that waterfowl in every Stream!How can you get water from that which cuts it off,How gain understanding from what destroys understanding,Apart from principles of reason are other principlesOf light and great price to be gained by love of God,Besides this reason of yours God has other reasonsWhich will procure for you heavenly nourishment.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:creativity","theme:justice","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000374","text":"Accept His command and you will be able to execute it,Seek union with Him and you will find yourselves united,Exertion is giving thanks for Gad’s blessings,Think ye that your fatalism gives such thanks?","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:gratitude","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000375","text":"We’ve done with outer warfare, lesser as it is,And as the Prophet, wage the greater warfare, his;We put our trust in God, from Him we ask for aid,With His assistance faith can move a mountain staid.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:relationships","tradition:christianity","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000376","text":"Of rhymes do I dream? ’Tis my love orders meOf love still to dream; swain devoted to be,‘Thyself make thou happy. Rhymes leave now aloneThe rhyme I seek thou art. I love thee my own.What’s rhyme that thou turnest thy thoughts thitherward,Mere bramble on wall, hedging round our vineyard,I care not for words, for asseverations,My time if I pass in these sweet delusions.’","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","theme:solitude","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000377","text":"The base coin says to me with pride every moment,‘O pure gold, how am I inferior to you?’The gold replies, ‘Even so, O comrade;But the touchstone is at hand; be ready to meet it!’","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000378","text":"The moon has revealed her face, and opened her radiant wings,Borrow a soul and eyes from some one, if you have them not.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000379","text":"God drops into the heart a single pearl-dropWhich is not bestowed on oceans or skies.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000380","text":"The warden of a castle on the marches laid,Far from his sovereign, distant from much-needed aid,Defends his post with valour from beleaguering foe,Disdains to be bought over, scorns the tempter’s foe,His station’s on a frontier, no eye sees him actTo duty true, he honestly fulfils his pact.Then in his monarch’s presence honours due he gains,Above the brave men fighting in the royal trains,Man’s faith and piety on earth are prized of God,But after death professed, less value have than clod.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:courage","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:mortality","theme:nature","theme:truth","tradition:animism","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000381","text":"The day of judgment is the day of the great review,Whoso is fair and enlightened longs for that review;Whoso like a Hindoo is black with sin,The day of review will sound the knell of his disgrace,If his thorn puts not forth a single rose-budThe spring in disclosing him is his foe.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:justice","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000382","text":"Argue not from the condition of common men,Stumble not at severity and mercy;For mercy and severity, joy and sorrow are transientAnd transient things die; God is heir of all.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:grief","theme:love","theme:mortality","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000383","text":"Place a padlock on your throat and hide the key.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000384","text":"The nearness of the voice proves to such an oneThat the voice proceeds from a friend who is near,The sweetness of the kinsman’s voice too, O beloved,Proves the veracity of that kinsman,To the wise whose hearts are enlightenedThe mere sound of that voice proves its truth.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:truth","theme:wisdom","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000385","text":"In this prison the food of true faith is scarce,And by the tricks of this dog what there is, is lost,In spite of prayers and fasts and endless painsOur food is altogether devoured by him,Let us seek refuge with Allah from Satan,Alas! we are perishing from his insolence.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:grief","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000386","text":"Ah, how many diverse roads are pointed outAnd each followed by some sect for dear life,If the right road were easily obtainableEvery Jew and Gueber would have hit on it.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000387","text":"Pity keep for Jesus, pity not the ass (i.e., the body),Let not fleshly impulse intellect surpass;If an ass could somewhat catch of Jesus’ mind,Ranked among the sages he his place would find,Though because of Jesus you may walk in woe,Still from Him comes healing; never let Him go.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:grief","theme:love","theme:mental-health","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000388","text":"Love carried off as plunder the chattels which we possessed,We are independent of profit and loss and market.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:grief","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000389","text":"God created pain and grief for this purpose,To wit, to manifest happiness by its opposites.Hidden things are manifested by their opposites,But as God has no opposite, He remains hidden,God’s light has no opposite in the range of creationWhereby it may be manifested to view,Perforce ‘Our eyes see Him not, though He sees us,’Behold this in the case of Moses and Mount Sinai.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:grief","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000390","text":"Night and day comes a winged arrow from the hidden bow,Yield up your sweet life; what can you do? you have no shield.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000391","text":"If the sleeping spirit knew itself to be asleep,Whatever it might see, it would feel neither joy nor sorrow.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:grief-healing","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:grief","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000392","text":"Mysteries are not communicable save to those who know,Mystery in the ear of infidels is no mystery.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000393","text":"The thread and the needle are related to one another; but a camel is not fitted to pass through the eye of a needle; how should the body of a camel become slender except by abstinence and exertion?","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000394","text":"When the spirit lovingly embraces Thee,In Thy presence all images become spirit.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000395","text":"'Twere better that the spirit which wears not true love as a garmentHad not been; its being is but shame.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000396","text":"Spirit is very subtle and love is very jealous,What room for form, if the felt is hundredfold?","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000397","text":"With muffled heads you cannot see,You’ve wrapped your cloaks in folds about your heads and eyes,Your sense of sight cannot see what before you lies.The world’s eye man is; all the rest’s mere skin and shell,A real eye’s he who strives his Friend to see right well.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000398","text":"One day I was filled with longingTo behold in human form the splendours of the Friend,To witness the ocean gathered up into a drop,The sun compressed into a single atom.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000399","text":"When my bier moveth on the day of death,Think not my heart is in this world,Do not weep for me, and cry, ‘Woe! Woe!’Thou wilt fall in the devil’s snare; that is woe.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:mortality","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000400","text":"Day and night you are eagerly asking for news,Whilst every member of your body is telling you news,Since each member of your body issued from Not-being,How much pleasure has it seen and how much pain?For no member grows and flourishes without pleasure,And each member is weakened by every pain.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:grief","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000401","text":"Though the mere imitator quotes a hundred proofs,They are all based on opinion, not on conviction,He is only scented with musk, he is not himself musk,He smells of musk but is really naught but dung.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000402","text":"O God there are hundreds of snares and baitsAnd we are even as greedy and foolish birds;Every moment our feet are caught in a fresh snare,Yea, each one of us though he be a falcon or Simurgh,Thou dost release us every moment and straightwayWe again fly into the snare, O Almighty one.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000403","text":"The million spears of Pharaoh vaunting in his might,By Moses’ wand were broken in the appointed night:And many sons of skill, for healing science famedBy Jesu’s curing halt, lame, blind, deaf, mad, were shamed;How many poets, orators, great men of note,By word of the Illiterate One were shown to dote.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:grief-healing","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:grief","theme:love","theme:mental-health","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000404","text":"The Word is become foul with mingled earth,The water is become muddy; close the mouth of the well,Till God makes it again pure and sweet,Yea, till He purifies what He has made foul;Patience will accomplish thy desire, not haste,Be patient, God knows what is best.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000405","text":"I journeyed years and months for love of that moon,Heedless of the way, absorbed in God,With bare feet I trod upon thorns and flints,Seeing I was bewildered, and beside myself and senseless;What knows the heart of road and stages,What of distant and near, while it is drunk with love.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000406","text":"The head whose reason has fled is a tail.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000407","text":"When the day dawns from heaven, night flees awayWhat then can its darkness know of the nature of light?The gnat scuds away before the blast of the winds,What then knows the gnat of the savour of the winds?When the Eternal appears, the transitory is annulled,What then knows the transitory of the Eternal?","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000408","text":"Though the material sun is unique and single,We can conceive similar suns like to it,But the Sun of the soul beyond this firmament,No like thereof is seen in concrete or abstract.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000409","text":"The wine of God’s grace hath no brim,If it appear to have a brim, ’tis the fault of the cup.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000410","text":"Giving thanks for blessing increases blessingsBut fatalism snatches those blessings from your hands,Your fatalism is to sleep on the road; sleep notTill ye behold the gate of the king’s palace.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:gratitude","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000411","text":"Look to your hearts! I whatever betide, O Moslems,Am so mingled with Him, that no heart is mingled with me,I was born of His love at the first, I gave Him my love at the last,When the fruit springs from the bough, on that bough it hangs.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000412","text":"Nor gold nor silver seek I but aboveAll gifts, the heart, and buy it with my love,Yea! one sad contrite heart which men despise,More than my throne and fixed decree I prize.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000413","text":"O base one, behold a hundred thousand soulsDancing towards the deadly sword of his love,Behold water in a pitcher; pour it out;Will that water run away from the stream?When that water joins the water of the streamIt is lost therein and becomes itself the stream.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000414","text":"The Sufi is as it were, the ‘son of the season’But the pure is exalted above season and state,Religious raptures depend on feelings and willBut the pure one is regenerated by the breath of Jesus,You are a lover of your own raptures, not of me,You turn to me only in hope of experiencing raptures.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","theme:nature","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000415","text":"The life of this world is a truce between opposites.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000416","text":"Form is born of that which is without form,Wherefore to thee every moment comes death and ‘return,’Mustafa saith ‘The world endureth only a moment,’So thought is an arrow shot by God into the air,How can it stay in the air? It returns to God.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","theme:mortality","theme:resilience","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000417","text":"I am a painter, a maker of pictures; every moment I shape a beauteous form,And then in thy presence I melt them all away.I call up a hundred phantoms and endue them with a spiritWhen I behold thy phantom, I cast them in the fire,Art thou the vintner’s cup-bearer or the enemy of him who is sober,Or is it thou who mak’st a ruin of every house I build?In thee the soul is dissolved, with thee it is mingled,So I will cherish the soul, because it has a perfume of thee.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:recovery","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:grief","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000418","text":"The lamp of the heart that is a timid traderAcquires neither loss nor gain by its ventures,Nay it acquires loss, for it is precluded from gain,’Tis the lamp that takes fire that acquires light.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:grief","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000419","text":"Till the corn be ground with the mill, how can our table be furnished with bread?","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000420","text":"Body is not veiled from soul, neither soul from body,Yet no man hath ever seen a soul.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000421","text":"Our breathings are lifted up in fear of God,Offerings from us to the throne of Eternity,Then come down to us rewards for our praisesThe double thereof yea mercies from the king of glory,Therefore are we constrained to utter these praisesThat slaves may attain the height of God’s gifts,And so this rising and descent go on evermore,And cease not for ever and aye.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000422","text":"Beats there a heart within that breast of thine,Then compass rev’rently its sacred shrine;For the true spiritual K‘aba is the heartAnd no proud pile of perishable art,When God ordained the pilgrim rite, that signWas meant to lead thy heart to things divine,A thousand times he treads that round in vain,Who e’en one human heart would idly pain.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:grief","theme:love","theme:solitude","tradition:animism","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000423","text":"Through ignorance, sloth and folly,Though He stands by us, we are shut off from Him,The noise of thunder makes the head of the thirsty ache,When he knows not that it unlocks the blessed showers,His eyes are fixed on the running streamUnwitting of the sweetness of the rain from heaven;He urges the steed of his desire towards the caused,And perforce remains shut off from the causer.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000424","text":"So long as a babe cannot grasp or run,It takes its father’s back for its carriage,But when it becomes independent and uses its handsIt falls into grievous troubles and disgrace.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000425","text":"Better to arm a drunken negro thanTo lavish learning on a wicked man.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000426","text":"Place a sword in his hand and remove his impotenceTo see if he turns out a warrior or a robber;Because freewill is that with which ‘We honour Adam,’Half the swarm become bees, and half wasps.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000427","text":"Our life’s our quiver. When our years are vainly spentIn chasing phantoms, grief one day will have its vent.Let God’s protection mercifully on us rest,All fancies and all phantoms stand at once confessed,God’s servants are His shadows here below on earthTo this world dead, but living in a second birth.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:grief-healing","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:grief","theme:leadership","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000428","text":"On the day that you entered upon existenceYou were first fire, or earth, or air,If you had continued in that your original state,How could you have arrived at this dignity of humanity.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:justice","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000429","text":"If you have not gone to the Kaaba, fortune will draw you thither,Do not flee, O babbler, for you have no refuge from God.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000430","text":"Thou hast come to draw men to union with Me,Not to drive them far away from Me,So far as possible, engage not in dissevering;‘The thing most repugnant to Me is divorce.’","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000431","text":"Thou wert first and last thou shalt be,Make my last better than my first,When Thou art hidden, I am of the infidels,When Thou art manifest, I am of the faithful.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000432","text":"You are in the bonds of (absorbed in) the arrangement of beard and turban,How will you gain him who quaffs the mighty flagon (of love)?","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:relationships","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000433","text":"Thou wert dust and art spirit, thou wert ignorant and art wise,He who has led thee thus far, will lead thee further also,How pleasant are the pains He makes thee suffer while He gently draws thee to Himself,His flames are as water, do not frown upon Him.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:grief","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000434","text":"Set thy whole desire on that whereof thou hast no hope,For thou hast come thus far from original hopelessness.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000435","text":"You are as a dry valley and I as the rain,You are as a ruined city and I as the architect,Except my service which is joy’s sunriseMan has never felt and never will feel an impression of joy.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000436","text":"Thou didst sow the seed of deceit, thou didst indulge in derision,Thou didst regard God as nothing: see now, O miscreant!","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000437","text":"O honoured guest in love’s high feast, O bird of the angel sphere,’Tis cause to weep if thou wilt keep thy habitation here.A voice at morn to thee is borne—God whispers to the soul,‘If on the way the dust thou’llt lay, thou soon wilt gain the goal,That road be thine toward the shrine; and lo! in bush and briarThe many slain by love and pain in flower of young desire,Who on the track fell wounded back and saw not ere the endA ray of bliss, a touch, a kiss, a token of the Friend.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:grief","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000438","text":"Seek earnestly for deliverance from the uncongenial,The society of the uncongenial is like the grave.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000439","text":"It is on account of their sweet voicesThat choice parrots and nightingales are prisoned in cages;Ugly owls and crows are never prisoned in cages,Such a thing was never heard of in history.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000440","text":"Thou fanciest thyself near to God,Saying ‘The maker of the dish is not far from the dish,’Knowest thou not that the nearness of saints to GodInvolves the power to do mighty works and signs?Iron was as wax in the hands of David,Wax in thy hands is as iron.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000441","text":"Thou art a darling bosom friend, thou art always behind the secret veil,Why dost thou make thy dwelling-place in this perishable abode,Regard thine own state, go forth and journeyFrom the prison of the Formal world to the meadow of Ideas.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000442","text":"God has enjoined this servitude upon us,We say not this merely on our own authority;We enjoy life on condition of doing His will;If He bids us, we sow our seed upon the sand.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000443","text":"He is like Pharaoh and his body like Moses,He runs abroad crying ‘Where is my foe?’While lust is in his house, which is his body,He bites his finger in spite against strangers.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000444","text":"Enter the hearts of my servantsTo gain the paradise of beholding me, O fearer of God.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:leadership","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000445","text":"Enter houses by the doorsAnd trace effects to their causes.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000446","text":"He is the perfect world, yet He is single,He holds in hand the writing of the whole of existence,Wherefore all forms and colours of beauty cry out,‘Good news! good news! lo! the spring is at hand!’","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000447","text":"Whoever may put off to sow seed in springIgnores the true value of time’s swiftest wing,Let each one take refuge in mercy of GodWho grace manifold on our souls has bestowed,Then shalt thou find shelter, when shelter thou needest,Fire’s, water’s protection thou’lt have as thou heedest.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000448","text":"Prize not at all life that has passed without love,Love is the water of life: receive it in thy heart and soul.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000449","text":"The people of love are hidden among the peoplesAs a liberal encompassed by the contumely of the base.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000450","text":"No mountain-pass as this life’s progress is so steep,Let envy not increase thy load; thou canst but creep,The flesh a hot-bed is of envy and of strifeThese soil the soil; for envy’s bane of mortal life.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mortality","theme:nature","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000451","text":"Thorn-eating camel truly is this world of ours,Ahmed then came and mounted; him that camel bears.O camel, on thy back thou bear’st a vase of rose,On thee from thence have sprouted rose-buds as God knows,Thy tastes lead thee to camel-thorn and wastes of sand,To thee the thorn’s a rose; the wilderness, rich land.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000452","text":"Seek the pearl, O brother, in the shell,And seek for skill among the learned.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000453","text":"Though you have no feet, choose to journey in yourself,Like the ruby-mine receive a print from the sunbeams,Make a journey out of self into self, O master,For by such a journey earth becomes a quarry of gold.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000454","text":"If the sun did not fare by foot and wing every night,How would the world be illuminated at morning tide?And if the salt water did not go up from the sea to the skyWhence would the garden be quickened by river and rain?","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000455","text":"O Ali! out of all forms of religious serviceChoose thou the shadow of that dear friend of God!Do thou seek refuge in the shadow of the wise manThat thou mayest escape thy fierce secret foes,Of all forms of service this is fittest for theeThou shalt surpass all who were before thee.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000456","text":"One I seek, one I know, one I see, one I call.He is the first, He is the last, He is the outward, He is the inward.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000457","text":"One said ‘The world would be a pleasant place,If death never set foot within it’;Another answered ‘If there were no death,The complicated world would not be worth a jot.It would be a crop raised in the desertLeft neglected and never threshed out.’","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mortality","theme:solitude","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000458","text":"One impulse from God is better than a hundred efforts.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000459","text":"Society with saints no doubt’s of great availTo piety it leads; ‘God’s fear shall never fail.’Thou wast a very rock, a worthless pebble-stone,By saints’ communion fined, a pearl of price thou’st shone.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000460","text":"Seek sweet syrup in the garden of love,For nature is a seller of vinegar and a crusher of unripened grapes.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000461","text":"From thy good thoughts are born the boys of Paradise and the houris,From thy evil thoughts is born the great demon (Iblis),See how the secret thought of the geometrician has become a castle or a palace,See how the hidden Providence without beginning has become this mighty universe.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000462","text":"Apparently thou art the ruler of thy wife like water over fire,In reality thou art ruled by and suppliant to her.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000463","text":"Serpents’ poison is life to serpents,In relation to mankind it is death.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mortality","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000464","text":"From the moment you came into the world of beingA ladder was placed before you that you might escape,First you were mineral, later you turned to plant,Then you became animal: how should this be a secret to you? Afterwards you were made man, with knowledge, reason, faith,Behold the body which is a portion of the dust-pit, how perfect it has grown!When you have travelled on from man, you will doubtless become an angel,After that you are done with this earth; your station is in heaven.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000465","text":"Thou mouldest of foul and fair the form of a manThat he may flee two leagues from the odour of foulness;Thou mak’st him a morsel of dust that he may become pure herbage,He is free from filth when Thou hast breathed into him a soul.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:justice","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000466","text":"I will not shun thy blow, for very crudeIs the heart that ne’er burned in the fire of thine affliction,To thy praise and praisers there is no end,What atom but is reeling with thy praise?","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000467","text":"Let not a weakling like you censure me;What seems night to you is broad day to me,What seems a prison to you is a garden to me,Busiest occupation is rest to me,Your feet are in the mire, to me mire is rose,What to you is funeral wailing is marriage drum to me.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000468","text":"Opposite shows up opposite as a Frank a negro.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000469","text":"Welcome soul-producing sun! when a single ray of thine hath appeared,Thousands of human souls shoot forth from black (barren) clay.","author":"Rumi","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000470","text":"A COURSE OF INSTRUCTIONS GIVEN AT ALL SAINTS","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000471","text":"IN WATCHINGS OFTEN: Addresses to Nurses and Others. With a Preface by the Right Rev. EDWARD KING, D.D., late Bishop of Lincoln. With a Frontispiece (the Crucifixion, by PERUGINO). Crown 8vo, paper boards, 2s. 6d.; cloth, 3s. 6d.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000472","text":"PRAYER AND ACTION; or, The Three Notable Duties (Prayer, Fasting, and Almsgiving). With an Introduction by the Bishop of London. Crown 8vo, 2s. 6d. net.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000473","text":"IMMORTALITY. Crown 8vo, 4s. net. (_Oxford Library of Practical Theology_.)","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:mortality","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000474","text":"PARADISE: A Course of Addresses on the State of the Faithful Departed. Crown 8vo, paper covers, 1s. net; cloth, 2s. net. *** _Extracted from \"Immortality\"_","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:mortality","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000475","text":"RESPONSIBILITY: An Address to Girls. 16mo, paper covers, 4d. net; bound in rexine, 1s. net. Cheap Edition, 1d. net.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:leadership","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000476","text":"LONDON, NEW YORK, BOMBAY, CALCUTTA, AND MADRAS","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000477","text":"These Lectures were originally delivered as the Boyle Lectures for 1910, and were afterwards repeated in a more popular form at All Saints, Margaret Street.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000478","text":"They are now written from notes taken at their delivery at All Saints, and the writer's thanks are due to the kindness of those who lent him the notes.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000479","text":"Some explanation of their elementary character seems called for.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000480","text":"(1) To remind an instructed congregation of that which they knew already--and to make them more grateful for the often underrated privilege of being members of the Catholic Church; and","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:gratitude","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000481","text":"(2) To suggest some simple lines of instruction which they might pass on to others.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000482","text":"Unless the instructed Laity will help the Clergy to teach their uninstructed brethren, a vast number of {viii} Church people must remain in ignorance of their privileges and responsibilities.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000483","text":"And if at times the instructed get impatient and say, \"Everybody knows that,\" they will probably be mistaken.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000484","text":"Many a Churchman is ignorant of the first principles of his religion, of why he is a Churchman, and even of what he means by \"the Church,\" just because of the false assumption--\"Everybody knows\".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000485","text":"It seems absurd to treat such subjects as _The Church, Her Books, Her Sacraments_, in half-hour Lectures; but, in spite of obvious drawbacks, there may be two advantages.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000486","text":"It may be useful to take a bird's-eye view of a whole subject rather than to look minutely into each part--and it may help to keep the Lecturer to the point!","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000487","text":"Dear Saviour! make our hearts to burn, And make our lives to shine, Oh! make us ever true to Thee, And true to all that's Thine-- Thy Church, Thy Saints, Thy Sacraments, Thy Scriptures; may we own No other Lord, no other rule, But Thee, and Thine alone.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:solitude","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000488","text":"_Christus Dilexit Ecclesiam_: \"Christ loved the Church\"[1]--and if we love what Christ loved, we do well.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000489","text":"(1) What is this Church which Christ loved?","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000490","text":"First: _What is the Church?_ The Church is a visible Society under a visible Head, in Heaven, in Paradise, and on Earth.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000491","text":"Jesus Christ--visible to the greatest number of its members (i.e.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000492","text":"in Heaven and in Paradise), and vicariously represented here by \"the Vicar of Christ upon Earth,\" the Universal Episcopate.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","theme:nature","tradition:animism","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000493","text":"Next: _When and where was it established?_ It was established in Palestine, in the Upper Chamber, on the first Whitsunday, \"the Day of Pentecost\".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000494","text":"Then: _What was it established for?_ It was established to be the channel of salvation and sanctification for fallen man. God may, and does, use other channels, but, \"according to the Scriptures,\" the Church is the authorized channel.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000495","text":"As such, let us think of the Church on earth under six Prayer-Book names:--","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:animism","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000496","text":"(I) The Catholic Church. (II) The National Church. (III) The Established Church. (IV) The Church of England. (V) The Reformed Church. (VI) The Primitive Church.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000497","text":"The Creeds call it \"the _Catholic_ Church\" and describe its doctrine as \"the _Catholic_ Religion,\" or the \"_Catholic_ Faith\".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000498","text":"The Te Deum, Litany, and Ember Collect explain this word \"Catholic\" to mean \"the holy Church _throughout all the {3} world_,\" \"_an universal_ Church,\" \"_thy holy_ Church universal\"; and the Collect for the King in the Liturgy defines it as \"the _whole_ Church\".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000499","text":"The \"Catholic Church,\" then, is \"the whole Church,\" East and West, Latin, Greek, and English, \"throughout all the world \".[2] Its message is world-wide, according to the terms of its original Commission, \"Go ye into _all the world_\".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000500","text":"Thus, wherever there are souls and bodies to be saved and sanctified, there, sooner or later, will be the Catholic Church.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000501","text":"And, as a matter of history, this is just what we find.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000502","text":"Are there souls to be saved and sanctified in Italy?--there is the Church, with its local headquarters at Rome.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000503","text":"Are there souls to be saved and sanctified in Russia?--there is the Church, once with its local {4} headquarters at Moscow.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000504","text":"Are there souls to be saved and sanctified in England?--there is the Church, with its local headquarters at Canterbury.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000505","text":"It is, and ever has been, one and the same Church, \"all one man's sons,\" and that man, the Man Christ Jesus.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000506","text":"There is the Atlantic Ocean, the Indian Ocean, the Pacific Ocean: and yet there are not three oceans, but one ocean.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000507","text":"The Atlantic Ocean is not the Indian Ocean, nor is the Indian Ocean the Pacific Ocean: they are all together the one universal ocean--\"the ocean\".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000508","text":"But, after all, is not this a somewhat vague and nebulous conception of \"The Church\". If it is to go into all the world, how, from a business point of view, is this world-wide mission, in all its grandeur, to be accomplished? The answer is seen in our second name:--","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000509","text":"For business and administrative purposes, the world is divided into different nations.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000510","text":"For business and practical purposes, the Church follows the same method.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000511","text":"The Catholic Church is the channel of \"saving health to all nations\".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mental-health","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000512","text":"As at Pentecost the Church, typically, reached \"every {5} nation under heaven,\" so, age after age, must every nation receive the Church's message.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000513","text":"Thus, a National Church is the local presentment of the Catholic Church in the nation.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000514","text":"Newman puts it: \"The Holy Church throughout all the world is manifest and acts through what is called _in each country_, the Church Visible\".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000515","text":"As such, the duty of a National Church is two-fold.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000516","text":"It must teach the nation; it must feed the nation.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000517","text":"First: it is the function of the National Church to teach the nation.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000518","text":"It is to teach the nation religion--not to be taught religion by the nation.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000519","text":"It is no more the State's function to teach religion to the authorities of the National Church[3] than it is the {6} function of the nation to teach art to the authorities of the National Gallery.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000520","text":"Nor, again, is it the function of a National Church to teach the nation a _national_ religion; it is the office of the Church to teach the nation the _Catholic_ religion--to say, in common with the rest of Christendom, \"the Catholic religion is this,\" and none other.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000521","text":"Thus, the faith of a National Church is not the changing faith of a passing majority; it is the unchanging faith of a permanent Body, the Catholic Church.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000522","text":"Different ages may explain the faith in different ways; different nations may present it by different methods; different minds may interpret it in different lights; but it is one and the same faith, \"throughout all the world \".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:christianity","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000523","text":"A second function of the National Church is to feed the nation--to feed it with something which no State has to offer.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000524","text":"It is the hand of the Catholic Church dispensing to the nation \"something better than bread\".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000525","text":"When a priest is ordained, the Bishop bids him be \"a faithful dispenser of the Word of God, and of His holy Sacraments,\" and then gives him a local sphere of action \"in the congregation where thou shalt be lawfully appointed thereunto\".[4] Ideally, this {7} is carried out by the parochial system.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000526","text":"For administrative purposes, the National Church is divided into parishes, and thus brings the Scriptures and Sacraments to every individual in every nation in which the Catholic Church is established.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000527","text":"It is a grand and business-like conception.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000528","text":"All this is, or should be, going on in England, and we have now to ask when and by whom the Catholic Church, established in the Upper Chamber on the Day of Pentecost, was established in our country.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000529","text":"The Catholic Church was established, or re-established,[5] in this realm in the year {8} 597.[6] It was established by St.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000530","text":"Augustine, afterwards the first Archbishop of Canterbury.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000531","text":"This is the only evidence which, in such a case, is final.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000532","text":"If it is asked when, and by whom, our great public schools were established, the answer can be proved or disproved by documents.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000533","text":"It can all be proved by, and only by, documentary evidence.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000534","text":"Documents can prove that the Congregationalists established themselves in England in 1568, under Robert Brown; Quakers in 1660, under George Fox; Unitarians in 1719, under Samuel Clarke; Wesleyans in 1799, under a Wesleyan Conference.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000535","text":"Records exist proving that these various sects were established at these given dates, and no records exist proving that they were established at any other dates.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000536","text":"Records exist proving that it was established by Augustine, in England, in 597, and no records exist even hinting that it was established at any other time by anybody else.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000537","text":"A not unnatural mistake has sometimes arisen from the phrase \"_as by law_ established\".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000538","text":"No law ever established the Church of England.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000539","text":"The expression refers to the protection given by law to the Catholic Church in England, enabling it to do its duty in, and to, the country.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000540","text":"It tells of the legal recognition of the Church in the country long before the State existed; it expresses the legal declaration that the Church of England is not a mere insular sect, but part of the Universal Church \"throughout all the world\".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000541","text":"A State can, of course, if it chooses, establish and {11} endow any religion--Mohammedan, Hindoo, Christian, in a country.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000542","text":"It can establish Presbyterianism or Quakerism or Undenominationalism in England if it elects so to do; but none of these would be the Church of Jesus Christ established in the Upper Chamber on the Day of Pentecost.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000543","text":"But an authentic {12} record does exist proving the establishment of the Pentecostal Church in England in 597.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:truth","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000544","text":"It is this old Pentecostal Church that we speak of as the Church of England.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000545","text":"The Pope.[9] It was given by Pope Gregory in a letter to Augustine.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000546","text":"In this letter[10] Gregory speaks of three Churches--the {13} Church of Rome, the Church of Gaul, and the _Church of the English_, and he bids Augustine compile a Liturgy from the different Churches for the \"Use\" of the Church of England.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000547","text":"We see, then, that the Church of England is the Catholic Church in England.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000548","text":"As the Church of Ephesus is the Catholic Church in Ephesus, or the Church of Laodicea is the Catholic Church in Laodicea, or the Church of Thyatira the Catholic Church in Thyatira, so the Church of England is the Catholic Church in England.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000549","text":"Clement begins his Epistle to the Corinthians with, \"The _Church of God_, which is at Rome, to the _Church of God_ which is at Corinth,\" so might Archbishop Davidson write to the Italians, \"_The Church of God_, which is at Canterbury, to the _Church of God_, which is at Rome\".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000550","text":"It is in each case, \"the Church of God,\" \"made visible,\" in the nation where it is planted.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000551","text":"But, being national (being, for example, in England), it is, obviously, subject to the dangers, as well as the privileges, of national character, national temperament--and, in our case, national insularity.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000552","text":"The national presentment of the Catholic Church may err, and may err without losing its Catholicity.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000553","text":"The Church of England, \"as also the Church of Rome, hath erred\";[11] it has needed, it needs, it will need, reforming.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000554","text":"The name is very suggestive. It suggests two things--life and continuity.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000555","text":"Reformation is a sign of animation, for a dead organism cannot reform itself.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000556","text":"The reformed man, must be the same man, or he would not be a reformed man but somebody else.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000557","text":"It would have been quite possible, however ludicrous, to have established a new Church in the sixteenth century, but that would not have been a reformed Church, it would have been {15} another Church--the very last thing the Reformers contemplated.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000558","text":"A Reformed Church, then, is not the formation of a new Church, but the re-formation of the old Church.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000559","text":"How did the old Church of England reform itself? Roughly speaking, the English Reformation did two things. It affirmed something, and it denied something.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000560","text":"For instance, the Church of England affirmed that the Church in this country in the sixteenth century was one with the Church of the sixth century.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000561","text":"It affirmed that it was the very same Church that had been established in Palestine on the Day of Pentecost, and in this realm by Augustine in 597.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000562","text":"It reaffirmed its old national independence in things local just as it had affirmed it in the days of Pope Gregory, It re-affirmed its adherence to every doctrine[12] held by the undivided Church, without adding thereto, or taking therefrom.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000563","text":"Thus, the Reformation both affirmed and denied. It affirmed the constitutional rights of the Church as against the unconstitutional claims of the Pope, and it denied the unconstitutional claims of the State as against the constitutional rights of the Church.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:justice","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000564","text":"Much more, very much more, \"for weal or for woe,\" it did.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000565","text":"It made its mistakes, as every growing movement will do.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000566","text":"It is still growing, still making mistakes, still purging and pruning itself as it grows; and it is still asserting its right to reform itself where it {17} has gone wrong, and to return to the old ideal where it has departed from it.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000567","text":"And this old ideal is wrapped up in the sixth name:--","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000568","text":"Re-formation must be based upon its original formation if it would aim at real reform.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000569","text":"It is not necessarily a mechanical imitation of the past, but a genuine portrait of the permanent.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000570","text":"It is, then, to the Primitive Church that we must look for the principles of reformation.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000571","text":"If the meaning of a will is contested years after the testator's death, reference will be made, as far as possible, to the testator's contemporaries, or to writings which might best interpret his intentions.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mortality","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000572","text":"This is what the English Reformers of the sixteenth century tell us that they did.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000573","text":"They refer perpetually to the past; over and over again they send us to the \"ancient fathers,\"[13] as to those living and writing nearest to the days when the Church was established, and as most likely to know her mind.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000574","text":"They go back to what the \"Commination Service\" calls \"The Primitive Church\".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000575","text":"This \"Primitive Church\" is the Reformed Church now established in England.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000576","text":"{18} The Reformers themselves never meant it to be anything else, and would have been the first to protest against the unhistoric, low, and modern use of the word \"established\".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000577","text":"In this sense, they would have been the sturdiest of sturdy \"Protestants\".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000578","text":"And this word Protestant reminds us that there is one more name frequently given to the Church of England, but not included in our scheme, because found nowhere in the Prayer Book.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000579","text":"The term is a foreign one--not English. It comes from Germany and was given to the Lutherans in 1529, because they protested against an edict[14] forbidding them to regulate their own local ecclesiastical affairs, pending the decision of a General Council.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:justice","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000580","text":"It had nothing whatever to do with \"protesting\" against ceremonial. The ceremonial of the Church in Lutheran Germany is at least as carefully elaborated as that seen in the majority of English churches.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000581","text":"Later still, it has been applied to those who protest against the ancient interpretation of Prayer-Book teaching on the Sacraments and Ceremonial.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000582","text":"There is, it is true, a sense in which the name is fairly used to represent the views of all loyal English Churchmen.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:justice","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000583","text":"Every English Churchman protests against anything unhistoric or uncatholic.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000584","text":"The Church of England does protest against anything imposed by one part of the Church on any other part of the Church, apart from the consent of the whole Church.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000585","text":"It does protest against the claims of Italy or of any other nation to rule England, or to impose upon us, as _de fide_, anything exclusively Roman.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000586","text":"In this sense, Laud declared upon the scaffold that he died \"a true Protestant\"; in this sense, Nicholas Ferrar, founder of a Religious House in Huntingdonshire, called himself a Protestant; in this sense, we are all Protestants, and in this sense we are not ashamed of our unhistoric name.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000587","text":"_Elect from every nation,_ _Yet one all o'er the Earth._","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000588","text":"[2] The primary meaning of the word Catholic seems to refer to world-wide extension.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000589","text":"Augustine teaches that it means \"Universal\" as opposed to particular, and says that \"The Church is called Catholic because it is spread throughout the whole world\".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000590","text":"Cyril of Jerusalem says: \"The Church is called Catholic because it extends throughout the whole world, from one end of the Earth to the other,\" and he adds, \"because it teaches universally all the doctrines which men ought to know\" (\"Catechetical Lectures,\" xviii.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000591","text":"[3] \"Foul fall the day,\" writes Mr. Gladstone, \"when the persons of this world shall, on whatever pretext, take into their uncommissioned hands the manipulation of the religion of our Lord and Saviour.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000592","text":"[4] Service for \"The Ordering of Priests\".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000593","text":"[5] There was, of course, an ancient British Church long before the sixth century, and there is evidence that it existed in the middle of the second century.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000594","text":"It sent bishops to the Council of Arles in 314, and there is a church at Canterbury in which Queen Bertha's chaplain celebrated some twenty-five years before the coming of Augustine.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000595","text":"But its origin is shrouded in mystery, and it had been practically extinguished by Jutes, Saxons, and Angles before Augustine arrived.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000596","text":"\"Of the ancient British Church,\" writes Bishop Stubbs, in an unpublished letter, \"we must be content to admit that history tells us next to nothing, and that what glimmerings of truth we think we can discover in legend grow fainter and fainter the more closely they are examined.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:truth","theme:wisdom","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000597","text":"Authentic records there are none.\" Some ascribe the first preaching of the Gospel in Britain to St.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:truth","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000598","text":"Simon Zelotes, and the monks of Glastonbury ascribe it to their founder, Joseph of Arimathea, who was, they say, sent to Britain by St.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000599","text":"Bright to \"The Guardian,\" 14 March, 1888, and see \"Letters and Memoirs of William Bright,\" pp.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000600","text":"[6] i.e. the English, as distinct from the British Church.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000601","text":"[8] A State can, of course, _endow_, as well as establish, any form of religion it selects.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000602","text":"But the State has never endowed the Church of England, and it can only disendow it in the sense that it can rob it of its own endowments--just as it can, by Act of Parliament, rob any business man of his money.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000603","text":"At the Great Rebellion, the Church of England was, in this sense, disestablished and disendowed.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000604","text":"By the Act of Uniformity of Charles II, it was reinstated into the rights and liberties from which it had been deposed.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:justice","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000605","text":"But it remained the same Church which Augustine established in England all the time.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000606","text":"Its reinstatement no more made the Church a new Church, than the restoration of Charles II made the monarchy a new monarchy.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000607","text":"[9] It is sometimes asked, Does not the presence of the Bishops in the House of Lords constitute an Established Church?","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000608","text":"Representatives from all the sects might, and some probably will, sit there without either making their sect the established Church of the country, or unmaking the Catholic Church the Church of the country.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000609","text":"Bishops have sat in the House of Lords ever since there has been a House of Lords to sit in, but neither their exclusion, nor the inclusion of non-Bishops, would disestablish the Church of England.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000610","text":"It is also asked, do not the Prime Ministers make the Bishops? Prime Ministers, as we shall see, do not _make_ but _nominate_ the Bishops.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000611","text":"[10] Augustine is worried, as we are worried, by the variety of customs in different Churches, and asks Pope Gregory \"why one custom of masses is observed in the Holy Roman Church and another in the Church of the Gallic Provinces\".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000612","text":"\"My brother knows,\" replied Gregory, \"the custom of the Roman Church in which he was brought up.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000613","text":"Choose, then, from each individual Church things pious, religious, righteous, and having, as it were, collected them into a volume, deposit them with the minds of the English as their custom, their Use.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000614","text":"[14] The Edict of the Diet (or Council) of Spires.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000615","text":"For the purpose of these lectures, we will select two:--","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000616","text":"(1) _The Bible_, the possession of the whole Church.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000617","text":"(2) _The Prayer Book_, the possession of the Church of England.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000618","text":"And notice: _first, the Church; then, the Bible_--first the Society, then its Publications; first the Writers; then the Writings; first the Messenger, then the Message; first the Agent, then the Agencies.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000619","text":"Preaching, not writing, was the Apostolic method.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000620","text":"Oral teaching preceded the written word.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000621","text":"Then, later on, lest this oral teaching should be lost, forgotten, or misquoted, it was gradually committed to {22} manuscript, and its \"good tidings\" published in writing for the Church's children.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000622","text":"It is very important to remember this order (\"first the Church, and then the Bible\"), because thousands of souls lived and died long before the New Testament was written.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000623","text":"The earliest books of the New Testament (the First and Second Epistles to the Thessalonians) were not written for twenty years after the Day of Pentecost; the earliest Gospel (St.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000624","text":"Mark) was not committed to writing before A.D.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000625","text":"And, even if the Bible had been written earlier, few could have read it; and even then few could have possessed it.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000626","text":"It was a rare book, wholly out of reach of \"the people\".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000627","text":"The first Bible was not printed until 1445.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000628","text":"But, thank God, the Church, which wrote the book, could teach without the book; and we may be sure that no single soul was lost for the want of what it could not possess.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000629","text":"Irenaeus, writing in the second century, \"they received, from the Church, teaching sufficient for the salvation of their souls.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000630","text":"Then, again, the Church alone could decide which books were, and which books were not, \"the Scriptures\".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:solitude","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000631","text":"The society authorizes its publications.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000632","text":"It affixes {23} its seal only to the books it has issued.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000633","text":"It affixes its seal to the books we now know as the Bible.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000634","text":"Paul's Epistles to the Corinthians are part of the Bible, and that St.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000635","text":"Clement's Epistle to the Corinthians is not part of the Bible?","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000636","text":"Because, and only because, the Church has so decided.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000637","text":"If we had lived in the days of persecution it would have made a considerable difference to us whether this or that sacred book was included in the Christian Scriptures.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000638","text":"Thus, when the early Christians were ordered by Diocletian to \"bring out their books,\" and either burn them or die for them, it became a matter of vital importance to know which these books were.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000639","text":"Only the society which published them, only the Church.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000640","text":"Again, the Church, and only the Church, is the final _interpreter_ of the Bible--it is the \"_witness_ and keeper of holy writ\".[1] The society which publishes a statement must be the final interpreter of that statement.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000641","text":"Probably no book ever published needed authoritative interpretation more than the Bible.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000642","text":"We call it \"the book of {24} peace\"; it is in reality a book of war.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000643","text":"No book has spread more discord than the Bible.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000644","text":"Every sect in the world quotes the Bible as the source and justification of its existence.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000645","text":"Men, equally learned, devout, prayerful, deduce the most opposite conclusions from the very same words.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000646","text":"Two men, we will say, honestly and earnestly seek to know what the Bible teaches about Baptismal Regeneration, or the Blessed Sacrament.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:truth","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000647","text":"They have exactly the same _data_ to go upon, precisely the same statements before them; yet, from the same premises, they will deduce a diametrically opposite conclusion.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000648","text":"Hence, party wrangling, and sectarian bitterness; hence, the confusion of tongues, which has changed our Zion into Babel.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000649","text":"Indeed, as we all know, so sharp was the contention in the thirteenth and sixteenth centuries, that translations of the Bible were actually forbidden by two local Church Councils.[2]","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000650","text":"An interpreter is as much needed now, as in the days of the Ethiopian Eunuch.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000651","text":"\"_How_ readest thou?\"[3] is a question second only in {25} importance (if, indeed, it is second) to \"_What_ is written?\" Upon \"how\" we read, will very largely depend the value of \"what\" we read.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000652","text":"We go, then, to the Church to interpret the book which it gave us.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000653","text":"And notice--to say this, is not to disparage the Scriptures because we exalt the Church.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000654","text":"It is to put both Church and Scriptures in their true, historical place.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000655","text":"We do not disparage a publication because we exalt the society which issues that publication; rather, we honour the one by exalting the other.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000656","text":"Thus, when we say that the creeds interpret the Bible, we do not disparage the Bible because we exalt the creeds, any more than we disparage the Church when we say that the Bible proves the creeds.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000657","text":"Take the \"Virgin Birth,\" as a single illustration.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000658","text":"Are we to believe that our Blessed Lord was \"born of the Virgin Mary\"?","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000659","text":"The Church taught it before the Bible recorded it; the Bible recorded it because the Church taught it.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000660","text":"For us, as Churchmen, the matter is settled once and for all by the Apostles' Creed.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000661","text":"Here we have the official and authoritative teaching of the Catholic Church, as proved by the New Testament; \"born of the Virgin Mary\".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000662","text":"It is this Bible, the Church's Manual of doctrine and devotion, that we are to think of.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000663","text":"We will think of it under five familiar names:--","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000664","text":"(I) The Scriptures. (II) The Bible. (III) The Word of God. (IV) Inspiration. (V) Revelation.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000665","text":"This was the earliest name by which the Bible was known--the name by which it was called for the first 1200 years in Church history.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000666","text":"It was so named by the Latin Fathers in the fifth century, and it means, of course, \"The Writings\".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000667","text":"These \"Scriptures,\" or \"Writings,\" were not, as the plural form of the word reminds us, one book, but many books, afterwards gathered into one book.[4] They were a library of separate books, called by St.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000668","text":"Irenaeus \"The Divine Library\"--perhaps {27} the best and most descriptive name the Bible ever had.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000669","text":"This library consists of sixty-six books, not all written at one period, or for one age, but extending over a period of, at least, 1200 years.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000670","text":"The original copies of these writings, or Scriptures, have not yet been discovered, though we have extant three very early copies of them, written \"by hand\". These are known as the _Alexandrine_ manuscript (or Codex), the _Vatican_ manuscript, and the _Sinaitic_ manuscript. Where may they be found?","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000671","text":"One, dating from the latter part of the fourth, or the early part of the fifth century, is in the British Museum--a priceless treasure, which comparatively few have taken the trouble to go and see.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000672","text":"It is known as the _Alexandrine_ manuscript, and was presented to Charles I by the Patriarch of Constantinople in 1628.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000673","text":"It consists of four volumes, three of which contain nearly all the Old Testament, and parts of the Apocrypha, and a fourth, containing a large part of the New Testament.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000674","text":"A second manuscript, dating from the fourth century, is in the Vatican Library in Rome, and is, therefore, known as the _Vatican_ manuscript. {28} It contains nearly the whole of both the Old and New Testaments, and of the Apocrypha.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000675","text":"The third manuscript, dating also from the fourth century, is in the Imperial Library at St. Petersburg. It was discovered by Prof. Tischendorf, in 1859, in a basket of fragments, destined to be burned, in the Monastery of St. Catherine on _Mount Sinai_; hence it is called the _Sinaitic_ manuscript.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000676","text":"collections of the Bible as yet discovered--and strange stories, of mystic beauty, and, it may be, of weird persecution, they could tell if only they could speak.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000677","text":"Other manuscripts we have--copies of ancient manuscripts; versions of ancient manuscripts; translations of ancient manuscripts; texts of ancient manuscripts.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000678","text":"So they come down the ages, till, at last, we reach our own \"Revised Version,\" probably the most accurate and trustworthy version in existence.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:relationships","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000679","text":"\"The Scriptures,\" or \"the Writings,\" then, consist of many books, and in this very fact, they tell their own tale--the tale of diversity in unity.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000680","text":"They were written for divers ages, divers intellects, divers nations, in divers languages, by divers authors or compilers.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000681","text":"In, and through the Scriptures, \"God, at sundry times, and in divers manners, spake in time past unto the fathers by the prophets\"; and in, and through them, He \"hath in these last days, spoken unto us by His Son\".[5]","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000682","text":"Time passes, and these sixty-six books, written at different periods, in different styles, in different dialects, are gathered together in one book, called \"The Book,\" or The Bible.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000683","text":"It was so named by the Greek Fathers in the thirteenth century, hundreds of years after its earliest name, \"The Scriptures\".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000684","text":"The word is derived from the Greek _Biblia_, books, and originally meant the Egyptian _papyrus_ (or _paper-reed_) from which paper was first made.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000685","text":"A \"bible,\" then, was originally any book made of paper, and {30} the name was afterwards given to the \"Book of Books\"--\"_The Bible_\".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000686","text":"Here, then, are sixty-six volumes bound together in one volume.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000687","text":"If \"The Scriptures,\" or scattered writings, speak of diversity in unity, \"The Bible,\" or collected writings, tells of unity in diversity.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000688","text":"Each separate book has its own most sacred message, while one central, unifying thought dominates all--the Incarnate Son of God.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000689","text":"The Old Testament writings foretell His coming (\"They are they which testify of me\"[6]); the New Testament writings proclaim His Advent (\"The Word was made flesh and dwelt among us\"[7]).","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000690","text":"_Many the tongues,_ _The theme is one,_ _The glory of the Eternal Son._","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000691","text":"Take away that central Figure, and both the background of the Old Testament and the foreground of the New become dull, sunless, colourless. Reinstate that central Figure, and book after book, roll after roll, volume after volume, becomes bright, sunny, intelligible.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000692","text":"In what sense is the Bible the Word of God? Almost any answer must hurt some, and almost every answer must disappoint others. For a time, the \"old school\" and the \"new school\" must bear with each other, neither counting itself \"to have apprehended,\" but each pressing forward to attain results.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000693","text":"In between these two extremes, there is another class, which holds that the Bible is the Word of God, and that just because it is the Word of God, it is--above all other books--an \"open Bible,\" a {32} book open for sacred study, devout debate, reverent criticism.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000694","text":"The first class holds that every one of the 925,877 words in the Bible is as literally \"God's Word\" as if no human hand had written it.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000695","text":"Thus, Dean Burgon writes: \"Every word of it, every chapter of it, every syllable of it, every letter of it, is the direct utterance of the Most High....","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000696","text":"Every syllable is just what it would have been ...","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000697","text":"_without the intervention of any human agent_.\" This, of course, creates hopeless difficulties.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000698","text":"For instance, in the Authorized Version (to take but one single version) there are obvious insertions, such as St.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000699","text":"9-20, which may not be \"the Word of God\" at all.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000700","text":"There are obvious misquotations, such as in the seven variations in St.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000701","text":"Stephen's speech.[8] There are obvious doubts about accurate translations, where the marginal notes give alternative readings.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000702","text":"There are obvious mistakes by modern printers, as there were by ancient copyists.[9] There are three versions of the Psalms now in use (the Authorized Version, the Revised Version, and the Prayer-Book Version), all differing {33} from each other.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000703","text":"The translators of the Authorized Version wish, they say, to make \"_one more exact_ translation of the Scriptures,\" and one-third of the translators of the Revised Version constantly differs from the other two-thirds.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000704","text":"Here, clearly, the human agent is at work.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000705","text":"Then there are those who, perhaps from a natural reaction, deny that any word in the Bible is in any special sense \"the Word of God\".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000706","text":"But this, too, creates hopeless difficulties, and satisfies no serious student.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000707","text":"If the Bible is, in no special sense, the Word of God, there is absolutely no satisfactory explanation of its unique position and career in history.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000708","text":"It is a great fact which remains unaccounted for.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000709","text":"Moreover, no evidence exists which suggests that the writers who call it the Word of God were either frauds or dupes, or that they were deceived when they proclaimed \"_God_ spake these words, and said\"; or, \"Thus saith _the Lord_\"; or, \"The Revelation of _Jesus Christ_ by His servant John\".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:leadership","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000710","text":"There must, upon the lowest ground, be a sense in which it may be truly said that the Bible is the Word of God as no other book is.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000711","text":"This we may consider under the fourth name, Inspiration.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000712","text":"What do we mean by the word? The Church has nowhere defined it, and we are not tied to any one interpretation; but the Bible itself suggests a possible meaning.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000713","text":"It is the Word of God heard through the voice of man.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000714","text":"Think of some such expression as: \"_The Revelation of Jesus Christ which God gave by His angel unto His servant John_\" (Rev.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:leadership","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000715","text":"Here two facts are stated: (1) The revelation is from Jesus Christ; (2) It was given through a human agent--John.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000716","text":"Again: \"_Holy men of old spake as they were moved by the Holy Ghost_\" (2 Pet.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000717","text":"The Holy Ghost moved them; they spake: the speakers, not the writings, were inspired.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000718","text":"Again: \"_As He spake by the mouth of His holy Prophets_\"[10] (St.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000719","text":"He spake; but He spake through the mouthpiece of the human agent.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000720","text":"And once again, as the Collect for the second Sunday in Advent tells us, it is the \"_blessed Lord Who (hast) caused all Holy Scriptures to be written_\".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000721","text":"God was the initiating {35} cause of writings: man was the inspired writer.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000722","text":"Each messenger received the message, but each passed it on in his own way.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000723","text":"It was with each as it was with Haggai: \"Then spake Haggai, the _Lord's messenger_ in the _Lord's message_\" (Haggai i.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000724","text":"The message was Divine, though the messenger was human; the message was infallible, though the messenger was fallible; the vessel was earthen, though the contents were golden.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000725","text":"In this unique sense, the Bible is indeed \"the Word of God\".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000726","text":"It is the \"Word of God,\" delivered in the words of man.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000727","text":"Sanday puts it, the Bible is, at once, both human and Divine; not less Divine because thoroughly human, and not less human because essentially Divine.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000728","text":"We need not necessarily parcel it out and say such and such things are human and such and such things are Divine, though there are instances in which we may do this, and the Scriptures would justify us in so doing.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000729","text":"There will be much in Holy Scripture which is at once very human and very Divine.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000730","text":"The two aspects are not incompatible with each other; rather, they are intimately united.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000731","text":"Look at them in one light, and you will see the one; look at them in another light, and you will see {36} the other.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000732","text":"But the substance of that which gives these different impressions is one and the same.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000733","text":"It is from no irreverence, but because of the over-towering importance of the book, that the best scholars (devout, prayerful scholars, as well as the reverse) have given the best of their lives to the study of its text, its history, its writers, its contents.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000734","text":"Their criticism has, as we know, been classified under three heads:--","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000735","text":"(1) Lower, or _textual_ criticism. (2) Higher, or _documentary_ criticism. (3) Historical, or _contemporary_ criticism.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000736","text":"_Lower criticism_ seeks for, and studies, the best and purest text obtainable--the text nearest to the original, from which fresh translations can be made.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000737","text":"_Higher criticism_ seeks for, and studies, documents: it deals with the authenticity of different books, the date at which they were written, the names of their authors.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:truth","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000738","text":"_Historical criticism_ seeks for, and studies, _data_ relating to the history of the times when each book was written, and the light thrown upon that history by recent discoveries (e.g. in archaeology, and excavations in Palestine).","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000739","text":"No very definite results have yet been reached on many points of criticism, and, on many of them, scholars have had again and again to reverse their conclusions.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000740","text":"We are still only _en route_, and are learning more and more to possess our souls in patience, and to wait awhile for anything in the nature of finality.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000741","text":"Meanwhile, the living substance is unshaken and untouched.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000742","text":"This living substance, entrusted to living men, is the revelation of God to man, and leads us to our last selected name--Revelation.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:relationships","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000743","text":"The Bible is the revelation of the Blessed Trinity to man--of God the Son, by God the Father, through God the Holy Ghost.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000744","text":"It is the revelation of God to man, and in man.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000745","text":"First, it reveals God _to_ man--\"pleased as Man with man to dwell\".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000746","text":"In it, God stands in front of man, and, through the God-Man, shows him what God is like.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000747","text":"It reveals God as the \"pattern on the mount,\" for man to copy on the plain.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000748","text":"But it does more than this: it reveals God _in_ man.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000749","text":"Paul writes: \"It pleased God to reveal His Son _in_ me\";[11] and again, \"God hath {38} shined _in_ our hearts\".[12] The Bible reveals to me that Jesus, the revelation of the Father, through the Eternal Spirit, dwells in me, as well as outside me.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:animism","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000750","text":"He is a power within, as well as a pattern without.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:solitude","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000751","text":"The Bible reveals God's purpose _for_ man.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000752","text":"There is no such other revelation of that purpose.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000753","text":"You cannot deduce God's purpose either in man's life, or in his twentieth century environment.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000754","text":"It can only be fully deduced from Revelation.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000755","text":"Man may seem temporarily to defeat God's purpose, to postpone its accomplishment; but Revelation (and nothing but Revelation) proclaims that \"the Word of the Lord standeth sure,\" and that God's primal purpose is God's final purpose.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000756","text":"Lastly, the Bible is the revelation of a future state. Things begun here will be completed there. As such, it gives man a hope on which to build a belief, and a belief on which to found a hope.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000757","text":"We must believe, For still we hope That, in a world of larger scope, What here is faithfully begun Will be completed, not undone.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000758","text":"Thus, we may, perhaps, find in these five familiar names, brief headings for leisure thoughts.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000759","text":"In them, we see the _Scriptures_, or many books, gathered together into one book called _The Book_.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000760","text":"In this book, we see the _Word of God_ delivered to men by men, and these men _inspired_ by God to be the living _media_ of the _Revelation_ of God to man.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000761","text":"Our next selected book will be the Church of England Prayer Book.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000762","text":"[2] The Council of Toulouse, 1229, and the Council of Trent, 1545-63.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000763","text":"[4] The first division of the Bible into _chapters_ is attributed either to Cardinal Hugo, for convenience in compiling his Concordance of the Vulgate (about 1240), or to Stephen Langton, Archbishop of Canterbury (about 1228), to facilitate quotation.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:leadership","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000764","text":"_Verses_ were introduced into the New Testament by Robert Stephens, 1551.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000765","text":"It is said that he did the work on a journey from Paris to Lyons.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000766","text":"[9] The University Presses offer L1 1s. for every such hitherto undiscovered inaccuracy brought to their notice.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000767","text":"[10] This is the Church's description of Inspiration in the Nicene Creed: \"Who spake by the Prophets\".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:islam","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000768","text":"We now come to the second of the Church's books selected for discussion--the Prayer Book.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000769","text":"The English Prayer Book is the local presentment of the Church's Liturgies for the English people.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000770","text":"Each part of the Church has its own Liturgy, differing in detail, language, form; but all teaching the same faith, all based upon the same rule laid down by Gregory for Augustine's guidance.[1] Thus, there is the Liturgy of St.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000771","text":"A National Church is within her rights when she compiles a Liturgy for National Use, provided that it is in harmony with the basic Liturgies of the Undivided Church.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:justice","theme:love","theme:solitude","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000772","text":"She has {41} as much right to her local \"Use,\" with its rules and ritual, as a local post office has to its own local regulations, provided it does not infringe any universal rule of the General Post Office.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000773","text":"For example, a National Church has a perfect right to say in what language her Liturgy shall be used.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000774","text":"When the English Prayer Book orders her Liturgy to be said in \"the vulgar,\"[3] or common, \"tongue\" of the people, she is not infringing, but exercising a local right which belongs to her as part of the Church Universal.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000775","text":"This is what the English Church has done in the English Prayer Book.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000776","text":"It is this Prayer Book that we are now to consider.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000777","text":"We will try to review, or get a bird's-eye view of it as a whole, rather than attempt to go into detail.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000778","text":"And, as the best reviewer is the one who lets a book tell its own story, and reads the author's meaning out of it rather than his own theories into it, we will let the book, as far as possible, speak for itself.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000779","text":"Now, in reviewing a book, the reviewer will probably look at three things: the title, the preface, the contents.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000780","text":"\"_The Book of Common Prayer, and Administration of the Sacraments and other Rites and Ceremonies of the Church, according to the Use of the Church of England._\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000781","text":"Here are three clear statements: (1) it is \"The Book of Common Prayer \"; (2) it is the local \"directory\" for the \"_Administration_ of the Sacraments of the Church,\" i.e. of the Universal Church; (3) this directory is called the \"Use of the Church of England\". Think of each statement in turn.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000782","text":"(1) _It is \"The Book of Common Prayer\"_.--\"Common Prayer\"[4] was the name given to public worship in the middle of the sixteenth century.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000783","text":"The Book of Common Prayer is the volume in which the various services were gathered together for common use.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000784","text":"As the Bible is one book made up of sixty-six books, so the Prayer Book is one book made up of six books.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000785","text":"These books, revised and abbreviated for English \"Use,\" were:--","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000786","text":"(1) The Pontifical. (2) The Missal. (3) The Gospels. (4) The Gradual. (5) The Breviary. (6) The Manual.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000787","text":"Before the invention of printing, these books were written in manuscript, and were too heavy to carry about bound together in one volume.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000788","text":"Each, therefore, was carried by the user separately.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000789","text":"Thus, when the Bishop, or _Pontifex_, was ordaining or confirming, he carried with him a separate book containing the offices for Ordination and Confirmation; and, because it contained the offices used by the Bishop, or _Pontiff_, it was called the _Pontifical_.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000790","text":"When a priest wished to celebrate the Holy Eucharist, he used a separate book called \"The Missal\" (from the Latin _Missa_, a Mass[5]).","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000791","text":"When, in the Eucharist, the deacon read the Gospel for the day, he read it from a separate book called \"The Gospels\".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000792","text":"When he {44} went in procession to read it, the choir sang scriptural phrases out of a separate book called \"The Gradual\" (from the Latin _gradus_, a step), because they were sung in _gradibus_, i.e.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000793","text":"upon the steps of the pulpit, or rood-loft, from which the Gospel was read.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000794","text":"When the clergy said their offices at certain fixed \"Hours,\" they used a separate book called \"The Breviary\" (from the Latin _brevis_, short), because it contained the brief, or short, writings which constituted the office, out of which our English Matins and Evensong were practically formed.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000795","text":"When services for such as needed Baptism, Matrimony, Unction, Burial, were required, some light book that could easily be carried _in the hand_ was used, and this was called \"The Manual\" (from the Latin _manus_, a hand).","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000796","text":"These six books, written in Latin, were, in 1549, shortened, and, with various alterations, translated into English, bound in one volume, which is called \"The Book of Common Prayer\".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000797","text":"Alterations, some good and some bad, have from time to time been adopted, and revisions made; but the Prayer Book is now the same in substance as it always has been--a faithful reproduction, in all essentials, of the worship and {45} teaching of the Undivided Church.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:leadership","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000798","text":"As we all know, a further revision is now contemplated.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:leadership","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000799","text":"All agree that it is needed; all would like to amend the Prayer Book in one direction or another; but there is a sharp contention as to whether this is the time for revision, and what line the revision should take.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:leadership","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000800","text":"The nature of the last attempted revision, in the reign of William III,[6] will make the liturgical student profoundly grateful that that proposed revision was rejected, and will suggest infinite caution before entrusting a new revision to any but proved experts, and liturgical specialists.[7]","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:gratitude","theme:leadership","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:relationships","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000801","text":"Whatever changes are made, they should, at least, be based on two principles--permanence and progress.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000802","text":"The essence of progress is loyalty to the past.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000803","text":"Nothing should be touched that is a permanent part of the Ancient Office Books; nothing should be omitted, or added, that is outside the teaching of the Universal Church.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000804","text":"For the immediate present, we would ask that the {46} Prayer Book should be left untouched, but that an Appendix, consisting of many unauthorized services now in use, should be \"put forth by authority,\" i.e.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000805","text":"(2) _The Administration of the Sacraments of the Church_.--The Sacraments are the treasures of the whole Church; the way in which they may be \"administered\" is left to the decision of that part of the Church in which they are administered.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000806","text":"Take, once again, the question of language.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000807","text":"One part of the Church has as much right to administer the Sacraments in English as another part has to administer them in Latin, or another part in Greek.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000808","text":"For instance, the words, \"This is My Body\" in the English Liturgy are quite as near to the original as \"_Hoc est Corpus Meum_\" is in the Latin Liturgy.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000809","text":"Each Church has a right to make its own regulations for its own people.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000810","text":"Provided the essence of the Sacrament is not touched, the addition or omission of particular rites and ceremonies does not affect the validity of the Sacrament.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000811","text":"For, the title of the Prayer Book carefully distinguishes between \"The Church\" and \"The Church of England,\" \"the _Sacraments_\" and the \"_administration_ of the Sacraments\".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000812","text":"It is for {47} _administrative purposes_ that there is an English \"Use,\" i.e.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000813","text":"an English method of administering the Sacraments of the Universal Church.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000814","text":"It is this use which the title-page calls:--","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000815","text":"(3) _The Use of the Church of England_.--This \"Use\" may vary at different times, and even in different dioceses.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000816","text":"We read of one \"Use\" in the Diocese of York; another in the Diocese of Sarum, or Salisbury; another in the Diocese of Hereford; another in the Diocese of Bangor; and so on.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000817","text":"Indeed, there were so many different Uses at one time that, for the sake of unity, one Use was substituted for many; and that Use, sufficient in all essentials, is found in our \"Book of Common Prayer \".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000818","text":"It was written, in 1661, by Bishop Sanderson, and amended by the Upper House of Convocation.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000819","text":"What, we ask, do these preface-writers say about the book to which they gave their _imprimatur_?","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000820","text":"First, they state their position. They have no intention whatever of writing a new book. Their aim is to adapt old books to new needs. {48} Adaptation, not invention, is their aim. Four times in their short Preface they refer us to \"the ancient Fathers\" as their guides.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:leadership","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000821","text":"Two dangers, they tell us, have to be avoided.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000822","text":"In compiling a Liturgy from Ancient Sources, one danger will be that of \"too much stiffness in _refusing_\" new matter--i.e.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000823","text":"letting a love of permanence spoil progress: another, and opposite danger, will be \"too much easiness in _admitting_\" any variation--i.e.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000824","text":"letting a love of progress spoil permanence.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000825","text":"\"It hath been the wisdom of the Church of England to keep the mean between the two extremes,\" when either extreme runs away from the \"faith once delivered to the Saints \".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000826","text":"Another object they had in view was to give a prominent place to Holy Scripture. \"So that here,\" they say, \"you have an Order for Prayer, and for the reading of the Holy Scriptures, much agreeable to the mind and purpose of _the old Fathers_.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000827","text":"Next, they deal with the principles which underlie all ritualism.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000828","text":"Finally, whilst wishing to ease men from the oppressive burden of a multitude of ceremonies, \"whereof St.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000829","text":"Augustine, in his time, complained,\" they assert the right of each Church to make its own ritual-rules (in conformity with the rules of the whole Church), provided that it imposes them on no one else.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000830","text":"\"And in these our doings we condemn no other nations, nor prescribe anything but to our own people only; for we think it {50} convenient that every country should use such ceremonies as they shall think best.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000831","text":"It is necessary to call attention to all this, because few Church people seem to know anything about the intentions, objects, and principles of the compilers, as stated by themselves in the Prayer Book Preface.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000832","text":"These a reviewer might briefly deal with under three heads--Doctrine, Discipline, and Devotion.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000833","text":"The importance of this cannot be exaggerated.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000834","text":"The English Prayer Book is, for the ordinary Churchman, a standard of authority when theological doctors differ.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000835","text":"The _Prayer Book_ is the Court of Appeal from the pulpit--just as the Undivided Church is the final Court of Appeal from the Prayer Book.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000836","text":"Many a man is honestly puzzled and worried at the charge so frequently levelled at the Church of England, that one preacher flatly contradicts another, and that what is taught as truth in one church is denied as heresy in another.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:truth","theme:wisdom","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000837","text":"This is, of course, by no {51} means peculiar to the Church of England, but it is none the less a loss to the unity of Christendom.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:grief","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000838","text":"The whole mischief arises from treating the individual preacher as if he were the Book of Common Prayer.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000839","text":"It is to the Prayer Book, not to the Pulpit, that we must go to prove what is taught.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000840","text":"For instance, I go into one church, and I hear one preacher deny the doctrine of Baptismal Regeneration; I go into another, and I hear the same doctrine taught as the very essence of The Faith.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000841","text":"I ask, in despair, what does the Church of England teach?","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000842","text":"I am not bound to believe either teacher, until I have tested his utterances by some authorized book.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000843","text":"What does the Church of England Prayer Book--not this or that preacher--say is the teaching of the Church of England?","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000844","text":"In the case quoted, this is the Prayer Book answer: \"Seeing now, dearly beloved brethren, that _this child is regenerate_\".[8] Here is something clear, crisp, definite.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000845","text":"It is the authorized expression of the belief of the Church of England in common with the whole Catholic Church.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000846","text":"In one, conversion is almost sneered at, or, at least, apologized for; in another, it is taught with all the fervour of a personal experience.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000847","text":"What does the Church of England teach about it?","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000848","text":"Open it at the Feast of the Conversion of St.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000849","text":"Paul, or at the third Collect for Good Friday, and you will hear a trumpet which gives no uncertain sound.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000850","text":"Or, I am wondering and worried about Confession and Absolution.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000851","text":"What does the Church of England teach about them?","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000852","text":"One preacher says one thing, one another.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000853","text":"But what is the Church of England's authoritative utterance on the subject?","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000854","text":"Open your Prayer Book, and you will see: you will find that, with the rest of the Christian Church, she provides for both, in public and in private, for the strong, and for the sick.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000855","text":"This, at least, is the view an honest onlooker will take of our position.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:truth","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000856","text":"A common-sense Nonconformist minister, wishing to teach his people and to get at facts, studies the English Prayer Book.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000857","text":"This is his conclusion: \"Free Churchmen,\" he writes, \"dissent from much of the teaching of the Book of Common Prayer.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000858","text":"In {53} the service of Baptism, expressions are used which naturally lead persons to regard it as a means of salvation.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000859","text":"God is asked to 'sanctify this water to the mystical washing away of sin'.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000860","text":"After Baptism, God is thanked for having 'regenerated the child with His Holy Spirit'.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000861","text":"It is called the 'laver of regeneration,' by which the child, being born in sin, is received into the number of God's children.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000862","text":"In the Catechism, the child is taught to say of Baptism, 'wherein I was made the child of God'.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000863","text":"It is said to be 'generally necessary to salvation,' and the rubric declares that children who are baptized, and die before they commit actual sin, are undoubtedly saved'.\"[9] What could be a fairer statement of the Prayer-Book teaching?","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:justice","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000864","text":"And he goes on: \"In the visitation of the sick, if the sick person makes a confession of his sins, and 'if he heartily and humbly desire it,' the Priest is bidden to absolve him.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000865","text":"I absolve thee from all thy sins in the Name of the Father, and of the Son, and of the Holy Ghost'.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000866","text":"In the Ordination Service, the Bishop confers the power of Absolution upon the Priest.\" Nothing could be fairer.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:justice","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000867","text":"It is precisely what the Church {54} of England _does_ teach in her authorized formularies which Archbishop Cranmer gathered together from the old Service-books of the ancient Church of England.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000868","text":"The pulpit passes: the Prayer Book remains.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000869","text":"The Prayer Book deals with principles, rather than with details--though details have their place.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000870","text":"It is a book of discipline, \"as well for the body as the soul\".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000871","text":"It disciplines the body for the sake of the soul; it disciplines the soul for the sake of the body.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000872","text":"Now it tightens, now it relaxes, the human bow.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000873","text":"For example, in the _Table of Feasts and Fasts_, it lays down one principle which underlies all bodily and spiritual discipline--the need of training to obtain self-control.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000874","text":"The _principle_ laid down is that I am to discipline myself at stated times and seasons, in order that I may not be undisciplined at any times or seasons.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000875","text":"I am to rejoice as a duty on certain days, that I may live in the joy of the Redeemed on other days.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000876","text":"Feasts and Fasts have a meaning, and I cannot deliberately ignore the Prayer-Book Table without suffering loss.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:grief","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000877","text":"It is the same with the rubrical directions as to {55} ritual.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000878","text":"I am ordered to stand when praising, to kneel when praying.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000879","text":"The underlying _principle_ is that I am not to do things in my own way, without regard to others, but to do them in an orderly way, and as one of many.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000880","text":"I am learning to sink the individual in the society.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000881","text":"So with the directions as to vestments--whether they are the Eucharistic vestments, ordered by the \"Ornaments Rubric,\" or the preacher's Geneva gown not ordered anywhere.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000882","text":"The _principle_ laid down is, special things for special occasions; all else is a matter of degree.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000883","text":"One form of Ceremonial will appeal to one temperament, a different form to another.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000884","text":"Bright, \"and I own that Lights and Vestments give me real pleasure.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000885","text":"The principle {56} which says, \"You shan't have it because I don't like it,\" or, \"You shall have it because I do like it,\" leads to all sorts of confusion.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000886","text":"Liddon says: \"When men know what the revelation of God in His Blessed Son really is, all else follows in due time--reverence on one side and charity on the other\".[11]","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000887","text":"Reading the Prayer Book as it stands, from Matins to the Consecration of an Archbishop, no reviewer could miss its devotional beauty.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000888","text":"It is, perhaps, a misfortune that the most beautiful Office of the Christian Church, the Eucharistic Office, should come in the middle, instead of at the beginning, of our Prayer Book, first in order as first in importance.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000889","text":"Its character, though capable of much enrichment, reminds us of how much devotional beauty the Prayer Book has from ancient sources.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:beauty","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000890","text":"In our jealous zeal for more beauty we are, perhaps, apt to underrate much that we already possess.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000891","text":"God won't give us more than we have until we have learnt to value that which we possess.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000892","text":"It is impossible, in the time that remains, to {57} do more than emphasize one special form of beauty in \"The Book of Common Prayer\"--The Collects.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:beauty","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000893","text":"The Prayer-Book Collects are pictures of beauty.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000894","text":"Only compare a modern collect with the Prayer-Book Collects, and you will see the difference without much looking.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000895","text":"Learn to value the Prayer Book. From birth to death it provides, as we shall see, special offices, and special prayers for the main events of our lives, though many minor events are still unprovided for.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mortality","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000896","text":"[2] Possibly, the origin of the British Liturgy revised by St. Augustine, and of the present Liturgy of the English Church.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000897","text":"[4] Cf. Acts iv. 24, \"They lifted up their voices _with one accord_\".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000898","text":"[5] The word _Mass_, which has caused such storms of controversy, originally meant a _dismissal_ of the congregation. It is found in words such as Christ-mas (i.e. a short name for the Eucharist on the Feast of the Nativity), Candle-mas, Martin-mas, Michael-mas, and so on.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000899","text":"[6] This was published _in extenso_ in a Blue Book, issued by the Government on 2 June, 1854.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000900","text":"[7] It is difficult to see how any revision could obtain legal sanction, even if prepared by Convocation, save by an Act of Parliament after free discussion by the present House of Commons.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:leadership","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000901","text":"[9] \"The Folkestone Baptist,\" June, 1899.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000902","text":"[10] \"Letters and Memoirs of William Bright,\" p. 143.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000903","text":"[11] \"Life and Letters of H. P. Liddon,\" p. 329.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000904","text":"We have seen that a National Church is the means whereby the Catholic Church reaches the nation; that her function is (1) to teach, and (2) to feed the nation; that she teaches through her books, and feeds through her Sacraments.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000905","text":"We now come to the second of these two functions--the spiritual feeding of the nation. This she does through the Sacraments--a word which comes from the Latin _sacrare_ (from _sacer_), sacred.[1] The Sacraments are the sacred _media_ through which the soul of man is fed with the grace of God.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000906","text":"We may think of them under three heads:--their number; their nature; their names.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000907","text":"In the early Church the number was unlimited.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000908","text":"After the twelfth century, the number was technically limited to seven.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000909","text":"Partly owing to the mystic number seven,[2] and partly because seven seemed to meet the needs of all sorts and conditions of men, the septenary number of Sacraments became either fixed or special.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000910","text":"The English Church, then, teaches that, without arbitrarily limiting their number, there are seven special means of grace, either \"generally necessary\" for all, or specially provided for some.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000911","text":"And, as amongst her books she selects two, and calls them \"_The_ Bible,\" and \"_The_ Prayer {60} Book,\" so amongst her Sacraments she deliberately marks out two for a primacy of honour.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000912","text":"These two are so supreme, as being \"ordained by Christ Himself\"; so pre-eminent, as flowing directly from the Wounded Side, that she calls them \"the Sacraments of the Gospel\".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000913","text":"They are, above all other Sacraments, \"glad tidings of great joy\" to every human being.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000914","text":"And these two are \"generally necessary,\" i.e.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000915","text":"necessary for all alike--they are _generaliter_, i.e.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000916","text":"for _all_ and not only for _special_ states (such as Holy Orders): they are \"for _every_ man in his vocation and ministry\".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000917","text":"The other five are not necessarily essential for all.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000918","text":"They have not all \"the like nature of Sacraments of the Gospel,\" in that they were not all \"ordained by Christ Himself\".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000919","text":"It is the nature of the two Sacraments of the Gospel that we now consider.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000920","text":"\"What meanest thou by this word, Sacrament?\" The Catechism, confining its answer to the two greater Sacraments, replies: \"I mean an outward and visible sign of an inward and spiritual grace...\"[5]","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000921","text":"Putting this into more modern language, we might say that a Sacrament is a supernatural conjunction of spirit and matter.[6] It is not matter only; it is not spirit only; it is not matter opposed to spirit, but spirit of which matter is the expression, and \"the ultimate reality\".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000922","text":"Thus, for a perfect Sacrament, there must be both \"the outward and visible\" (matter), and \"the inward and spiritual\" (spirit).","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000923","text":"It is the conjunction of the two which makes the Sacrament.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000924","text":"Thus, a Sacrament is not wholly under the conditions of material laws, nor is it wholly under the conditions of spiritual laws; it is under the conditions of what (for lack of any other name) we call _Sacramental_ laws.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000925","text":"As yet, we know comparatively little of either material or spiritual laws, and we cannot be surprised that we know still less of Sacramental laws.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000926","text":"We are in the student stage, and are perpetually revising our conclusions.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000927","text":"{62} In all three cases, we very largely \"walk by faith\".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000928","text":"But this at least we may say of Sacraments.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000929","text":"Matter without spirit cannot effect that which matter with spirit can, and does, effect.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000930","text":"As in the Incarnation, God[7] expresses Himself through matter[8]--so it is in the Sacraments.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000931","text":"In Baptism, the Holy Spirit \"expresses Himself\" through water: in the Eucharist, through bread and wine.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000932","text":"In each case, the perfect integrity of matter and of spirit are essential to the validity of the Sacrament.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:truth","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000933","text":"In each case, it is the conjunction of the two which guarantees the full effect of either.[9]","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000934","text":"As given in the Prayer Book, these are seven--\"Baptism, and the Supper of the Lord,\" Confirmation, Penance, Orders, Matrimony, and Unction.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000935","text":"Leo defines a Sacrament thus: \"_Sacramentum_.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000936","text":"[5] The answer is borrowed from Peter Lombard (a pupil of Abelard and Professor of Theology, and for a short time Bishop of Paris), who defines a Sacrament as a \"visible sign of an invisible grace,\" probably himself borrowing the thought from St. Augustine.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000937","text":"[6] Dr. Illingworth calls \"the material order another aspect of the spiritual, which is gradually revealing itself through material concealment, in the greater and lesser Christian Sacraments, which radiate from the Incarnation\" (\"Sermons Preached in a College Chapel,\" p. 173).","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:animism","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000938","text":"[8] The Word was made _Flesh_, St. John i. 14.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000939","text":"[9] The water in Baptism is not, of course, _consecrated_, as the bread and wine are in the Eucharist. It does not, like the bread and wine, \"become what it was not, without ceasing to be what it was,\" but it is \"_sanctified_ to the mystical washing away of sins\".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000940","text":"Consider, What it is; What it does; How it does it.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000941","text":"The Sacrament of Baptism is the supernatural conjunction of matter and spirit--of water and the Holy Ghost. Water must be there, and spirit must be there. It is by the conjunction of the two that the Baptized is \"born anew of water and of the Holy Ghost\".","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000942","text":"At the reception of a privately baptized child into the Church, it is laid down that \"matter\" and \"words\" are the two essentials for a valid Baptism.[1] \"Because some things essential to this Sacrament may happen to be omitted (and thus invalidate the Sacrament), ...","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000943","text":"The child is then given \"Conditional Baptism,\" and Baptism is administered with the conditional words: \"If thou art not already baptized,\"--for Baptism cannot be repeated--\"I baptize thee in the name of the Father, and of the Son, and of the Holy Ghost.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000944","text":"Amen.\" So careful is the Church both in administering and guarding the essentials of the Sacrament.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000945","text":"And notice: nothing but the water and the words are _essential_.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000946","text":"Other things may, or may not, be edifying; they are not essential; they are matters of ecclesiastical regulation, not of Divine appointment.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000947","text":"Thus, a _Priest_ is not essential to a valid Baptism, as he is for a valid Eucharist.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000948","text":"A Priest is the normal, but not the necessary, instrument of Baptism.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000949","text":"\"In the absence of a {65} Priest\"[2] a Deacon may baptize, and if the child is _in extremis_, any one, of either sex, may baptize.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000950","text":"Again, _Sponsors_ are not essential to the validity of the Sacrament.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000951","text":"Sponsors are safeguards, not essentials.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000952","text":"They are only a part--an invaluable part--of ecclesiastical regulation.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000953","text":"When, in times of persecution, parents might be put to death, other parents were chosen as parents-in-God (God-parents)[3] to safeguard the child's Christian career.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mortality","tradition:christianity","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000954","text":"Sponsors are \"sureties\" of the Church, not parts of the Sacraments.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000955","text":"They stand at the font, as fully admitted Church members, to welcome a new member into the Brotherhood.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000956","text":"But a private Baptism without Sponsors would be a valid Baptism.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000957","text":"The mode of administering the Sacrament may vary: it is not (apart from the matter and words) of the essence of the Sacrament.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000958","text":"There are, in fact, three ways in which Baptism may be validly administered.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000959","text":"It may be administered by _Immersion_, _Aspersion_, or _Affusion_.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000960","text":"Immersion (_in-mergere_, to dip into) is the original and primitive form of administration. {66} As the word suggests, it consists of dipping the candidate into the water--river, bath, or font.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000961","text":"Aspersion (_ad spargere_, to sprinkle upon) is not a primitive form of administration. It consists in sprinkling water upon the candidate's forehead.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000962","text":"Affusion (_ad fundere_, to pour upon) is the allowed alternative to Immersion. It consists in pouring water upon the candidate.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000963","text":"Immersion was the Apostolic method, and explains most vividly the Apostolic teaching (in which the Candidate is \"buried with Christ\" by immersion, and rises again by emersion)[4] no less than the meaning of the word--from the Greek _baptizo_, to dip.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000964","text":"Provision for Immersion has been made by a Fontgrave, in Lambeth Parish Church, erected in memory of Archbishop Benson, and constantly made use of.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:leadership","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000965","text":"But, even in Apostolic times, Baptism by \"Affusion\" was allowed to the sick and was equally valid.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000966","text":"In the Prayer Book, affusion is either permitted (as in the Public Baptism of infants), or ordered (as in the Private Baptism of infants), or, again, allowed (as in the Baptism of those of riper years).","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000967","text":"It will be {67} noted that the Church of England makes no allusion to \"Aspersion,\" or the \"sprinkling\" form of administration.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000968","text":"The child or adult is always either to be dipped into the water, or to have water poured upon it.[5] Other ceremonies there are--ancient and mediaeval.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000969","text":"Some are full of beauty, but none are essential.","author":"Rumi","source":"Masnavi — Whinfield Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000970","text":"Produced by Michael Ciesielski, Martin Pettit and the Online Distributed Proofreading Team at http://www.pgdp.net","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000971","text":"A ROMANCE OF \"THE BEGGAR'S OPERA\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000972","text":"_\"Why how now Madam Flirt\"--Lucy._","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000973","text":"\"STIRRING DEEDS IN THE GREAT WAR,\" \"A QUEEN OF THE PADDOCK,\" \"CORINTHIAN JACK,\" ETC.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000974","text":"LONDON STANLEY PAUL & CO. 31, ESSEX STREET, STRAND, W.C.2.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000975","text":"_Printed in Great Britain at the Athenæum Printing Works, Redhill_","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000976","text":"\"IF YOUR NAME ISN'T POLLY IT OUGHT TO BE\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000977","text":"\"As pretty a wench as man ever clapped eyes on. Wake up, Lance, and look at her.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000978","text":"The portly man of genial aspect sitting in the corner of the bow window of the Maiden Head Inn at the High Street end of Dyott Street in the very heart of St.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000979","text":"Giles, clapped his sleeping friend on the shoulder and shook him.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000980","text":"The sleeper, a young man whose finely drawn features were clouded with the dregs of wine, muttered something incoherently, and with an impatient twist shifted his body in the capacious arm-chair.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000981","text":"When a man's in his cups he's best by himself.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000982","text":"'Twill take him a day's snoring to get rid of his bout.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000983","text":"\"Long life indeed, my lord. A couple of hours at most. Not that the length of life is to be measured by years. I don't know but what it's possible to cram one's whole existence into a few hours, thanks to that thief of time,\" rejoined John Gay pointing to the bottle on the table.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000984","text":"The poet's placid face saddened.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000985","text":"John Gay had always taken life as a pleasure, but there is no pleasure without pain as he had come to discover.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:grief","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000986","text":"Maybe at that moment a recollection of his follies gave his conscience a tinge.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000987","text":"Of Gay it might be said that he had no enemies other than himself.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000988","text":"\"Oh, the passing hour is the best doubtless, since we never know whether the next may not be the worst,\" laughed Henry St.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000989","text":"\"I'll wager Jack Sheppard's best was when the noose was round his neck.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000990","text":"The rascal will trouble nervous folks no more.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000991","text":"But for the brave show he made at Tyburn yesterday, would those ladies and gentlemen be merry making, think you, and would the tavern keepers and the gin sellers be putting money in their pockets?\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:courage","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000992","text":"Gay turned his eyes to the open window.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000993","text":"\"I don't want to think of the rascally knave or the rabble either. My thoughts are on yonder pretty little jade. Look for yourself, Bolingbroke. You're not so insensible to beauty as Lance Vane is at this moment.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:beauty","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000994","text":"\"Faith, I hope not. Where's the charmer?\" said Bolingbroke walking to the window.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000995","text":"\"Stay. She's going to sing. She has the voice of a nightingale. I've heard her before. Lord! to think she has to do it for a living!\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000996","text":"\"Humph. She has courage. Most girls would die rather than rub shoulders with that frousy, bestial, drunken mob.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:courage","theme:love","theme:resilience","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000997","text":"\"Aye, but that little witch subdues them all with her voice. What says Will Congreve? Music has charms to soothe a savage breast? Listen.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000998","text":"A girl slight in figure but harmoniously proportioned had placed herself about two yards from the bow window.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-000999","text":"She fixed her eyes on Gay and her pretty mouth curved into a smile.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001000","text":"The ditty was \"Cold and Raw,\" a ballad that two hundred years ago or so, never failed to delight everybody from the highest to the lowest.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001001","text":"She gave it with natural feeling and without any attempt at display.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001002","text":"The voice was untrained but this did not matter.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001003","text":"It was like the trill of a bird, sweet, flexible and pure toned.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001004","text":"\"A voice like that ought not to be battered about. It's meant for something better than bawling to a mob. What says your lordship?\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001005","text":"Bolingbroke's face had become grave, almost stern.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001006","text":"His high, somewhat narrow, slightly retreating forehead, long nose and piercing eyes lent themselves readily to severity.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001007","text":"Twenty-five years before it was not so.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001008","text":"He was then the gayest of the gay and in the heyday of his career.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001009","text":"Disappointed political ambitions and political flirtations with the Jacobite party had ended in exile in France, from which, having been pardoned, he had not long returned.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001010","text":"Meeting Gay, the latter suggested a prowl in St. Giles, where life was in more than its usual turmoil consequent upon the execution of Jack Sheppard; so Viscount Bolingbroke revisited the slums of St. Giles, which had been the scene of many an orgy in his hot youth.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001011","text":"The nobleman returned no answer to Gay's question.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001012","text":"His thoughts had gone back to his early manhood when he took his pleasure wherever he found it.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001013","text":"Giles was more to his taste than St.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001014","text":"So long as the face was beautiful, and the tongue given to piquant raillery, any girl was good enough for him.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001015","text":"He was of the time when a love intrigue was a necessary part of a man's life, and not infrequently of a woman's too.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001016","text":"Successful lover though he had been he was not all conquering.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001017","text":"The ballad singer's tender liquid tones carried his memory back to the low-born girl with the laughing eyes who had captured his heart.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001018","text":"She sold oranges about the door of the Court of Requests, she sang ballads in the street, she was a little better than a light of love, yet Bolingbroke could never claim her as his own.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001019","text":"It angered him sorely that she had a smile for others.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001020","text":"But he bore her no malice, or he would hardly have written his poetical tribute commencing:--","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001021","text":"\"Dear, thoughtless Clara, to my verse attend, Believe for once the lover and the friend.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001022","text":"So Gay's words were unheeded. A heavy step sounded on the sanded floor. A big man with features formed on an ample mould had entered. Gay was entranced by the singer and did not hear him. The newcomer stood silently behind the poet. He too, was listening intently.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001023","text":"The girl's voice died into a cadence. Gay beckoned to her and she came up to the window.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001024","text":"\"Finely sung, Polly,\" cried Gay. \"Who taught thee, child?\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001025","text":"\"I taught myself, sir,\" said she dropping a curtsey.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001026","text":"\"Then you had a good teacher. There's a crown for you.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001027","text":"\"Nay, Polly--if your name isn't Polly it ought to be. What does your mother call you?\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001028","text":"Her face remained unmoved save her eyes, which danced with sly merriment.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001029","text":"The men at the window burst into a roar of laughter. He who had entered last laughed the loudest and deepest, and loud and deep as was that laugh it was full of music. At its sound Gay turned sharply.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001030","text":"\"What? Dick Leveridge? You've come at the right moment. We need someone who knows good music when he hears it. What of this pretty child's voice. Is it good?\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001031","text":"\"Is it good? I'll answer your question, Mr. Gay, by asking you another. Are you good at verses?\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001032","text":"\"'Tis said my 'Fables' will be pretty well. The young Prince William will have the dedication of it and if his mother, the Princess of Wales approves, methinks my fortune's made,\" cried Gay buoyantly.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001033","text":"\"Glad to hear it,\" replied Leveridge, dryly. \"If I know anything about His Royal Highness you'll gain a fortune sooner by writing a ballad or two for this pretty songster. Make her famous as you made me with 'All in the Downs' and 'T'was when the seas were roaring.'\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001034","text":"\"Faith, Dick, you've set my brain working. I'll think on't, but that means I must keep my eye on the wench.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001035","text":"\"Oh, I'll trust you for that,\" rejoined Leveridge, the ghost of a smile flitting across his solemn visage.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:relationships","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001036","text":"Meanwhile the girl had retreated a yard or two from the window, her gaze fixed wistfully on Gay and Leveridge. She knew from their looks that she was the subject of their talk.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001037","text":"Gay turned from his friend Richard Leveridge, the great bass singer of the day, and rested his hands on the window sill. Bolingbroke had sunk into his chair, and buried in his thoughts, was slowly sipping his wine. Lancelot Vane continued to breathe heavily.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001038","text":"\"Come here, child,\" said Gay through the open window and sinking his voice. The crowd had pressed round her and were clamourous for her to sing again. Some had thrown her a few pence for which a couple of urchins were groping on the ground.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001039","text":"\"My name's Lavinia--Lavinia Fenton, sir,\" she interrupted.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001040","text":"\"Too fine--too fine. I like Polly better. Never mind. If it's Lavinia, Lavinia it must be. What's your mother? Where does she live?\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001041","text":"\"At the coffee house in Bedfordbury.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001042","text":"\"Wait on the customers--sometimes.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001043","text":"\"And sometimes you sing in the streets--round the taverns, eh?\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001044","text":"\"Only when mother drives me out.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001045","text":"\"Oh. She ill treats you, does she? That bruise on your shoulder--was it her work?\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001046","text":"\"You wouldn't mind if you left your mother and did nothing but sing?\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001047","text":"\"Oh, that would be joy,\" cried the girl squeezing her hands tightly together to stifle her emotions. \"But how can I?\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001048","text":"\"It may be managed, perhaps. I must see your mother----\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001049","text":"He was interrupted by a deafening roar--hoarse, shrill, raucous, unmistakably drunken.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001050","text":"A huge, ragged multitude had poured into the High Street from St.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001051","text":"Martin's Lane, jostling, fighting, cursing, eager for devilment, no matter what.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001052","text":"They rushed to the hostelries, they surrounded the street sellers of gin, demanding the fiery poisonous stuff for which they had no intention of paying.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001053","text":"The landlord of the \"Maiden Head\" hurried into the room somewhat perturbed.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001054","text":"\"Best shut the window, gentlemen,\" said he. \"This vile scum's none too nice. Anything it wants it'll take without so much as by your leave, or with your leave.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001055","text":"\"What does it mean, landlord?\" asked Bolingbroke.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001056","text":"The people are mad about the rascal just because the turnkeys couldn't hold him, nor prison walls for the matter o' that.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001057","text":"He was clever in slipping out o' prison I grant ye.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001058","text":"Well, sirs, his body was to be handed over to the surgeons like the rest o' the Tyburn gentry, but his friends would have none of it.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001059","text":"A bailiff somehow got hold of the corpse to make money out of it--trust them sharks for _that_ when they see a chance--an' smuggled it to his house in Long Acre.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:relationships","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001060","text":"It got wind afore many hours was past and the mob broke into the place, the Foot Guards was called out an' there's been no end of a rumpus.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001061","text":"\"Faith, my poor Gay,\" said Bolingbroke with a sardonic smile, \"the people make more fuss over a burglar than over a ballad maker. And what's become of the noble Sheppard's body, landlord?\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001062","text":"\"It's hidden somewhere. They say as it'll be buried to-night in St. Martin's Churchyard. So the people'll get their way after all.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001063","text":"\"As they mostly do if they make noise enough,\" rejoined Bolingbroke refreshing himself with a pinch of snuff.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001064","text":"The sound of a loud high pitched, strident voice floated into the room through the open window. Gay, whose eyes had never shifted from the girl outside, saw her cheeks suddenly blanch. She looked round hurriedly like a frightened rabbit seeking a way of escape.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:judaism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001065","text":"\"Bring the girl in, landlord,\" exclaimed the poet hastily. \"She'll come to harm else. Lord! Look at those drunken beasts. No--no\"--the landlord was about to shut the latticed windows--\"run to the door, child. Quick.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001066","text":"A howling sottish mob mad with drink, clamouring, gesticulating, men and women jostling each other, embracing vulgarly, their eyes glassy, their faces flushed, was approaching the inn.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001067","text":"The mob was headed by a handsome woman.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001068","text":"She was in the plenitude of fleshly charms.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001069","text":"Her dress, disordered, showed her round solidly built shoulders, her ample bust.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001070","text":"Some day unless her tastes and her manner of life altered she would end in a bloway drab, every vestige of beauty gone in masses of fat.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001071","text":"But at that moment she was the model of a reckless Bacchante, born for the amusement and aggravation of man.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001072","text":"Her maddening eyes were directed on the Maiden Head inn.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001073","text":"Her full lips were parted in a harsh boisterous laugh; her white teeth gleamed; the blood ran riot in her veins; she was the embodiment of exuberant, semi-savage, animal life.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001074","text":"She danced up to the open window.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001075","text":"The sight of the sleeping Lance Vane had drawn her thither.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001076","text":"Up to that moment Lavinia Fenton's back was towards the woman. Lavinia tried to get away without notice, but the Bacchante's escort was too numerous, too aggressive, too closely packed. They hoped for some fun after their own tastes.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001077","text":"\"Mercy on me,\" muttered Gay apprehensively, \"that impudent hussy, Sally Salisbury.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001078","text":"Dick,\" he whispered hurriedly to Leveridge, \"you can use your fists if need be.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001079","text":"I've seen you have a set-to in Figg's boxing shed.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001080","text":"Leveridge nodded and followed his friend out of the room.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001081","text":"Gay's action was none too prompt.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001082","text":"No sooner had Sally Salisbury--destined to be, a few years later, the most notorious woman of her class--set eyes on the girl than her brows were knitted and her lips and nostrils went white.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001083","text":"Her cheeks on the other hand blazed with fury.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001084","text":"She gripped the shrinking girl and twisted her round.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001085","text":"Then she thrust her face within a few inches of Lavinia's.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:solitude","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001086","text":"\"What do you mean by coming here, you squalling trollop?\" she screamed. \"How dare you poach on my ground, you----\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:courage","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001087","text":"How Sally finished the sentence can be very well left to take care of itself.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001088","text":"Lavinia despite her terror of the beautiful virago never lost her self-control.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001089","text":"\"You're welcome to this ground every inch of it, but I suppose I've as much right to walk on it as you have,\" said she.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001090","text":"\"Don't talk to me, you little trull, or you'll drive me to tear your eyes out. Take that.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001091","text":"With the back of her disengaged hand she struck the girl's cheek.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001092","text":"\"GO YOUR OWN WAY YOU UNGRATEFUL MINX\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:gratitude","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001093","text":"The mob roared approval at the prospect of a fight, and though the combatants were unfairly matched some of the ruffians urged the girl to retaliate.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:justice","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001094","text":"\"Go for her hair, little un,\" one shouted. \"There's plenty of it. Once you get a fair hold and tear out a handful she'll squeak, I'll warrant.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:justice","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001095","text":"The advice was not taken and maybe nobody expected it would be. Anyway, before Sally could renew the attack her arm was seized by a man, slight in stature and with a naturally humorous expression on his lean narrow face and in his bright twinkling eyes.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001096","text":"\"Enough of this brawling, mistress. If you _must_ fight choose someone as big and as strong as yourself, not a lambkin.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001097","text":"The crowd knew him and whispers went round. \"That's Spiller--Jemmy Spiller the famous play actor.\" \"No, is it though. Lord, he can make folks laugh--ah, split their sides a'most. I see him last Saturday at Master Rich's theayter in the Fields, and I thought I should ha' died.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001098","text":"Spiller was better at making people laugh than at holding an infuriated woman. But he had two friends with him, stalwart butchers from Clare Market, and he turned the task over to them with the remark that they were used to handling mad cattle.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001099","text":"At this point Gay and Leveridge forced their way through the crowd. Gay saw the red angry mark on the girl's pallid face and guessed the cause. He drew her gently to him.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001100","text":"\"Run inside the house. I'll join you presently,\" he whispered.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001101","text":"She thanked him with her eyes and vanished. Gay turned to Spiller.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001102","text":"\"You deserve a double benefit at Drury Lane, Jemmy, for what you did just now. That wild cat was about to use her claws,\" said he.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001103","text":"\"Aye, and her teeth too, Mr. Gay.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001104","text":"\"You'll need a mouthful of mountain port after that tussle. And your friends as well, when they've disposed of Mistress Salisbury.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001105","text":"The butchers had removed her out of harm's way.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001106","text":"But she vowed vengeance on the \"squalling chit\" sooner or later.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001107","text":"Meanwhile the object of Sally Salisbury's hoped for revenge was sitting in a dark corner of the coffee room of the Maiden Head tavern.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001108","text":"She felt terribly embarrassed and answered Bolingbroke's compliments in monosyllables.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001109","text":"He pressed her to take some wine but she refused.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001110","text":"To her great relief he did not trouble her with attentions.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001111","text":"Then Gay entering with Spiller and his butcher friends, and Leveridge, as soon as he could, approached her.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001112","text":"\"Tell me, Polly,--my tongue refuses to say Lavinia--how you have offended that vulgar passionate woman?\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001113","text":"She's burning to sing but she can't.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001114","text":"Sing, why she sets one's teeth on edge!","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001115","text":"It might be the sharpening of a knife on a grindstone.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001116","text":"She would be a play actress, and Mrs.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001117","text":"Barry at Drury Lane promised to help her, but they quarrelled.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001118","text":"Sally wanted to be a great actress all at once, but you can't be, can you, sir?\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001119","text":"She looked at the poet earnestly. Her large grey eyes were wonderfully expressive, and Gay did not at once answer. He was thinking how sweet was the face, and how musical and appealing the voice.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001120","text":"\"True, child, and that you should say it shows your good sense. Wait here a few minutes and then you shall take me to your mother.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001121","text":"Gay crossed the room to his friends, and they talked together in low voices. Spiller and Leveridge had much to say--indeed it was to these two, who had practical knowledge of the theatre, to whom he appealed. Bolingbroke sat silently listening.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001122","text":"Gay's project concerning his new found protégée was such as would only have entered into the brain of a dreamy and impecunious poet.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001123","text":"He saw in Lavinia Fenton the making of a fine actress--not in tragedy but in comedy--and of an enchanting singer.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001124","text":"But to be proficient she must be taught not only music, but how to pronounce the English language properly.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001125","text":"She had to a certain extent picked up the accent of the vulgar.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001126","text":"It was impossible, considering her surroundings and associations, to be otherwise.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001127","text":"But proper treatment and proper companions would soon rid her of this defect.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001128","text":"Both Spiller and Leveridge agreed she was fitted for the stage. But how was she to be educated? And what was the use of education while she was living in a Bedfordbury coffee house!","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001129","text":"\"She must be sent to a boarding school and be among gentlefolk,\" declared Gay energetically.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001130","text":"\"Excellent,\" said Bolingbroke, speaking for the first time, \"and may I ask who will pay for the inestimable privilege of placing her among the quality?\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001131","text":"The irony in St. John's voice did not go unnoticed by Gay, but he continued bravely.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:courage","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001132","text":"\"I will, if her mother won't.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001133","text":"\"You? My good friend, you can scarce keep yourself. But 'tis like you to add to the burden of debt round your neck rather than reduce it. Have you been left a fortune? Have your dead South Sea Shares come back to life?\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001134","text":"\"Nay, Bolingbroke, don't remind me of my folly,\" rejoined Gay, a little piqued. \"We can't always be wise. Thou thyself--but let that pass, the future is the foundation of hope. Before long I shall be in funds. The 'Fables' will be in the booksellers' hands ere the month is out.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001135","text":"\"Oh, that's well. But the booksellers, though eager enough to sell their wares, are not so ready to pay the writer his due. Moreover if I know anything of John Gay, of a certainty all the money he puts in his pocket will go out of the hole at the other end.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001136","text":"\"I know--I know,\" rejoined the poet hastily. \"But I'm not thinking alone of the booksellers. It is a 'place' I shall have and an annual income that will sweep away all my anxieties.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:solitude","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001137","text":"\"Then you're in favour with the Princess and her obedient servant Sir Robert--or is Walpole her master? What will the Dean of St. Patrick and Mr. Pope say to your surrender?\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:leadership","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001138","text":"\"No, no. I will never write a word in praise of either. There's not a word in the 'Fables' that can be twisted into bolstering up the Government.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001139","text":"\"And you think to receive your comfortable 'place' out of pure admiration of your poetical gifts? My poor Gay!\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001140","text":"\"Well, well, you must go your own way or you wouldn't be a poet. I leave you to your commendable work of rescuing damsels in distress.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001141","text":"And after refreshing himself with a pinch of snuff Bolingbroke with a wave of the hand to Gay and his friends strode from the room leaving the poet with his pleasant face somewhat overcast.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001142","text":"But his chagrin did not last long.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001143","text":"His natural buoyancy asserted itself and he beckoned to Lavinia who was sitting primly on the edge of the hard chair, her folded hands resting on her lap.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001144","text":"Before she could cross the room Spiller and Leveridge took up Bolingbroke's argument, and urged Gay not to meddle further in the matter.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001145","text":"It would be a shame and a pity that so much good talent should be wasted on the groundlings of St.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001146","text":"Besides, there is the girl herself,\" Gay lowered his voice.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001147","text":"\"You wouldn't have her be like Sally Salisbury, Jemmy, would you?","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001148","text":"She has a good and innocent nature.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001149","text":"It will be torn to tatters if she be not looked after now.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001150","text":"Neither you nor Dick Leveridge will talk me out of my intent.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001151","text":"Do you see what misguided youth may easily come to?","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:leadership","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001152","text":"Gay pointed to the sleeping young man.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001153","text":"\"I know--I know. The young fool,\" returned Spiller a little angrily. \"Wine is Lancelot Vane's only weakness--well, not the only one, any pretty face turns his head.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001154","text":"\"He's not the worse for that provided a good heart goes with the pretty face.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001155","text":"\"Look after him then. When he awakens from his drunken fit he'll be like clay in the hands of the potters.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001156","text":"\"Faith, you're right, Mr. Gay, but there's one thing that'll protect him--his empty purse. I doubt if he has a stiver left. I know he drew some money from the _Craftsman_ yesterday.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001157","text":"\"What, does he write for that scurrilous, venomous print?\" cried Gay, visibly disturbed.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001158","text":"\"Not of his own will. He hates the paper and he hates Amherst, who owns it. But what is a man to do when poverty knocks at the door?\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001159","text":"Still--I wish he had nothing to do with that abusive fellow, Nicholas Amherst, who calls himself 'Caleb D'Anvers,' why I know not, unless he's ashamed of the name his father gave him.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001160","text":"Do you know that the _Craftsman_ is always attacking my friends, Mr.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001161","text":"As for myself--but that's no matter.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001162","text":"\"Oh, Amherst's a gadfly, no doubt. But your friends can take care of themselves. For every blow they get they can if it so pleases them, give two in return.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001163","text":"\"That's true, and I'll say nothing more. I wish your friend well rid of the rascally D'Anvers. Look after him, Jemmy. Come Polly--let us to your mother.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001164","text":"The dirt and the poverty-stricken aspect of the locality did not deter the poet from his intention. Bedfordbury was not worse than St. Giles. The girl led him to a shabby coffee shop from the interior of which issued a hot and sickly air.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001165","text":"\"That's mother,\" she whispered when they were in the doorway.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001166","text":"A buxom woman not too neatly dressed, whose apron bore traces of miscellaneous kitchen work, scowled when her eyes lighted on her daughter.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001167","text":"\"So you've come home, you lazy good-for-nothing hussy,\" she screamed. \"Where have you been? You don't care how hard I have to work so long as you can go a pleasuring. There's plenty for you to do here. Set about washing these plates if you don't want a trouncing.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001168","text":"Mrs. Fenton was in a vile temper and Gay's heart somewhat failed at the sight of her. Then he glanced at the girl and her frightened face gave him courage.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:courage","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:resilience","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001169","text":"\"Madame,\" said he advancing with a polite bow, \"I should like with your permission to have a few words with you in private. My business here concerns your daughter in whom I take an interest.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001170","text":"\"Oh, and who may you be?\" asked the woman ungraciously.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001171","text":"\"My name is Gay--John Gay--but I'll tell you more when we're alone.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:solitude","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001172","text":"He cast a look around at the rough Covent Garden porters with which the place was fairly full.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:justice","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001173","text":"One of the boxes was empty and Mrs.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001174","text":"Fenton pointed to it, at the same time ordering her daughter to go into the kitchen and make herself useful.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001175","text":"Then she flopped down opposite Gay, separated from him by a table marked by innumerable rings left by coffee mugs.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001176","text":"Gay put forward his ideas and painted a glorious future for Lavinia. Her mother did not seem particularly impressed. It was doubtful indeed if she believed him.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:grief","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001177","text":"\"You'll find the wench a handful.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001178","text":"I'd as lieve let her go her own way as keep her.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001179","text":"A young 'oman with a pretty face hasn't got no need to trouble about getting a living.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001180","text":"Sooner or later she'll give me the slip--but--well--if you takes her and makes a lady of her what do I get out of it?\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001181","text":"This was a view of the matter which had not occurred to the poet. He felt decidedly embarrassed. His project appeared to be more costly than he had at first imagined.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001182","text":"\"It is for the benefit of your daughter,\" he stammered.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001183","text":"\"Her benefit, indeed. Fiddle-de-dee! Your own you mean. I know what men are. If she was an ugly slut you wouldn't take no notice of her. Don't talk rubbish. What are you a going to give me for saying, yes. That's business, mister. Come, how much?\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001184","text":"The poet saw there was no other way but talking business. This embarrassed him still more for he was the last man qualified to act in such a capacity.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001185","text":"\"I'll see what I can do,\" said he nervously, \"but you mustn't forget that Lavinia will have to be quite two years at school, and there is her music master----\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001186","text":"\"Oh I dare say,\" rejoined the lady scoffingly, \"and the mantle maker, and the milliner, and the glover, and the hairdresser. That's your affair, not mine. Name a round sum and I'll try to meet you. What d'ye say?\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:courage","theme:justice","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001187","text":"\"What!\" shrieked Lavinia's mother. \"And you call yourself a gentleman?\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001188","text":"\"The sum I admit is a small one, but as you seemed anxious to get your daughter off your hands I thought I was doing you a service by putting the girl in a way to earn a good living.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001189","text":"I'm not to be taken in like that.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001190","text":"Fine words butter no parsnips.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001191","text":"While Lavinia's in the house I'll go bail I'll make her work.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001192","text":"If she goes away I've got to pay someone in her place, haven't I?","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001193","text":"Twenty guineas is the very lowest I'll take, and if you was anything like the gentleman you look you'd make it double.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001194","text":"The haggling over such a matter and the coarse mercenary nature of the woman jarred upon the poet's sensitive soul.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001195","text":"The plain fact that he hadn't got twenty guineas in the world could not be gainsaid.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001196","text":"If he could only interest them in this protégée of his something might be done.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001197","text":"\"Twenty guineas,\" he repeated. \"Well, I'll do my best. In two days' time, Mrs. Fenton, I will come and see you and most likely all will be settled to your satisfaction.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001198","text":"\"Two days. Aye. No longer or maybe my price'll go up.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001199","text":"\"I shall not fail. Now, Mrs. Fenton, before I go I'd like to see Lavinia once more.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001200","text":"\"No, this business is between you an' me, mister. The hussy's naught to do with it. She'll have to behave herself while she's with me. That's all I have to say about _her_.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001201","text":"So Gay rose and walked out of the box feeling as though he'd been through a severe drubbing.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001202","text":"He might have been sufficiently disheartened to shatter his castle in the air had he not seen Lavinia's big sorrowful eyes fixed upon him from the kitchen.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:grief","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001203","text":"He dared not disobey her mother's behest not to speak to her so he tried to smile encouragingly, and to intimate by his expression that all was going well.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:courage","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001204","text":"Whether he succeeded in so doing he was by no means sure.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001205","text":"On leaving the coffee house Gay walked towards Charing Cross and thence along the Haymarket to Piccadilly.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001206","text":"His destination was Queensberry House to the north of Burlington Gardens.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001207","text":"Here lived Gay's good friends the Duke and Duchess of Queensberry, and indeed Gay himself, save when he was at Twickenham with Pope.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001208","text":"At dinner that evening Gay broached the subject of the phenomenal singer whom he had discovered in the streets of St.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:solitude","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001209","text":"Giles and his scheme concerning her.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001210","text":"The duke laughed at the poet's visions, but the duchess was fascinated.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:leadership","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001211","text":"Anything of the unusual at once appealed to the warmhearted, impulsive, somewhat eccentric, lady.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001212","text":"Her enthusiasm where she was interested always carried her away, and her impatience and energy would not let her rest until her object was accomplished.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001213","text":"\"I would vastly like to hear Mr. Gay's pretty nightingale. You must bring her to-morrow. I am dying to see if she is really the wonder you pretend she is. You know that the best judge of a woman is another woman. A man is apt to be partial.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001214","text":"\"And a woman to be prejudiced,\" said Gay smilingly.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001215","text":"\"Faith, Kitty,\" laughed the duke, \"our poet has thee there.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001216","text":"\"I deny it. But we will discuss the question after we've seen the paragon. When shall she come?\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001217","text":"\"Not until we've settled with the mother. She's a harpy. If she knows that your grace has anything to do with the affair she'll double her price.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:justice","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001218","text":"\"Why, our Gay is teaching us something,\" said the Duke banteringly. \"He is giving us a lesson in financial economy. Duchess, you must keep your eye on the next post vacant in the Exchequer.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001219","text":"\"Pish!\" retorted her grace. \"Mr. Gay is only exercising commonsense. We all of us have a little of that commodity. If we could only have it handy when it's wanted how much better the world would be.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001220","text":"Neither of the men disputed the lady's proposition, and the duchess rising, left them to their wine.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001221","text":"Armed with the twenty guineas, Gay presented himself the following day at the Bedfordbury coffee house. Mrs. Fenton was still ungracious, but the sight of the little pile of gold and the chink of the coins mollified her humour.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001222","text":"\"Where and when are you going to take her?\" she demanded.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001223","text":"Gay had arranged a plan with the duchess and he replied promptly.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001224","text":"\"She will stay here for a few days while her wardrobe is being got ready, then she is to go to Miss Pinwell's boarding school in Queen Square.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001225","text":"\"Carry me out and bury me decent,\" ejaculated Mrs. Fenton. \"Then I'm to be the mother of a fine lady, am I?\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001226","text":"\"I don't say that, but a clever one if I'm not mistaken.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001227","text":"\"Clever! Oh la! Much good will her cleverness do her. Clever! Aye in always having a crowd o' sparks a dangling after her. That Miss What's-her-name in Queen Square'll have to get up early to best Lavinia when there's a man about.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001228","text":"\"A mother shouldn't say such ill-natured things of her own child,\" said Gay reprovingly. \"She's hardly a woman yet.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001229","text":"\"But she knows as much. Well, you've got your bargain. Make your best of it. What about her clothes? She's but a rag-bag though it's no fault o' mine. Pray who's going to buy her gowns, her hats, her petticoats, her laces and frills. You?\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001230","text":"\"I? Bless me! no, woman. I know nothing about such things,\" rejoined Gay colouring slightly. \"I will send a woman who understands the business.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001231","text":"\"It's all one to me. Maybe you'd better tell your tale to Lavinia with your own lips. I've done with her.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001232","text":"\"By all means. I should like to see her.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001233","text":"Fenton, whose eyes all the while had been gloating over the gold on the table now swept it into her pocket.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001234","text":"It was a windfall which had come at the right moment.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001235","text":"There was a coffee house business in the Old Bailey going cheap, the twenty pounds would enable her to buy it.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001236","text":"As for her daughter, she had no scruple about letting her go with a man who was quite a stranger.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001237","text":"The girl's future didn't trouble her.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001238","text":"Since Lavinia had entered her teens, mother and daughter had wrangled incessantly.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001239","text":"Lavinia was amiable enough, but constant snubbing had roused a spirit which guided her according to her moods.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:leadership","theme:love","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001240","text":"Sometimes she was full of defiance, at others she would run out of the house, and ramble about the streets until she was dead tired.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001241","text":"Lavinia was shrewd enough to discover why her mother did not want her at home.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001242","text":"Fenton, still good-looking, was not averse to flirting with the more presentable of her customers, and as Lavinia developed into womanhood she became a serious rival to her mother, so on the whole, Gay's proposition suited Mrs.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001243","text":"Fenton admirably, and she certainly never bothered to find out if he spoke the truth.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:truth","theme:wisdom","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001244","text":"She was not inclined to accept his story of the boarding school as a stepping-stone to the stage, but to pretend to believe it in a way quieted what little conscience she possessed.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001245","text":"If the scheme turned out badly, why, no one could say _she_ was to blame.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001246","text":"Lavinia, tremulous with excitement and looking prettier than ever, came into the room where the poet was awaiting her.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001247","text":"Her face fell when Gay talked about the boarding school and of the possibility of her having to remain there a long time, but she brightened up on his going on to say that the period might be considerably shortened if she made a rapid improvement.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001248","text":"\"And do you really think, sir, I shall ever be good enough to act in a theatre like Mrs. Barry and Mrs. Oldfield, and--oh, and Mrs. Bracegurdle?\" cried the girl, her eyes blazing with anxious ambition.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001249","text":"\"I don't say you'll act like them. You'll act in your own way, and if you work hard your own way will be good enough. If you succeed the friends who are now helping you will be more than rewarded.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001250","text":"\"Ah, I will do anything to please you, sir.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001251","text":"She caught his hand and impulsively raised it to her lips.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001252","text":"Gay was a little embarrassed at this outburst.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001253","text":"Did it mean that the girl had fallen in love with him?","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001254","text":"He checked the rising thought.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001255","text":"Yet there was nothing outrageous in such a possibility.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001256","text":"Lavinia was only sixteen, it is true, and romantic sixteen might see nothing incongruous in thirty-seven, which was Gay's age.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001257","text":"\"What pleases me, child, doesn't matter,\" he returned hastily. \"I want to see you please others--in the play house I mean.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001258","text":"\"But,\" he continued, \"it will be time enough to talk of that when I see how you get on. Now is it all settled? You're leaving this place and your mother of your own free will--isn't that so?\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001259","text":"Lavinia said nothing, but pinched her lips and nodded her head vigorously. The action was sufficiently expressive and Gay was satisfied.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001260","text":"Three days went by. Her Grace of Queensberry's maid, a hard-faced Scotswoman who was not to be intimidated nor betrayed into confidences, superintended Lavinia's shopping and turned a deaf ear to Mrs. Fenton's scoffs and innuendoes.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001261","text":"The girl was transformed. Her new gowns, hats, aprons, and what not sent her into high spirits and she bade her mother adieu with a light heart.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001262","text":"\"Go your own way, you ungrateful minx,\" was Mrs. Fenton's parting shot, \"and when you're tired of your fine gentleman or he's tired of you, don't think you're coming back here 'cause I won't have you.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:gratitude","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001263","text":"Lavinia smiled triumphantly and tripped into the hackney coach that was awaiting her.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001264","text":"\"OH, MISTRESS MINE, WHERE ART THOU ROAMING?\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001265","text":"The victim of the feather of a quill pen tickling her neck dared not raise her voice.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:courage","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001266","text":"Miss Pinwell, the proprietress of the extremely genteel seminary for young ladies, Queen Square--quite an aristocratic retreat some two hundred years ago--was pacing the school-room.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001267","text":"Her cold, sharp eyes roamed over the shapely heads--black, golden, brown, auburn, flaxen--of some thirty girls--eager to detect any sign of levity and prompt to inflict summary punishment.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001268","text":"\"Miss Fenton, why are you not working?\" came the inquiry sharply from Miss Pinwell's thin lips.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001269","text":"Lavinia Fenton withdrew the instrument of torture and Priscilla Coupland's neck was left in peace.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001270","text":"It was done so swiftly that Miss Pinwell's glance, keen as it was, never detected the movement.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001271","text":"The young lady's industry did not deceive Miss Pinwell.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001272","text":"Lavinia Fenton was the black sheep--lamb perhaps is a more fitting word, she was but seventeen--of the school.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001273","text":"But somehow her peccadilloes were always forgiven.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001274","text":"She had a smile against which severity--even Miss Pinwell's--was powerless.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001275","text":"\"What were you doing just now when you were not writing?\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001276","text":"The wealth of wavy brown hair fell back from the broad smooth brow.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001277","text":"The large limpid imploring eyes looked straight, without a trace of guilt in them, at the thin-faced schoolmistress.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001278","text":"The beautiful mouth, the upper lip of which with its corners slightly upturned was delightfully suggestive of a smile, quivered slightly but not with fear, rather with suppressed amusement.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001279","text":"\"Nothing madam,\" was the demure reply.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001280","text":"\"Nothing? I don't believe you. Your hand was not on your book. Where was it?\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001281","text":"\"Oh, _that_. Yes, a wasp was flying near us. I thought it was going to settle on Priscilla Coupland's neck and I brushed it away with my pen.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001282","text":"Miss Pinwell could say nothing to this, especially as she distinctly heard at that moment the hum of some winged insect.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001283","text":"It _was_ a wasp, a real one, not the insect of Lavinia's fervid imagination.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001284","text":"The windows were open and it had found its way in from Lamb's Conduit Fields, at a happy moment allying itself with Lavinia.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001285","text":"Others heard it as well and sprang to their feet shrieking. The chance of escaping from tiresome moral maxims was too good to be lost.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001286","text":"\"Young ladies----\" commanded Miss Pinwell, but she could get no further.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001287","text":"Her voice was lost in the din.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001288","text":"The lady no more loved wasps than did her pupils.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001289","text":"She retreated as the wasp advanced.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001290","text":"The intruder ranged itself on the side of the girls and circled towards their instructress with malevolence in every turn and vicious intent in its buzz.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001291","text":"The only one not afraid was Lavinia Fenton who, waving a pocket handkerchief met the foe bravely but without success.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:courage","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001292","text":"The enemy refused to turn tail.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001293","text":"Other girls plucking up courage joined the champion and soon the school-room was in a hubbub.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:courage","theme:love","theme:resilience","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001294","text":"It was sometime before the excitement died down, and meanwhile Lavinia Fenton's remissness of conduct was forgotten--indeed her intrepidity singled her out for praise, which she received with becoming graciousness.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001295","text":"But before the day was out she relapsed into her bad ways.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001296","text":"She could or would do nothing right.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001297","text":"Miss Pinwell chided her for carelessness, she retorted saucily.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001298","text":"As discipline had to be maintained she was at last condemned to an hour with the backboard and there she sat in a corner of the room on a high legged chair with a small and extremely uncomfortable oval seat made still more uncomfortable by it sloping slightly forward.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001299","text":"As for the back, it was high and narrow.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001300","text":"It afforded no rest for the spine.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001301","text":"The delinquent was compelled to sit perfectly upright.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001302","text":"Thus it was at the same time an instrument of correction and of deportment.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001303","text":"Whatever bodily defects the early Georgian damsels possessed they certainly had straight backs and level shoulders. The backboard was admirable training for the carriage of the stately sacque, the graceful flirting of the fan and for the dancing of the grave and dignified minuet.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001304","text":"The hour for retiring was early, and at dusk the head of each bedroom took her candle from the hall table and after a low curtsy to the mistress of the establishment preceded those who slept in the same room up the broad staircase.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001305","text":"The maidens' behaviour was highly decorous until they were safe in their respective bed-chambers, when their tongues were unloosed.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001306","text":"Oddly enough Lavinia, who was usually full of chatter, had to-night little to say. Her schoolmates rallied her on her silent tongue.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001307","text":"\"Oh, don't bother me, Priscilla,\" she exclaimed pettishly. \"I suppose I can do as I like when Miss Pinwell isn't looking.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001308","text":"\"My dear, you generally do that when she _is_. I never saw such favouritism. I declare it's not fair. You were terribly tormenting all day. Anybody but you would have been sent to bed and kept on bread and water. What's the matter with you, miss?\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:justice","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001309","text":"\"Nothing. I'm tired, that's all.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001310","text":"\"First time in your life then. You were lively enough this afternoon when you nearly got me into a scrape trying to make me laugh with your tickling. It was as much as I could do to keep from screaming,\" exclaimed Priscilla angrily.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001311","text":"\"Well, you can do your screaming now if it pleases you, so long as it doesn't bring Miss Pinwell upstairs. Let me alone. I'm thinking about something.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:solitude","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001312","text":"\"Some _one_, my dear, you mean,\" put in a tall fair girl, Grace Armitage by name. \"Confess now, isn't it the new curate at St. George's? He seemed to have no eyes for any one but you last Sunday evening. How cruel to disturb the poor man's thoughts.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:justice","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001313","text":"\"Console yourself, Grace dear--_you're_ never likely to do that.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001314","text":"The girls tittered at Lavinia's repartee.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001315","text":"All knew that Grace Armitage was the vainest of the vain and believed every man who cast his eyes in her direction was in love with her.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001316","text":"She had no sarcastic rejoinder ready and if she had it was doubtful if she would have uttered it.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001317","text":"Lavinia Fenton, the soul of sweetness and amiability, could show resolute fight when roused.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001318","text":"Miss Armitage turned away with a disdainful toss of her head.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001319","text":"The others knew this too, for they ceased to irritate Lavinia and continued their talk among themselves. All the same, the principal topic was Lavinia Fenton. She was so strangely unlike herself to-night.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001320","text":"Half an hour later the room was in silence save for the whispering between the occupants of those beds sufficiently close to each other to permit this luxury. When the neighbouring clock of St. George's, Bloomsbury, chimed half-past nine even these subdued sounds had ceased.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:solitude","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001321","text":"At half-past ten the moon was at the full.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001322","text":"The pale light streamed through the small window panes and threw the shadows of the broad framework lattice-wise on Lavinia's bed which was next the window.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001323","text":"In daylight she had but to lie on her right side and she could see across the fields and the rising ground each side of the Fleet river to the villages of Islington and Hornsey.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001324","text":"Gradually the latticed shadow crept upwards.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001325","text":"It at last reached Lavinia's face.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001326","text":"Her eyes very wide open were staring at the ceiling with a vague, wistful expression.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001327","text":"She gave a long sigh, her body twisted, and leaning on her right elbow, her left hand insinuated itself beneath the pillow and drew forth a letter which she held in the moonlight and read.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001328","text":"Her forehead puckered as though she were in doubt.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001329","text":"Her steadfast eyes seemed to contradict the smile curving her upper lip.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001330","text":"The paper slipped from her limp fingers and she pondered, her colour deepening the while.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001331","text":"Nothing short of a love letter could have caused that delightful blush.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001332","text":"\"My soul is full of expectancy.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001333","text":"I can think of nothing but you--the divinest being that ever tortured the heart of man.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001334","text":"But the torture is exquisite because I know when I fold you in my arms it will change to bliss.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001335","text":"You will keep your promise and meet me at the 'Conduit Head' to-morrow midnight, will you not?","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001336","text":"I can scarce contain myself with thinking of it.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001337","text":"If you come not what remains for me but death?","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mortality","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001338","text":"Without you life is worthless.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001339","text":"My coach will be in readiness and the parson waiting for us at the Fleet.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001340","text":"\"When we are married, as I've told you, my family cannot refuse to receive my wife, but until we are made one they will do all they can to keep us apart.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:relationships","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001341","text":"My father insists upon my marrying a rich city madam, but I'll none of her.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001342","text":"I will only have you, my beauteous Lavinia.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001343","text":"I swear to you by all the gods that you shall be back at school before dawn, as on the night of the dance when I first saw my adorable divinity.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001344","text":"It will be a delicious secret.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001345","text":"After I have seen you safely to Queen Square and have parted from my dearest--it will be misery to bid thee adieu--I shall ride post haste to my father and tell him everything.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001346","text":"He will at first be angry, but he will relent when he sees your loveliness.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001347","text":"We shall be forgiven and Heaven will be ours.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001348","text":"\"Panting with impatience, ever your most devoted humble servant,","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:leadership","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001349","text":"Present taste would pronounce this effusion to be extravagant, rhapsodical, high-flown, super-sentimental, but it did not read so to Lavinia.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001350","text":"It was in the fashion of the times--indeed it approached nearer modern ideas than the majority of love letters of that day which generally began with \"Madam\" without any endearing prefix.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001351","text":"Lavinia liked it none the less because it was not so formal as the letters which some girls had shown her in all pride and secrecy.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001352","text":"But it troubled her all the same.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001353","text":"\"I wonder if I really--really love him,\" she mused.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001354","text":"\"I suppose I do or I shouldn't be continually thinking about him.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001355","text":"But to be married--oh, that's a different thing.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001356","text":"Perhaps he'd want to live in the country.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001357","text":"That would be horribly dull, especially if he had to come to London often.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001358","text":"He hopes to be a great lawyer some day he says.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001359","text":"I don't think I'd like him in a wig and gown and white bands.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001360","text":"He would look so horribly old.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001361","text":"Oh, but I wouldn't let him have his rooms in the Temple after we're married.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001362","text":"He'll have to burn his musty old books.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001363","text":"He's told me so hundreds of times.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001364","text":"A half dozen times would have been nearer the mark and this would probably represent the number of their meetings, once at a ball at Sadler's Wells Gardens and afterwards at stolen opportunities which the ingenious Lavinia contrived to bring about.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:sufism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001365","text":"To tell the honest truth, Lavinia's gallant Archibald Dorrimore, the young Templar, served only to amuse the young lady.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:truth","theme:wisdom","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001366","text":"She was not blind to the fact that he was a fop and not blessed with too much brain.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001367","text":"She had seen many of his sort before and did not trust them.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:relationships","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001368","text":"But Dorrimore struck her as more sincere than the rest.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:truth","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001369","text":"Besides, he was very good looking.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001370","text":"Lavinia couldn't help having admirers.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001371","text":"Nature should not have endowed her with such alluring, innocent looking eyes, with so sweet a mouth.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001372","text":"She had always had some infatuated young man hovering about her even when she was her mother's drudge at the coffee house in Bedfordbury.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001373","text":"Perhaps she inherited flirting from that buxom, good-looking mother who had the reputation of knowing her way quite well where a man was concerned.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001374","text":"\"Archibald Dorrimore will be _Sir_ Archibald some day,\" she mused. \"It would be rare to be called her ladyship. I can hear the footman saying: 'Your coach is waiting, my lady.' Lady Dorrimore--how well it sounds! Archibald loves me....\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001375","text":"May be this conviction settled the matter. The girl slid out of bed and dressed herself hurriedly, though eleven o'clock had only just struck and she had plenty of time. Perhaps she thought that if she hesitated any longer she might alter her mind and not be married after all.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001376","text":"Despite her haste she was not neglectful of herself.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001377","text":"Now and again she glanced at the little mirror over which the girls squabbled daily, smoothed her rebellious hair and settled the Nithsdale hood of her cloak coquettishly.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001378","text":"Then she noiselessly crept from the room, flitted down the staircase and was at the hall door shooting back its heavy bolts--fortunately always kept well greased--and lifting the massive chain which stretched across the centre.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001379","text":"Street doors were well guarded and ground floor windows barred in those days, and not without reason.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001380","text":"The moon was still shining brightly and Lavinia drew her hood closer over her face, though there was little need, for the fields were deserted.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001381","text":"She turned to the east, keeping in the shadow, slight as it was, of the school garden wall.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001382","text":"When the \"Conduit Head\" at the top of Red Lion Street (the northern end now known as Lamb's Conduit Street) was reached she paused and her heart went pit-a-pat.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001383","text":"If Dorrimore should not be there!","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001384","text":"She stopped, overcome by sudden scruples.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:resilience","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001385","text":"In a flash her life at the school, its monotony and discipline, the irksomeness of regular work, rose before her!","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001386","text":"She had been some months at Miss Pinwell's establishment and her restless soul pined for a change.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001387","text":"Though she looked back to her vagabond life in the streets with a shudder, she yearned for its freedom, but without its degradations.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:relationships","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001388","text":"The step she was about to take, so she persuaded herself, meant freedom, but it also meant ingratitude towards Gay and the duchess.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:gratitude","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001389","text":"For the latter's opinion she did not care much.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001390","text":"The imperious manner of her grace was not to her taste.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001391","text":"Gay--that was a different thing.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001392","text":"She looked upon Gay as a father--of her own father she had but a shadowy recollection--though sometimes she thought she detected in him signs of a warmer affection than that which a father usually bestows on a daughter.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001393","text":"She was glad to have his praise.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001394","text":"She laughed when he persisted in calling her Polly--why she knew not--but she was sure she could never endure his making love to her.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:resilience","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001395","text":"In her heart of hearts she was afraid of this.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001396","text":"The dread had much to do with her encouragement of Dorrimore.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:courage","theme:love","theme:resilience","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001397","text":"Of course if she married it would mean an estrangement between her and Gay and his powerful friends, and most likely the end of her ambition to be a great actress.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001398","text":"Her mind had long been torn, and at the eleventh hour when she was on her way to meet her fate in Dorrimore she still hesitated.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001399","text":"If she really loved Dorrimore there would have been no hesitation.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001400","text":"But she had never met any man who did more than flatter her and gratify the pleasure she felt at being admired.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001401","text":"Her decision was in the balance.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001402","text":"The weight of a feather would turn the scale one way or another.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001403","text":"The feather came in the shape of Dorrimore himself.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001404","text":"There he was in three cornered hat and cloak, his powdered wig white in the moonlight, pacing up and down, his hand resting on his sword hilt.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001405","text":"He caught sight of the shrinking figure in the shadow and the hat was doffed in a profound bow.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001406","text":"Undoubtedly a good looking young man, but as undoubtedly a fop of the first water with his ruffles and bosom of Mechlin lace, red heels to his shoes, gold clocks on his silk stockings and the whiff of scent which heralded his coming.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001407","text":"When near enough his arm went round her and he drew back her hood. He kissed her closely, so closely indeed that his ardour almost frightened her, though she knew not why. He withdrew his lips and gazed into her face, his own paling under the violence of his passion.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001408","text":"\"Dearest Lavinia,\" he murmured. \"You are the loveliest creature in the world and I protest I am the luckiest of men. Have you no words of love for me? Why so silent?\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001409","text":"She had not uttered a word. The rise and fall of her bosom showed her agitation.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001410","text":"\"I'm here. I'm here. Isn't that enough?\" she faltered.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001411","text":"\"Faith you're right, sweetheart. Then let us waste no time. My coach is yonder.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001412","text":"He slid her arm within his and drew her forward.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:solitude","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001413","text":"He was not unconscious of a certain reluctance in her movements and a shyness in her manner, but he put both down to maiden modesty.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001414","text":"Her restraint made her all the more enchanting and he quickened his pace.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001415","text":"She was compelled to accommodate her steps to his, but she did so unwillingly.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001416","text":"A sudden distrust whether of him or of herself she could not quite determine--had seized her.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:relationships","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001417","text":"She was repenting her rashness.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001418","text":"She would have run from him back to the school but that he held her too tightly.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001419","text":"Within another minute they had reached the heavy lumbering coach.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:solitude","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001420","text":"The coachman had seen them coming and descended from his box to open the door.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001421","text":"He was a big fellow who held himself erect like a soldier.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001422","text":"His swarthy complexion had a patch of purplish bloom spreading itself over the cheek bones which told of constant tavern lounging.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001423","text":"A pair of hawk's eyes gleamed from under bushy beetling brows; wide loose lips and a truculent, pugnacious lower jaw completed the picture of a ruffian.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001424","text":"Lavinia glanced at him and that glance was enough, it deepened her distrust into repugnance.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:relationships","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001425","text":"But she had no time to protest.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001426","text":"She was hurried into the coach, Dorrimore in fact lifting her inside bodily with unnecessary violence for she was almost thrown into a corner of the back seat.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001427","text":"Dorrimore followed, turned, shut the door and almost immediately the carriage moved.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001428","text":"The coachman must have sprung to his box with the quickness of a harlequin.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001429","text":"The whip cracked and the horses broke into a gallop.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001430","text":"\"IF WE'RE NOT TO BE MARRIED TELL ME\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001431","text":"The rattle of the wheels over the loose, roughly laid cobble stones, and the swaying carriage hung on leathers, forbade talking.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001432","text":"Lavinia heard her companion's voice but she did not know what he was saying.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001433","text":"Not that it mattered for she was in too much of a flutter to heed anything but her own emotions, and these were so confused that they told her little.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001434","text":"Then Dorrimore's arm stole round her waist.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001435","text":"Would they not be soon man and wife?","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001436","text":"The puzzle was that she had no feeling of response.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001437","text":"She would rather that he did not embrace her.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001438","text":"She did not want to be noticed.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001439","text":"Yet she could not find it in her heart to be unkind, so she allowed him to draw her nearer, to let her head droop on his shoulder.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001440","text":"She tried to think it was pleasant to be so loved and she lowered her eyelashes when he kissed her again and again.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001441","text":"Two or three minutes of oblivion.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001442","text":"The coach had raced down Red Lion Street.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001443","text":"It was in Holborn going eastwards and here the din and clatter were heightened by the shouts of drunken roisterers.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001444","text":"The overhanging houses cast deep shadows and the coach was travelling in the gloom.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001445","text":"It was past midnight and the lamps hung at every tenth house were extinguished.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001446","text":"Then Lavinia became conscious that the carriage was going down hill.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001447","text":"It had passed Fetter Lane into which it should have turned and was proceeding towards Holborn Bridge.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001448","text":"Fetter Lane led into Fleet Street and so to the Fleet.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001449","text":"Had the coachman misunderstood his instructions?","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001450","text":"She wrenched herself free and looked out of the window.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001451","text":"Andrew's Church in Holborn Valley.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001452","text":"She turned swiftly and faced Dorrimore.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001453","text":"The coach had crossed the bridge and had commenced the steep ascent of Holborn Hill on the other side.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001454","text":"The horses had slackened their pace.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001455","text":"\"You said we were going to the Fleet, but we're not. Where are you taking me?\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001456","text":"\"Don't trouble about such a trifle, darling little one,\" he cried gaily. \"Aren't you with me? What more do you want? Come, kiss me. Let us forget everything but our two selves.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001457","text":"He would have embraced her but she repulsed him angrily.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001458","text":"\"No. If you've altered your mind--if we're not to be married tell me so, and I'll leave you to yourself,\" she cried agitatedly.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001459","text":"\"Leave me? And d'you think I'll let you go when you're looking handsomer than ever? Faith, what d'you take me for? You dear fluttering little Venus. Why, you're trembling? But hang me, it must be with joy as I am.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001460","text":"Both his arms were round her. She struggled to free herself; pushed his face away and panting, strove to reach the window, but he was strong and prevented her.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001461","text":"\"I'll go no further with you,\" she cried. \"Set me down at once or I'll scream for help.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001462","text":"\"You pretty little fool. Much help you'll get here. Oh, you shall look if you want to, but your wings must be clipped first.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001463","text":"He gripped both her wrists and held them fast.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001464","text":"Her frightened eyes glanced through the window.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001465","text":"She heard a confused thud of hoofs, now and again the deep bellowing of cattle, in the distance dogs barking, drivers yelling.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001466","text":"She could see horned heads moving up and down.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001467","text":"The coach was now moving very slowly.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001468","text":"It was surrounded by a drove of bullocks from the Essex marshes going to Smithfield.","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"rumi-ext-001469","text":"\"You see?\" laughed Dorrimore. \"D'you suppose I would set you down to be tossed and gored by vulgar cattle. Why the sight of your red ribands would send them mad, as it's nearly sent me.\"","author":"Rumi","source":"Divan-i Shams-i Tabriz — Nicholson Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."}]}